<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Stocks Turn Lower; Dow Off 11.37 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices dipped lower in late afternoon as  
investors kept an eye on NATO air strikes in Kosovo while adjusting 
portfolios before the end of the quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	At 3 p.m., the Dow Jones industrial average was down 11.37 at  
9,825.02. The blue-chip index fell 89 points in early trading 
before whittling away most of its losses. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were weaker. The Nasdaq composite was  
down 9.77 at 2,425.03, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was off 
5.04 at 1,284.95. 
</P>
<P>
	The stock market had advanced Thursday partly on relief about  
the military action in Kosovo. But investors were uneasier today. 
Stock prices fell this morning after NATO aircraft and missiles hit 
targets in Yugoslavia, directing much of their fire on Kosovo, 
where fighting continued between Serbs and ethnic Albanians. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors were worrying about what could happen over the  
weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of the people who believed that one or two air strikes in  
Kosovo would solve our problems over there are having second 
thoughts,'' said Alan Ackerman, senior vice president at Fahnestock 
&AMP; Co. ``Now many people are concerned with whether or not we will 
have to commit ground troops.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The end of the quarter next Wednesday was also affecting  
trading, as institutional investors such as mutual funds buffed up 
their portfolios before having to show them to clients. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is still money in the hands of these money managers that  
has to be spent over the next couple of days,'' said Ricky 
Harrington, technical analyst at Interstate/Johnson Lane in 
Charlotte, N.C. ``That's giving the market a lift.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bond prices dropped after rising this morning as investors,  
concerned about the situation in Kosovo, sought the safety of 
Treasurys. The yield on the Treasury's 30-year bond was back up to 
5.58 percent, which is where it closed late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Among technology stocks, IBM was up 2 5/8 at 174, while Compaq and  
Dell Computer also rose. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 7-to-6 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 549.74 million 
shares, down from Thursday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.19 percent,  
Germany's DAX index fell 1.75 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 rose 
0.89, and France's CAC-40 fell 0.7 percent. 




</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
