<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 12:35:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kwan Falls and Drops to Fourth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HELSINKI, Finland (AP) -- Michelle Kwan can do a double axel with  
her eyes closed. But with her eyes open in the World Figure Skating 
Championships, the tearful Kwan fell on the jump Friday and dropped 
to fourth place after the short program. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if her sparkle and skill come back for Saturday's final,  
she can retain her title only if Maria Butyrskaya of Russia 
falters. Butyrskaya took first place in a routine combining 
precision and allure to the seductive wail of ``St. James 
Infirmary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Runner-up Julia Soldatova of Russia and third-place Vanessa  
Gusmeroli of France both said they were surprised to find 
themselves ahead of Kwan. 
</P>
<P>
	``Michelle is still the best skater,'' Gusmeroli said.  
</P>
<P>
	If Kwan regains her top form Saturday, even Butyrskaya would be  
hard-pressed to beat her in the long program. But under a new 
scoring system that was introduced this year, in which the 
qualification round counts for 20 percent, Butyrskaya could win the 
title even if she places second behind Kwan in the free skate. 
</P>
<P>
	Butyrskaya has had a tendency to slip at critical times, such as  
falling twice at the Grand Prix finals. But she also can rise to 
the occasion, as at the Russian nationals where she hit seven 
triples. 
</P>
<P>
	Kwan is more consistent, but has off days. She expressed  
confidence Friday that she could win the free skate, but knows that 
ultimately the title is Butyrskaya's to lose. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't control my own destiny,'' she said, after crying  
backstage. 
</P>
<P>
	Kwan caught a cold en route to Helsinki and said, ``I haven't  
been on all week,'' adding she was still surprised at missing the 
double axel. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can close my eyes and do it. This time, I was wide awake and  
couldn't do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although Kwan had looked increasingly assured during practices,  
she appeared tentative almost from the beginning Friday. Before 
missing the double axel, she had trouble landing the first part of 
a triple lutz-double toe loop combination. 
</P>
<P>
	Her technical marks ranged from 5.1 to 5.4, but were stronger on  
presentation with mostly 5.8s and 5.9s. 
</P>
<P>
	Soldatova and Gusmeroli are solid, appealing skaters, but no  
challenges to a top-form Butyrskaya. Tatiana Malinina of Uzbekistan 
is the only skater other than Kwan considered to have much chance 
of knocking Butyrskaya to third in the free program. 
</P>
<P>
	Malinina, who beat Butyrskya at the Grand Prix finals two weeks  
ago, was short of her best Friday, finishing fifth in a program 
that was wan but free of major errors. 
</P>
<P>
	Kwan's performance was not the only surprise for the Americans.  
Sarah Hughes ended the short program in ninth place, higher than 
expected for a 13-year-old. 
</P>
<P>
	Clearly pleased, Hughes was able to shrug off an anomalous low  
technical mark of 4.4 from the Austrian judge. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guess I have to try harder to impress the Austrian judge,''  
she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
