<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Auburn's Ellis: AP Coach of Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- Cliff Ellis capped an unforgettable  
season for Auburn with the biggest personal triumph of his coaching 
career. 
</P>
<P>
	Ellis, who led the Tigers to a school-record 29 victories and a  
No. 1 seed in the NCAA tournament, was honored Friday as The 
Associated Press coach of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	``This really is a thrill, just to be in a position to get  
something an award like this,'' he said after accepting his trophy 
at the Final Four. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's something I'm going to cherish forever, an honor I accept  
on behalf on the entire Auburn family, the Auburn players and 
everybody else who helped me along the way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ellis received 36 votes for coach of the year, 17 more than  
runner-up Jim O'Brien of Ohio State. He is the first Auburn coach 
to win the award and the second from the SEC in the 1990s, joining 
Eddie Fogler of Vanderbilt in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Before his arrival at the Southeastern Conference school in  
1994, Auburn had one winning season in six years. The Tigers 
haven't had a losing record under Ellis and began this season with 
17 consecutive victories. 
</P>
<P>
	``For this team to come out of nowhere to do what it did is very  
special,'' Ellis said. ``There was no mention of us in the rankings 
before the season and we rose as high as No. 2. It was an amazing 
and incredibly exciting run.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A musician, author and ostrich farmer in addition to being a  
coach, Ellis also enjoyed success at Cumberland College, South 
Alabama and Clemson before taking over Auburn's struggling program. 
He has a career record of 444-271 in 24 seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Auburn won the SEC regular-season title for the first time since  
1960 and, as the top seed in the South Regional, advanced to the 
round of 16 in the NCAA tournament before losing to Ohio State. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tigers finished fourth in the final national rankings.  
</P>
<P>
	``It really was an incredible year,'' Ellis said. ``For that  
team to do what it did -- winning so many games at the beginning of 
the season -- and not folding under the pressure is just a tribute 
every one of the players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With four starters returning next season, the Tigers should be  
strong again. 
</P>
<P>
	``The expectations are going to be higher, but that's what you  
play for,'' he said. ``We're looking to forward to it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
