<DOCNO> APW19990326.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 23:41:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kwan Fights for World Skating Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HELSINKI, Finland (AP) -- Michelle Kwan is trying to duplicate  
her winning performances in the 1996 and 1998 World Figure Skating 
Championships. So far, she's a lot closer to her 1997 form. 
</P>
<P>
	Stuck in fourth place after a mistake Friday in the short  
program, the American star is faced with the possibility of falling 
short even with a victory in today's free program. 
</P>
<P>
	That's exactly what happened in 1997 in Switzerland, with fellow  
American Tara Lipinski skating off with the title that gave her a 
big boost to the Olympic gold medal the following year. 
</P>
<P>
	Now Russia's Maria Butyrskaya has the advantage over Kwan.  
</P>
<P>
	A fall on the relatively simple double axel in the short program  
dropped Kwan to fourth. An error-free routine, combined with her 
qualifying group victory Wednesday, left Butyrskaya in position to 
complete a Russian sweep of the titles. 
</P>
<P>
	``I certainly can win the long, but I don't control my own  
destiny,'' Kwan said. ``It's like I have to rely on others skaters 
now to miss.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Butyrskaya has to finish third or worse for Kwan to win. If the  
Russian is second, she takes the title no matter what Kwan does. 
</P>
<P>
	Kwan caught a cold on her way to Finland and was forced to take  
antibiotics earlier in the week to improve her condition in time 
for three skates within 75 hours. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, I've been crying, so I'm congested again,'' she  
said after her program. 
</P>
<P>
	``I haven't been on all week,'' added Kwan, still surprised at  
missing the double axel. ``I can close my eyes and do it. This 
time, I was wide awake and couldn't do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's Julia Soldatova was second, followed by France's  
Vanessa Gusmeroli. Both are solid skaters, but have little hope of 
catching Butyrskaya. 
</P>
<P>
	``Michelle is still the best skater,'' Gusmeroli said.  
</P>
<P>
	Tatiana Malinina of Uzbekistan is the only skater other than  
Kwan considered to have much chance of knocking Butyrskaya to third 
in the free program. 
</P>
<P>
	Malinina, who beat Butyrskaya in the Grand Prix finals two weeks  
ago, was fifth Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the ice dance, Angelika Krylova and Oleg Ovsiannikov kept  
Russia's title streak alive with a close victory. 
</P>
<P>
	They performed a routine entirely to the rhythm of drums with no  
melody. However their technique and variety of rhythms was enough 
for them to gain a 5-4 decision in a head-to-head match against 
France's Marina Anissina and Gwendal Peizerat. 
</P>
<P>
	Anissina, born in Russia, and Peizerat skated a more  
conventional routine to ``Man in the Iron Mask'' that was 
highlighted by unique lifts, including one where she holds him off 
the ice. 
</P>
<P>
	Canada's Shae-Lynn Bourne and Victor Kraatz finished third.  
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, Russia's Alexei Yagudin won the men's title, and  
compatriots Yelena Berzhnaya and Anton Sikharulidze took the pairs 
championship. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
