<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nuclear Waste Reaches US Waste Dump </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CARLSBAD, N.M. (AP) -- Through cheers, jeers and an attempted  
blockade, a big rig loaded with radioactive waste made a historic 
journey today to the nation's first nuclear waste dump. 
</P>
<P>
	The truck left Los Alamos National Laboratory in northern New  
Mexico and traveled 270 miles south to the Waste Isolation Pilot 
Plant near Carlsbad, a 7.5 hour trip that followed 25 long years of 
studies, protests and lawsuits. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm ecstatic -- this is just the culmination of everything I've  
worked for for 25 years,'' said Wendell Weart, a Sandia National 
Laboratories scientist who was instrumental in creating WIPP. 
</P>
<P>
	The $1.8 billion facility is designed to gather contaminated  
material from military sites spread across the nation into a single 
depository carved out of ancient salt caverns nearly half a mile 
below ground. 
</P>
<P>
	An appellate court in Washington, D.C., and a federal judge in  
Santa Fe on Wednesday rejected last-ditch appeals from 
environmentalists who sought to scuttle the transfer. 
</P>
<P>
	The driver gave a thumbs-up as he left Los Alamos on Thursday  
evening, and a crowd of about 100 people cheered in response. 
</P>
<P>
	But down the road in Santa Fe, a hub of anti-WIPP sentiment,  
dozens of protesters lined the route holding up placards that read 
``Stop Nuke Trucks'' and ``Science or Science Fiction?'' 
</P>
<P>
	William Beems, 42, of Albuquerque, was arrested after he tried  
to block the truck's path by parking his car across the roadway, 
said state Public Safety Secretary Darren White. An advance team of 
officers cleared the way. 
</P>
<P>
	The truck carried about 600 pounds of waste --  
plutonium-contaminated clothing, gloves, booties, filters, 
coveralls, plastic covers and metal cans. The waste was packed in 
boxes loaded in three specially designed stainless steel 
containers, each about 8 feet wide and 10 feet high. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the material was from the lab's manufacture of nuclear  
batteries used in NASA deep space probes, such as the Voyager 
missions. 
</P>
<P>
	Eventually, such shipments will become ``highly routine,'' lab  
spokesman Kevin Roark said. 
</P>
<P>
	``WIPP shipments will go out every week and no one will even  
notice,'' he said. ``There was more fanfare for the first shipment 
because of its historical significance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eventually, about 37,000 shipments will fill WIPP's underground  
storage rooms and become entombed by salt over the next 30 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 06:03:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Bombs Yugoslavia for 2nd Night </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO aircraft and missiles blasted  
targets in Yugoslavia for a second night, directing much of their 
fire on Kosovo, where fighting raged between Serbs and ethnic 
Albanians. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslav forces Thursday continued their offensive on the ground  
in Kosovo against ethnic Albanians. President Slobodan Milosevic 
cut off diplomatic relations with the United States, France, 
Germany and Britain, while Serbian authorities ordered journalists 
from NATO nations out of the country. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.N. refugee agency said today it feared Serb reprisals  
against Kosovo's ethnic Albanian majority now that foreign 
observers and relief workers have left. 
</P>
<P>
	``With only a handful of independent observers left on the  
ground, we are extremely worried about the plight of Kosovo's 
civilian population, which has already been through a terrible 
ordeal,'' U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees Sadako Ogata said in 
Geneva. 
</P>
<P>
	Western officials insisted today the barrage won't stop until  
Milosevic agrees to a peace deal in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will end when we have limited (Milosevic's) ability to  
terrorize his people, to ethnically cleanse Kosovo,'' British 
Defense Secretary George Robertson told BBC Television. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no hint from Milosevic that he would back down over  
Kosovo, the southern province of Serbia. 
</P>
<P>
	State-run television in Serbia, the main Yugoslav republic,  
quoted a government official saying the second night of NATO 
attacks caused civilian casualties and targeted schools and 
telecommunications networks. 
</P>
<P>
	The NATO strikes Thursday hit inside Kosovo around its  
provincial capital, Pristina, the northern town of Kosovska 
Mitrovica and the southwestern town of Prizren, media in Yugoslavia 
said. Serbian TV said three missiles hit a police station on a 
military base, injuring one policeman and leaving two others 
missing. 
</P>
<P>
	A Belgrade city official said there was ``heavy activity'' by  
warplanes attacking targets outside the Yugoslav capital, Belgrade. 
The official Tanjug news agency reported that an airport in the 
central Serbian city of Nis had been hit and was in flames. 
</P>
<P>
	Local television broadcast appeals for blood donors after 10  
explosions rattled Kraljevo, 75 miles south of Belgrade, the 
independent Beta news agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Montenegro, Yugoslavia's other republic, there were reports  
of explosions at army compounds and barracks, as well as at an 
airport and radar facilities in various towns. 
</P>
<P>
	A NATO missile hit Djakovica, near the Kosovo-Albanian border,  
missing an army compound, Tanjug reported. ``The material damage is 
substantial, and there are casualties,'' it said. 
</P>
<P>
	Western officials said all NATO aircraft returned to base safely  
after their attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was evidence of anti-aircraft units firing on allied  
fliers, but there were no reports at this stage that Yugoslav 
fighters had been launched to intercept them,'' Group Capt. Ian 
Travers Smith said after eight British jets returned to base in 
Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	Pleurat Sejeu, spokesman for the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army in  
London, said in an interview with BBC World television that 
Yugoslav MiGs were being used against ethnic Albanians, who make up 
90 percent of Kosovo's population. 
</P>
<P>
	Sejeu said Serbs had rounded up thousands of displaced ethnic  
Albanian civilians in the central Drenica region and were marching 
them toward Pristina. ``Nobody knows what will happen'' to them, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	A KLA commander, Ramush Hajredinaj, told The Associated Press by  
telephone Thursday that refugees were trapped in Drenica. He didn't 
give any numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 200 Kosovo Albanians crossed into Albania Thursday, saying  
Serb security forces had swept into their village of Goden, 
detaining men, setting the village on fire, and marching women and 
children across the border. 
</P>
<P>
	Selim Ferraj, 37, one of the few males with the group from  
Goden, said he feared the other men were dead. ``I am only alive 
because I knew the Serb commander before,'' said Ferraj, who 
escaped with his wife and five children. 
</P>
<P>
	UNHCR estimates that more than 450,000 people have been forced  
from their homes since fighting began in Kosovo more than one year 
ago. Some 260,000 people remain displaced within Kosovo, it said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Romania, Foreign Minister Andrei Plesu said today the country  
is prepared to take in refugees from neighboring Yugoslavia if 
needed. 
</P>
<P>
	Tanjug reported that ethnic Albanian rebels had attacked Serb  
police in Djakovica, wounding one. 
</P>
<P>
	In Skopje, the capital of Macedonia, supporters of the Serbs  
took to the streets with rocks and gasoline bombs to attack 
embassies of the United States, Britain and other NATO countries. 
Police used tear gas to disperse the demonstrators. 
</P>
<P>
	Vojislav Seselj, an ultranationalist Serbian deputy premier,  
urged Serbs to attack American interests all over the world, the 
independent Beta news agency reported, according to Studio 99 
television in Belgrade. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslavia's deputy premier, Vuk Draskovic, gave a series of  
television interviews Thursday calling on NATO to stop the bombing, 
although he did not say his country was prepared to accept the 
Kosovo agreement negotiated in France. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, he proposed reopening negotiations on the agreement.  
And he said Yugoslavia would call off its offensive in Kosovo only 
after ethnic Albanians and NATO ceased fire. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, signed by the ethnic Albanians in Paris, gives the  
province broad autonomy and provides for a NATO force to enforce 
the it. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Paris agreement is destroyed now by the bombs,'' Draskovic  
told Britain's Channel 4 News. ``Is that democracy? You are bombing 
us to accept something we don't like to accept, to accept ... the 
dissolution of our state, promoting Kosovo as an independent 
state.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
