<DOCNO> APW19990326.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 22:52:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tyson Records Become Issue Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- Nevada boxing commissioners are trying to keep  
the personal lives of boxers private. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission argued Friday for a new law that would keep  
almost all information about fighters and promoters given it 
confidential. The commission is concerned that Nevada could lose 
its place as the host of most major fights. 
</P>
<P>
	A press representative, however, called the bill a ``knee-jerk  
reaction'' to the release of Mike Tyson's psychological records and 
said the public that buys tickets or makes bets on fights has a 
right to know about a boxer's mental and physical state. 
</P>
<P>
	``Can anyone say with certainty that the public dissemination of  
Mike Tyson's psychological reports caused any substantial harm to 
Mike Tyson?'' asked Kent Lauer, director of the Nevada State Press 
Association. ``I don't think so. In fact, I think the public 
confidence in the commission's decision on Tyson's license was 
bolstered by the release of those reports.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The action in Nevada came on the same day a Maryland judge  
praised the ``remarkable'' progress made by the former heavyweight 
champion, but rejected his request for a reduced sentence. Tyson 
must still serve 60 days in Maryland for violating probation for a 
1992 rape conviction in Indiana. 
</P>
<P>
	In the end, a Nevada Assembly committee decided to delete  
sweeping language keeping most records confidential. But it 
authorized an amendment to keep medical information not relevant to 
an application to box confidential. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee also approved legislation allowing the commission  
to grant a boxing license with restrictions. That also became an 
issue with Tyson when the commission wanted to grant him a license 
to box again -- with certain conditions -- but couldn't add the 
conditions because Nevada law didn't allow it. 
</P>
<P>
	Three of the five Nevada athletic commissioners appeared before  
the committee in Carson City to argue that records given the 
commission should not be made public without a court order. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to psychological records, the bill supported by the  
commissioners would have restricted access to medical and criminal 
records. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is in no way an effort to keep information from the  
public,'' commissioner Lorenzo Fertitta said. ``I believe it is 
good public policy to have this information open to the public. But 
there are certain circumstances where it affects our ability to 
regulate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other than the release of Tyson's psychological records prior to  
his relicensing hearing in October, commissioners cited no other 
case in which there was a problem over the release of a boxer's 
information. 
</P>
<P>
	But commissioner Glenn Carano said that by assuring boxers that  
any information given the commission when it is licensing a fighter 
be kept private it will help the state get more big fights. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are the boxing capital of the world. The Nevada Athletic  
Commission is very highly regarded,'' Carano said. ``It is, 
however, a very competitive industry. We need the confidence of 
everybody we do business with -- that includes the boxers and 
promoters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lauer, however, said that the present system has been in place  
for years and that Nevada has had no problems before. 
</P>
<P>
	``This information has been open for a long time now, and I  
didn't hear the athletic commission testify to any abuses of this 
open information,'' Lauer said. ``All of a sudden because of this 
Mike Tyson episode they want to make everything confidential.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson was ordered last September to undergo five days of  
psychological testing by a team of doctors at Massachusetts General 
Hospital before boxing regulators would agree to hear his request 
for a license to replace the one taken from him for biting Evander 
Holyfield's ears. 
</P>
<P>
	He went to court to try and keep the records closed, but a judge  
ruled that Nevada law made them public documents and they were 
released. 
</P>
<P>
	``How can you say that embarrassed Mike Tyson?'' Lauer asked.  
``It didn't. Mike Tyson does a good enough job of embarrassing 
himself in other ways.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 14:55:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Questioned on IOC Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Two congressional leaders asked President  
Clinton on Friday why he hasn't extended federal anti-bribery laws 
to the International Olympic Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Reps. Tom Bliley, chairman of the House Commerce Committee, and  
Michael Oxley, head of its finance subcommittee, noted that the 
White House was asked almost a month ago by the U.S. Olympic 
Committee to include the IOC under the Foreign Corrupt Practices 
Act. 
</P>
<P>
	That request came as an independent USOC investigation, headed  
by former Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, concluded that 
the IOC fostered a ``culture of improper gift-giving'' that led to 
a multimillion-dollar vote-buying scheme in Salt Lake's successful 
quest for the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	``The recent events regarding the ethical lapses concerning the  
IOC raise serious questions that must be addressed promptly,'' 
Bliley, R-Va., and Oxley, R-Ohio, wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	At the White House, spokesman Barry Toiv said Clinton ``is still  
reviewing the Mitchell recommendations.'' He declined to elaborate. 
</P>
<P>
	Saying they were ``shocked and discouraged'' by the revelations  
of cash, scholarships, medical treatment and other inducements for 
IOC members from Salt Lake bidders, the lawmakers asked the 
president what steps he had taken to make such actions illegal and 
make sure other nations did likewise. 
</P>
<P>
	They gave Clinton until April 13 to either add the IOC to the  
organizations covered by federal international business bribery 
laws or tell them why he had failed to act. 
</P>
<P>
	They also asked him to list what countries the White House had  
contacted to try to have them adopt similar codes ``so as to make 
bribery of an IOC official illegal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bliley and Oxley were primary House architects of the foreign  
bribery laws last year and said Clinton could cover the IOC through 
a stroke of a pen on an executive order. 
</P>
<P>
	``Fairness, clear rules and objectivity are critical in the  
sporting world,'' their letter said. ``The Olympic spirit reflects 
the highest ideals in this respect, or at least it should. 
</P>
<P>
	``Athletes spend years of hard work in training in order to  
pursue the Olympic dream. Their tireless dedication to excellence 
should not be sullied by corruption, or by acquiescence to 
corruption.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The letter from the House members was the latest step by federal  
agencies into the Olympic bribery case, the worst scandal in the 
history of the world's biggest sports event. 
</P>
<P>
	The Justice Department and the FBI are investigating possible  
violations of federal fraud and tax laws, and the Senate Commerce 
Committee has scheduled hearings on the scandal for April 14. 
</P>
<P>
	Pending Senate legislation also would strip the IOC's tax-exempt  
status in the United States, limit the amount of Olympic fees 
sponsors could deduct and place U.S. TV rights fees -- the single 
biggest source of Olympic income -- with the USOC instead of the 
IOC. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC expelled six members last week for accepting bribes and  
started the action on what it described as a series of long-range 
reforms, including a task force to restructure the committee and 
membership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
