<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Up Before Report / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices moved higher  
early today on the Chicago Board of Trade as investors began to 
square positions ahead of a key government report next week. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Agriculture Department early Wednesday is expected to  
reveal farmer planting intentions for the spring crop, including 
the first concrete estimate of whether producers intend to plant 
more soybeans over corn and wheat. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat also found continued support from rumors that the Clinton  
administration is considering a one-time exemption on export bans 
to Iran and other countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery rose 1 3/4 cents to $2.94 1/2 a bushel; May  
corn rose 1 1/4 cents to $2.30 a bushel; May oats rose 1/4 cent to 
$1.20 1/4 a bushel; May soybeans rose 3/4 cent to $4.99 3/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Live cattle and pork futures were mixed on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange, while feeder cattle advanced. 
</P>
<P>
	April live cattle fell .05 cent to 65.90 cents a pound; April  
feeder cattle rose .25 cent to 71.30 cents a pound; April lean hogs 
fell .35 cent to 43.75 cents a pound; May pork bellies fell 2.10 
cents to 54.20 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
