<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 23:41:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Guerrero Riding Infiniti in Phoenix </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- As if to underline what a good fit he's found at  
Cobb Racing, Roberto Guerrero even likes that his team equipped its 
cars with Infiniti engines. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-four of 28 cars entered in the MCI WorldCom 200 on Sunday  
are powered by Oldsmobile Auroras. But Guerrero believes the 
Infinitis are catching up in quality, if not in reputation, and he 
supports the idea of diversity. 
</P>
<P>
	``For the good of the series, it's important to have more than  
just one engine,'' Guerrero said Friday at practice for the Indy 
Racing League event. ``The other thing that's exciting is that it 
would be very nice for me to win the first race with an Infiniti.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He already is the first to lead a race with the stepchild power  
plant that team owner Price Cobb believes is good enough to become 
dominant. 
</P>
<P>
	Guerrero finished fourth last August at Texas Motor Speedway  
after leading the first 22 laps ever by an Infiniti-powered car. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nissan used to trounce us all the time,'' said Cobb, who won  
the World Porsche Cup while driving in IMSA's Camel GTP series. ``I 
know where they've been and I know where they're going. I know if I 
latch onto their start, it'll make Cobb Racing look that much 
better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cobb says the crew let Guerrero down in Dallas and again on Jan.  
24 in this season's first race, when Guerrero finished 13th after 
running 88 laps with a piece of another car's bodywork caught 
underneath the chassis. 
</P>
<P>
	``Roberto had come from 18th to lead the race and did it  
effortlessly,'' Cobb said. ``I mean, there really was no discussion 
about who was the fastest car on the track. We didn't finish well 
there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Robbie Buhl is the only other driver at Phoenix with an  
Infiniti-equipped G Force. Rookies Jaques Lazier and Scott 
Harrington have Infinitis in their Dallara chassis. 
</P>
<P>
	Harrington Motorsports chief mechanic Steve Dunlap said Nissan  
improved its backup support while taking the bugs out of the 
powerplant. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had good luck with our private tests and mileaged the  
engine out without any difficulty, and when we got down to the 
block it was in great shape,'' Dunlap said. 
</P>
<P>
	Horsepower and durability aside, Guerrero has reason to feel  
confident in Phoenix, where he won the fastest race in the history 
of the irregular, one-mile oval 12 years ago -- averaging 138.020 
mph over 200 miles in a turbocharged CART machine. 
</P>
<P>
	``We started last,'' he recalled. ``We were 2 1/2 pounds  
underweight after qualifying, so they made us start at the back of 
the pack. We had a few things go wrong throughout the race and 
still went ahead and got my first Indy car win, so that was a very 
special day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Later in 1987, Guerrero was second in the Indianapolis 500, and  
the next year qualified for his only Indy 500 pole while setting a 
track record of 232.482 mph. But that Memorial Day weekend came to 
an inglorious end when he spun into the wall during the second 
parade lap. 
</P>
<P>
	He also crashed at the Indy 500 in 1993 and 1994.  
</P>
<P>
	Guerrero entered the Pep Boys IRL with Pagan Racing in 1996, a  
team he left midway through last season. He missed three races 
before catching a ride with Cobb. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 17:12:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sprague Wins Chevy Trucks 150 Pole </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Jack Sprague, who has won more NASCAR Craftsman  
Truck Series races at Phoenix International Raceway than any other 
driver, delivered a record qualifying lap Friday to win the pole 
for the Chevy Trucks 150. 
</P>
<P>
	Last in line to qualify, Sprague exhibited no jitters whatsoever  
in bumping Rick Crawford's Ford from the pole position. The 1997 
series champion drove a Chevrolet Silverado around the one-mile 
oval at 128.402 mph to reclaim the speed standard he lost to Mike 
Bliss in October 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Crawford, the only other driver to better Bliss' old mark of  
127.741, put a Ford F-150 in the No. 2 starting position. His speed 
was 128.105. 
</P>
<P>
	Bliss, who won October's series race here from the No. 1  
starting position, failed to challenge for the top spot. He 
qualified 10th, also in a Ford, at 126.796. 
</P>
<P>
	Kevin Harvick will start third in Saturday's race after posting  
a speed of 127.768. He'll share the second row with Greg Biffle, 
who delivered a lap of 127.669. Both drive Fords. 
</P>
<P>
	Two-time series champion Ron Hornaday was fifth in Chevrolet at  
127.438. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirty-five trucks will start Saturday's 150-mile race.  
</P>
<P>
	Friday's pole run was Sprague's fourth in Phoenix and 13th in  
the series, two shy of Mike Skinner's record. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of Sprague's three previous Phoenix victories also came from  
the No. 1 starting slot, including his last in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 12:36:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Brand, Ellis Win AP Awards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- Duke sophomore center Elton Brand  
and Auburn's Cliff Ellis were honored today by The Associated Press 
as college basketball's player and coach of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Brand, the only unanimous All-America selection this season,  
enters the Final Four averaging 17.8 points and 9.6 rebounds for 
the top-ranked Blue Devils, who have won a school-record 31 
consecutive games. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-8 Brand has had 17 double-doubles this season, nine  
in the last 15 games and two in the Atlantic Coast Conference 
tournament. Brand is shooting 62 percent from the field and he has 
83 blocked shots. 
</P>
<P>
	Brand received 28 votes from AP member newspapers and radio  
stations, while senior guard Andre Miller of Utah was runner-up 
with 17. 
</P>
<P>
	Brand is the third Duke player to win the Adolph Rupp Trophy,  
following Art Heyman in 1963 and Christian Laettner in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Ellis led Auburn to one the best seasons in school history as  
the Tigers finished 29-4, a school record for victories, and 
reached their highest ranking ever, No. 2. Auburn, which finished 
as the Southeastern Conference's regular-season champion, was 
fourth in the final rankings and earned a No. 1 seeding in the NCAA 
tournament, losing to Ohio State in the regional semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
	Ellis, who has been at Auburn since 1994, has compiled a 444-271  
record in 24 seasons as a head coach. 
</P>
<P>
	He received 36 votes for coach of the year, 17 more than  
runner-up Jim O'Brien of Ohio State. Ellis is the first Auburn 
coach to win the award and the second from the SEC in the 1990s, 
joining Eddie Fogler of Vanderbilt in 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
