<DOCNO> APW19990326.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 21:41:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Women's NCAA Final Four Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Last fall, Duke came to San Jose, too.  
Only the Duke that played then and the Duke that will play for the 
national championship are different teams. 
</P>
<P>
	Duke opened its season 1-3, including a 104-74 season-opening  
loss to Connecticut in the Four in the Fall tournament at the San 
Jose Arena last November. 
</P>
<P>
	Duke followed the loss with a 77-57 victory over Stanford, but  
then lost consecutive games to Virginia Tech and Notre Dame. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, all of that was forgotten as the Blue Devils defeated  
Georgia 81-69 in the semifinals back at the San Jose Arena. 
</P>
<P>
	``We started 1-3, but the way we played in the ACC, we went 15-1  
and we beat UCLA. I think we just really believed that we were 
going to the Final Four,'' senior guard Hilary Howard said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We knew that it was going to come together, but it was  
frustrating at the beginning of the season,'' she added. ``We lost 
by 30 points right off the bat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fellow guard Nicole Erickson admitted that the team was terrible  
in its first visit to San Jose. The difference? 
</P>
<P>
	``We're healthy right now, and we're in shape,'' she said.  
``Four of our five starters didn't even play in the preseason.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Center Michele VanGorp said it was more a matter of chemistry.  
</P>
<P>
	``I knew it was going to be a certain time before everybody  
started to feel comfortable with eachother and in a groove,'' she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *UKARI'S GAME:* There was one thing that all the Purdue players  
could agree upon after Friday's 77-63 victory over Louisiana Tech: 
It was all about Ukari Figgs. 
</P>
<P>
	Figgs, a senior guard, had 24 points and 10 rebounds to advance  
the Boilermakers to the title game against Duke on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ukari doesn't get a lot of the respect that she deserves,''  
guard-forward Katie Douglas said. ``She really deserves it 
tonight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Forward Michelle Duhart also heaped on the praise.  
</P>
<P>
	``Ukari, she's incredible,'' Duhart said. ``I didn't know just  
how well she was doing until somebody told me she had 18 points at 
the half.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Lady Techsters had no answer for Figgs, admitted coach Leon  
Barmore. He credited her with making the difference for Purdue in a 
tight second half. 
</P>
<P>
	``She made a couple unbelievable shots,'' he said. ``It wasn't  
the person guarding her's fault on a couple of those shots. She 
just knocked them down.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *DOUBLE THREAT:* Georgia twin guards Kelly Miller and Coco  
Miller usually mean double trouble for their opponents. Duke 
figured out that it wasn't a matter of control so much as 
containment. 
</P>
<P>
	Coco scored 18 points and had eight rebounds, while Kelly had 13  
points and six rebounds. But it wasn't enough, as the Blue Devils 
beat the Lady Bulldogs 81-69 to advance to the national 
championship game Sunday against Purdue. 
</P>
<P>
	Duke guard Hilary Howard knew it was going to take some effort,  
especially in light of Kelly's 33-performance against Iowa State in 
the Mideast Regional final. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we just wanted them not to go off,'' Howard said. ``We  
knew we couldn't stop them, but we wanted to contain them 
nonetheless.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The good news for Georgia is that Coco and Kelly are sophomores,  
which means they still have a couple more years to confound 
opponents. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you have people like that on your basketball team, the  
bar is set, the pace is set,'' coach Andy Landers said. ``In that 
way, they lead us.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *CHAMIQUE'S DONE:* Chamique Holdsclaw's college career is  
officially over. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tennessee star was invited to play in the Women's Basketball  
Coaches Association all-star game on Saturday but declined. She was 
available to play because Tennessee was eliminated from the NCAA 
tournament in the regional finals by Duke. 
</P>
<P>
	``I talked to my coaches and there wasn't a real need for me to  
play,'' Holdsclaw said. ``I kind of always said when I ended my 
career, I wanted to end it wearing a Tennessee uniform.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Holdsclaw is seeing the Final Four from a different perspective  
this year because she led Tennessee to the national championship in 
each of her first three seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	While she'd rather be playing, Holdsclaw is finding the  
experience to be interesting while collecting various player of the 
year and All-America awards. 
</P>
<P>
	``Here this weekend I have kind of a sad feeling, but I'm just  
blessed to be here, to be able to have a great career, to be here 
with friends and family,'' Holdsclaw said. 
</P>
<P>
	``And this is a time I really never had a chance to enjoy -- just  
to sit back and watch and just enjoy the event.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *CREDENTIALS COUNT:* Maybe it was the absence of Tennessee and  
Connecticut, maybe it was the cross-country journey from the East 
Coast. For whatever reason, the number of media credentials issued 
for the Final Four was the lowest in three years. 
</P>
<P>
	The NCAA said it issued 744 credentials to the news media. The  
record was 780 in Kansas City last year, when Tennessee won its 
third consecutive national championship, and there were 754 issued 
for the 1997 Final Four in Cincinnati. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the media contingent this year is much larger than it was  
in the late 1980s. For 1988 Final Four in Tacoma, 271 media 
credentials were issued. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 15:25:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. House Faults U.N. Oil Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Troubled by the depressed condition of the  
domestic oil and natural gas industry, oil-state lawmakers 
criticized a U.N. humanitarian program that permits Iraq to add 
millions of barrels of oil to an already oversupplied market. 
</P>
<P>
	At a hearing Friday of the House Commerce energy and power  
subcommittee, lawmakers assailed a U.N. policy that allows Iraq to 
sell oil for food and medicine, saying it may be harming American 
producers while not meeting the United States' stated aim of 
removing Iraqi President Saddam Hussein from power. 
</P>
<P>
	``I for one am suspicious of this program,'' said Rep. Ralph  
Hall of Texas, top Democrat on the subcommittee. ``It appears to be 
born out of an appropriate humane consideration, but may be 
disruptive of worldwide crude oil markets and could spawn a lot of 
abuse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But a State Department official, who came in for sharp  
questioning, defended the policy, saying elimination of the 
oil-for-food program would lead to erosion of support within the 
worldwide community for continued sanctions against Iraq. 
</P>
<P>
	``The sanctions deprive Saddam of the revenue he would otherwise  
use to reconstitute his weapons of mass destruction,'' said Bill 
Wood, principal deputy assistant secretary of state. ``It is 
essential that we address the humanitarian needs of the Iraqi 
people. Doing so is right in itself but also crucial to maintaining 
Security Council, regional and other international support for the 
sanctions while we continue our efforts to change the Iraqi 
regime.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Economic sanctions were imposed by the U.N. Security Council in  
1990 to punish Iraq for invading Kuwait. To ease the sanctions' 
devastating effect on the Iraqi people, the United Nations launched 
the oil-for-food program in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	France has called for an end to the oil embargo, prompting the  
administration to counter with a proposal in January that would 
expand the oil-for-food program, which comes up for Security 
Council review in May. Congress has no direct say in whether it 
continues, but some lawmakers are pressuring the administration to 
seek changes or an end to the policy. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the program, Iraq is allowed to sell up to $10.4 billion  
in oil annually, with the proceeds directed by the United Nations 
for purchases of food, medicine and infrastructure. Iraq, which is 
producing about 2.5 million barrels per day, has not neared the 
$10.4 billion ceiling. 
</P>
<P>
	Administration officials contend that the Iraqi production has a  
negligible impact on U.S. oil prices, which have been in a serious 
slump for well over a year. Yet congressional Republicans note that 
when OPEC recently proposed cutting production by an amount similar 
to Iraq's output, worldwide crude prices rose by nearly $2 a 
barrel. 
</P>
<P>
	The domestic energy industry has shrunk by some 50,000 jobs in  
the past year or so and producers have closed more than 136,000 
marginal oil wells that individually produce less than 15 barrels 
daily but collectively account for one-fifth of domestic 
production. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel's chairman, Rep. Joe Barton of Texas, said he has  
concluded that ``our Iraqi policy is designed to maximize Iraqi 
production at the expense of the marginal producer in the United 
States.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
