<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McDougal Forgets Whitewater Deals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Under questioning by prosecutors, Susan  
McDougal is claiming ignorance or memory lapse about the land deals 
that are central to Kenneth Starr's Whitewater investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Repeatedly stating ``I don't recall'' and ``I don't remember,''  
Mrs. McDougal testified in her criminal trial that she had 
forgotten what little she knew in the 1980s about the Whitewater 
real estate dealings involving her husband, James McDougal, 
President Clinton and his wife, and others. 
</P>
<P>
	Her trial recessed Thursday afternoon for the weekend when the  
prosecution had technical difficulties with a video machine while 
showing the jury a tape of an ABC television interview of Mrs. 
McDougal years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The defense may call two more witnesses next week before  
resting. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal was indicted on two counts of criminal contempt  
and a count of obstruction of justice for refusing to answer 
federal grand jury questions in the Whitewater probe. 
</P>
<P>
	Before running into technical problems, prosecutors were able to  
show a few minutes of the interview. In one outtake, Mrs. McDougal, 
who had been convicted and sentenced in the Whitewater 
investigation before the interview, was asked what the one thing 
she wanted to say after four years of silence in the investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	In a joking manner, she said ``that I hate'' the prosecutors  
``and that I want them dead and their children dead.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal has maintained she did not trust Starr and refused  
to answer the grand jury questions because she feared the 
independent counsel would twist her words to implicate the Clintons 
or charge her with perjury if she did not say what he wanted. 
</P>
<P>
	During two days of questioning by prosecutor Mark Barrett, Mrs.  
McDougal said more than 40 times that she did not recall various 
business deals. She said her former husband, who died in federal 
prison last year, handled most of the financial matters. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wasn't someone who studied business ... but generally I  
agreed with Jim,'' she told the jury. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal was confronted with information she provided to  
accountants in 1986 about McDougal's failed savings and loan. She 
maintained that she knew little about the financial deals. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was talking to Jim'' and passing along what he said to the  
accountants, she explained. 
</P>
<P>
	Her ex-husband had suffered a stroke after federal regulators  
removed him from the S&AMP;L, Madison Guaranty. Accountants were trying 
to track the losses to the institution caused by the McDougals' 
numerous real estate projects. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal also testified that she didn't remember dealing  
personally with former Arkansas Gov. Jim Guy Tucker on a proposed 
shopping center, even though the accountants' written summary of 
her 1986 interview said she dealt with Tucker on the project, which 
was never built. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed shopping center was an important part of the 1996  
fraud case against the McDougals and Tucker, each of whom was 
convicted of felonies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
