<DOCNO> APW19990326.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 13:35:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Thurmond Seeks Crash Restitution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Monica Cindrich's fury grew as she learned  
that legislation was sliding through Congress to pay $40 million to 
the families of those who died when a Marine jet sent an Italian 
gondola plunging to the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven of the 20 gondola victims were German - but Germany has  
not yet compensated Cindrich for the death of her husband, Greg, in 
an in-flight collision of military jets two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Her grief and anger inflamed, Cindrich, 28, this week unpacked  
the only thing she has left of her husband from that tragic 
accident -- the tattered flight suit she keeps in Greg's study. 
</P>
<P>
	``I took it out and looked at it and thought, 'Who is going to  
help us?''' Cindrich said in a telephone interview from her home in 
North Charleston, S.C. ``It's a slap in my face if reparations are 
going to be made to the Germans before they are made for my 
husband's death.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cindrich's complaint caught the ear of her senator, Republican  
Strom Thurmond, who informed his Senate colleagues this week that 
he will offer legislation that would make the American payment to 
the seven German families contingent on Germany's payment to 
Cindrich. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a simple matter of fairness,'' said Thurmond, the  
former Senate Armed Services Committee chairman. ``If the United 
States Senate does not look out for the interests of American 
servicemen and women, who will?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Air Force Capt. Greg Cindrich, 28, and eight other Americans  
were killed Sept. 13, 1997, when their C-141 transport was hit 
head-on by a German air force jet 60 miles off the coast of 
Namibia. Several investigations determined the German plane had 
been flying at the wrong altitude. 
</P>
<P>
	The families of the nine Americans have filed legal claims with  
the German government, but they have received no compensation. 
</P>
<P>
	Cindrich is also waging a fight for better collision-warning  
systems on Air Force jets, but it was the $40 million amendment, 
sponsored by Sen. Charles Robb, D-Va., and tucked into a $2.5 
billion spending bill, that especially roused her. 
</P>
<P>
	After she called Thurmond's office to complain, the 96-year-old  
senator approached Robb with legislative language that would make 
the American payment contingent on the German payment to Cindrich 
and the eight other families of the 1997 crash, Thurmond aides say. 
</P>
<P>
	Robb refused to change his measure.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're looking forward to working with Sen. Thurmond's office  
on bringing some closure, comfort and relief to the families of 
both of these terrible accidents,'' Robb spokesman John DiBiase 
said Friday. ``The problem with Sen. Thurmond's legislation is that 
it sets two groups of victims against each other and we want to 
find a solution that helps both groups.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Thurmond urged Senate Appropriations Committee  
Chairman Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, to scuttle Robb's amendment in 
negotiations with the House. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just as the United States government has a responsibility to  
compensate the families of the victims of those who died in Italy, 
the German government has an identical obligation to those American 
families who lost loved ones because of negligence and fault of the 
German Air Force,'' he wrote to Stevens on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	A diplomatic source familiar with the situation said the German  
government asked the families of the 1997 crash victims in November 
to specify the amount they are seeking, and the Germans are still 
trying to get details. The official spoke on condition of 
anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	A lawyer for the German gondola victims' families, John Arthur  
Eaves Jr., said they are sympathetic to Cindrich and willing to 
intervene with German officials on her behalf. 
</P>
<P>
	But he criticized the Thurmond approach as unfair, saying the  
cases aren't comparable because the gondola victims were civilians 
while the 1997 victims were military. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really wouldn't think that one victim would be vindictive  
enough to want to keep other people from finding a resolution in 
their lives just because she hasn't found a resolution,'' Eaves 
said Friday from his Jackson, Miss., office. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Devine, the Washington-based lawyer representing Cindrich  
and the families of four other 1997 crash victims, said his clients 
feel restitution should be paid in both cases. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mrs. Cindrich and the other claimants aren't being vindictive  
at all,'' Devine said. ``All they're saying is they lost their 
loved ones six months before the gondola victims perished, and they 
think it's only fair that they be compensated by the German 
government before our government rushes to compensate them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Thurmond, Cindrich has powerful help. An aide said he likely  
will introduce independent legislation to hold up the payment to 
the gondola victims' families if Robb's amendment survives. 
</P>
<P>
	Cindrich, left the single mother of the couple's 4-year-old  
child, Christopher, said the scuffle with Congress and seeing the 
flight suit again has her revisiting her first nightmarish days of 
widowhood. 
</P>
<P>
	``It brings me back to the first three weeks, when all I could  
think of was, `Will they bring his body back?''' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
