<DOCNO> APW19990326.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 02:11:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NY Cops Charged in Diallo Shooting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Four white police officers who shot and killed  
an unarmed black immigrant have been charged with second-degree 
murder in a case that has led to days of protests and hundreds of 
arrests. 
</P>
<P>
	The charges in a sealed grand jury indictment were confirmed  
Thursday by a source close to the case who spoke on condition of 
anonymity. Spokespersons for police and prosecutors declined 
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Amadou Diallo, a 22-year-old street vendor from Guinea, was  
killed Feb. 4 outside his Bronx home, struck by 19 of the 41 
bullets fired at him. Police said officers Sean Carroll, Kenneth 
Boss, Edward McMellon and Richard Murphy were searching for a rape 
suspect. 
</P>
<P>
	Some officers also face lesser charges, the source said. They  
were assigned paid desk duty during the investigation and have not 
commented publicly. Lawyers said they declined to testify before 
the grand jury. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorney Stephen Worth has said the policemen fired  
because they thought Diallo was reaching for a gun. Marvyn 
Kornberg, a lawyer for Carroll, said he had not been notified of 
the indictment but was not surprised. 
</P>
<P>
	``As sure as I was that he was going to be indicted, that's how  
sure I am that he's going to be acquitted,'' Kornberg said. 
</P>
<P>
	The shooting has strained relations between the minority  
community and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who has been criticized as 
not being sensitive to community concerns. It has also led to 
growing protests, including 13 consecutive days of demonstrations 
outside police headquarters. 
</P>
<P>
	The more than 800 people arrested for disorderly conduct have  
included politicians, Jewish leaders, groups of seniors and youths 
and notables like National Association for the Advancement of 
Colored People President Kweisi Mfume. Oscar-winning actress Susan 
Sarandon was arrested Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rev. Al Sharpton said the demonstrations will go on, despite  
the indictments. The Rev. Jesse Jackson was expected at today's 
rally. 
</P>
<P>
	``The impact of those demonstrations has mobilized this city in  
a most healthy way,'' Jackson said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The people cannot rest until the trial is over,'' he added.  
``Reverend Sharpton, the ministers, the rabbis and others are going 
to escalate their protests, which I fully support, until the 
madness ends.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The shooting is also under investigation by the Justice  
Department's civil rights division. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York, second-degree murder is used in most homicide cases  
and implies a degree of intent to commit a felony. It carries a 
maximum prison sentence of 25 years to life. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 09:15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jurors Excused in Gay Slaying Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LARAMIE, Wyo. (AP) -- Two men who opposed the death penalty were  
dismissed as potential jurors in the first-degree murder trial of a 
man charged in the beating death of a gay college student. 
</P>
<P>
	Fourteen potential jurors were released Thursday from the trial  
of Russell Henderson, who faces the death penalty if convicted in 
the Oct. 6 attack on Matthew Shepard. More candidates were 
questioned today. 
</P>
<P>
	Opening statements are expected to begin April 6.  
</P>
<P>
	Henderson and Aaron McKinney, both 21, are accused of luring  
Shepard out of a bar, pistol-whipping him and tying him to a fence. 
The University of Wyoming student died a few days later. 
Authorities have said Shepard's sexuality was a factor in the 
slaying. 
</P>
<P>
	Both men face murder, kidnapping and aggravated robbery charges.  
McKinney will be tried in August. 
</P>
<P>
	McKinney has been complaining about his treatment in the county  
jail. His attorneys have alleged that he is being treated more 
harshly than other inmates, that visitation by family members has 
been restricted and that he was denied athletic shoes his father 
attempted to drop off. 
</P>
