<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pirates' Silva Out for Two Weeks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRADENTON, Fla. (AP) -- Pittsburgh Pirates right-hander Jose  
Silva, struck in the face by a line drive earlier this week, won't 
be able to pitch in game conditions for two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Silva could be ready to pitch 3-4 days after the season begins,  
depending on how quickly the injury heals, so he may not have to go 
on the disabled list. 
</P>
<P>
	One option for Silva to keep his arm in shape might be to throw  
batting practice or practice games from behind a protective screen 
at the Pirate City minor league complex. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a two-week period in which the doctors say he must be  
careful,'' Pirates trainer Kent Biggerstaff said. ``That means what 
they said: He can't do anything that might cause it (the injury) to 
worsen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Silva was hit in the right cheekbone by a line drive Wednesday  
while pitching at Pirate City. The Pirates were off that day, but 
Silva pitched so he could stay on his normal throwing schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	The right side of Silva's face was badly swollen and his right  
eye was bloodshot Friday before the Pirates' pregame workout, but 
he should be able to throw softly on the sidelines as early as 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Silva would have been more badly injured if he didn't have a  
steel plate in his face from a 1994 traffic accident, Biggerstaff 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any bones that might have been broken were already protected  
by metal,'' Biggerstaff said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pirates probably won't try to rig up a protective face mask  
or shield that might allow Silva to throw without a screen because 
of a prior neck injury. He suffered a fractured jaw, nose and both 
eye orbits in the 1994 auto accident, which sidelined him for all 
but three minor-league games in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Silva isn't an established pitcher yet in the majors, but he is  
one of the unluckiest. 
</P>
<P>
	He was the Pirates' best starting pitcher early last season,  
going 6-3 with a 3.44 ERA in his first 15 starts, until breaking 
his right arm while bunting June 16 in Philadelphia. He missed the 
next three months of the season and was ineffective after returning 
in September, losing his final four decisions as his ERA climbed to 
4.40. 
</P>
<P>
	Once he returns, Silva is expected to be the No. 4 starter in  
the Pirates' rotation behind Francisco Cordova, Jason Schmidt and 
Pete Schourek. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pirates have a five-man rotation, but may need only four  
starters until late April because they have four off days during 
the first three weeks of the season. Chris Peters or rookie Kris 
Benson, who has an 0.50 ERA this spring, could move into the 
rotation until Silva is ready. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
