<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Stocks End Lower; Dow Down 14.15 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices drifted lower in sluggish trading  
Friday, as investors adjusted their holdings before the end of the 
quarter and kept an eye on NATO air strikes in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average was down 14.15 at 9,822.24,  
erasing most of an early 89-point loss. The Dow ended the week down 
81.31 points, having succumbed to light profit-taking after 
repeatedly hitting 10,000 in intraday trading last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators declined after a brief rally in  
technology shares lost steam. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 7.19 
to 1,282.80. The Nasdaq composite declined 15.63 to 2,419.17. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything seems a little heavy today,'' said Hank Herrmann,  
chief investment officer at Wadell &AMP; Reed in Overland Park, Kan. 
``Bonds rolled over, and the tech world is heavy, and I just think 
it's tired.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The stock market had advanced Thursday partly on relief about  
the military action in Kosovo. But investors were uneasier Friday. 
Stock prices fell in the morning after NATO aircraft and missiles 
hit targets in Yugoslavia, directing much of their fire on Kosovo, 
where fighting continued between Serbs and ethnic Albanians. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond prices also eased amid caution about Kosovo, pushing the  
yield on the 30-year Treasury bond up to 5.59 percent from 5.58 
percent late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors were worrying about what could happen over the  
weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of the people who believed that one or two air strikes in  
Kosovo would solve our problems over there are having second 
thoughts,'' said Alan Ackerman, senior vice president at Fahnestock 
&AMP; Co. ``Now many people are concerned with whether or not we will 
have to commit ground troops.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The end of the quarter next Wednesday also affected trading, as  
institutional investors such as mutual funds buffed up their 
portfolios before having to show them to clients. Some analysts 
expect that last-minute window-dressing to send stocks higher. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is still money in the hands of these money managers that  
has to be spent over the next couple of days,'' said Ricky 
Harrington, technical analyst at Interstate/Johnson Lane in 
Charlotte, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	Among technology stocks, IBM rose 1 1/16 to 172 3/8, while Compaq  
and Dell Computer also rose. 
</P>
<P>
	Big losers among the Dow components were Goodyear, down 2 3/16  
to 49 11/16. The Akron, Ohio tire and chemical maker said it will 
expand a Canadian passenger tire plant and increase production 
capacity by 40 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Merck, another Dow stock, fell 2 3/16 to 80 3/8. But Allied Signal  
rose 2 3/8 to 50 3/8. The company's truck brake systems subsidiary formed 
an alliance with Delphi Automotive Systems Corp. to make a new 
generation of anti-lock breaking systems. Delphi stock eased 1/16 
to 18. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 7-to-6 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where consolidated volume was moderate at 
851.9 million shares and down from Thursday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index fell 2.51 to 602.35, but the American  
Stock Exchange composite index rose 6.34 to 718.74. The Russell 
2000 index of smaller companies rose 0.93 to 393.92. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.19 percent,  
Germany's DAX index fell 1.75 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 rose 
0.89, and France's CAC-40 fell 0.7 percent. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
