<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Nissho Iwai Retrenching </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese trading company Nissho Iwai Corp. will  
sell its 5.2 percent stake in the package delivery company DHL 
International Ltd. to raise money after what is expected to be a 
huge loss at Nissho Iwai this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Nissho Iwai also announced today that its president, Masatake  
Kusamichi, will resign to take responsibility for the losses. 
</P>
<P>
	Nissho Iwai will sell its DHL stake back to the company for $73  
million, and expects to earn $42 million on the sale. DHL 
International's parent, DHL Worldwide Express, is based in Redwood 
City, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	For the fiscal year ending on March 31, Nissho Iwai estimates it  
will lose $669 million, much of it due to poor stock investments. 
</P>
<P>
	Nissho Iwai, Japan's sixth largest consolidated trading company,  
is an international wholesaler of everything from lumber to 
aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
	Shiro Yasutake, now Nissho Iwai's managing director, will  
succeed the outgoing president, who will stay with the company as 
an adviser and member of the board of directors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 16:44:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Juice Co. Seeks Address Name Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACO, Maine (AP) -- Fresh Samantha Inc., the fast-growing company  
that makes healthful fruit juices with funky cartoon labels, is 
worried that its not-so-natural sounding address conveys an image 
of smokestacks and chain-link fences. 
</P>
<P>
	Because the address, 84 Industrial Park Road, is printed on  
every bottle, company officials are hoping the city of Saco, Maine, 
will help them find a more appetizing alternative. 
</P>
<P>
	``People think of us as this all-natural, no preservatives, no  
concentrates company, which we are,'' said Fresh Samantha 
spokeswoman Betta Stothart. ``But we're located on this Industrial 
Park Road, which doesn't sound very attractive and it doesn't 
really apply.'' 
</P>
<P>
	First, because the city was planning to expand the industrial  
park to Springhill Road, Fresh Samantha suggested that the City 
Council adopt that name. 
</P>
<P>
	Council members rejected that idea, however, citing the costs of  
changing street signs, city maps and letterheads of every company 
on the road. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, Fresh Samantha says it may seek the council's permission to  
name its driveway as a private road and use that as its address. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the suggested names: Fresh Samantha Way and Yumdillishous  
Way, the latter being one of the trademark sayings that appear on 
most Fresh Samantha labels. 
</P>
<P>
	City officials seem receptive. ``As long as it's legal, I don't  
see any problem with it,'' Mayor William Johnson said. 
</P>
<P>
	In seven years, Fresh Samantha has grown from a seller of bean  
sprouts to a $38 million company, expanding into such markets as 
New York City, Washington, D.C., and Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	While no customers have complained about the current address,  
``as our product gets farther away from Maine, people don't have a 
real idea of what we're about as a company,'' Stothart said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 16:14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Walter Payton Delivers Pep Talk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LISLE, III. (AP) -- An upbeat Walter Payton kept his promise and  
delivered a long-distance motivational speech Thursday, calling 
area business leaders from a Minnesota hotel room near the clinic 
where he receives treatment for a liver disorder. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm doing good,'' Payton told the audience by telephone. ``My  
weight and energy have come back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Chicago Bears Hall of Famer was calling from Rochester,  
Minn., where he is being treated at the Mayo Clinic for a rare 
disease that can be corrected only by a liver transplant. 
</P>
<P>
	Before his illness was discovered, Payton had agreed to be the  
keynote speaker at an expo here. He had planned to attend the event 
as recently as last week, but said his doctor wanted him to come to 
the clinic for a bone scan. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just taking tests,'' Payton said. ``There are a lot of  
things you have to go through before things can happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Payton said he found it awkward making his remarks via telephone  
because he was unable to gauge the response of his audience. As it 
turned out, the audience's reaction was as enthusiastic as Payton's 
pep talk. 
</P>
<P>
	One by one, individuals shared their favorite memories of  
Payton's NFL career and commended him for his courage in the face 
of a life-threatening condition. In return, the ex-running back 
displayed the winning attitude that led to his success on the 
football field as well as in the corporate board room. 
</P>
<P>
	``No matter what you do, you can always do it better,'' said  
Payton, whose many business ventures include night clubs and Indy 
race cars. ``Customer satisfaction is as important as prosperity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Payton also spoke of the importance of family and raising  
children. He said he was particularly impressed with public 
reaction to the news of his illness. 
</P>
<P>
	``For me, it's been uplifting,'' he said. ``It's humbling. The  
reason I'm doing so well is because of the prayers that God has 
heard for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That Payton had to speak to them long-distance had a moving  
effect on many who heard his remarks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I saw teary eyes,'' said Shane Beard, chairman of the expo.  
``Perhaps it was more inspiring with him being where he was -- more 
so than if he were actually here.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
