<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 22:31:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Woman Awarded in Mastectomy Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- When JoAnne Motichka's mastectomy-scarred chest  
graced the cover of The New York Times Magazine, it was, in part, a 
tribute to women who have survived one of life's greatest traumas. 
</P>
<P>
	But according to the 45-year-old photographer-artist, known  
professionally as ``Matuschka,'' it was a trauma she didn't have to 
endure. On Friday a jury agreed, awarding her $2.2 million after 
determining that a doctor removed her breast unnecessarily. 
</P>
<P>
	In response to the award, she said simply: ``I would rather have  
my breast.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A lawyer for the defendant, Dr. Hiram S. Cody, argued that the  
doctor told Matuschka enough for her to make an informed decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``Based on the law and the facts, we are very confident that the  
jury's verdict will be overturned on appeal,'' David Richmond said 
in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Matuschka said Dr. Hiram S. Cody found a malignant lump, a  
little smaller than a penny, in her breast. However, she said the 
doctor mistakenly exaggerated her condition. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said I had intraductal carcinoma and needed a mastectomy  
immediately. There was no discussion of any other treatment 
possibility,'' Matuschka said. 
</P>
<P>
	She underwent a mastectomy in June 1991.  
</P>
<P>
	It was in later conversations with Cody and other doctors that  
Matuschka learned that a lumpectomy, surgery in which only the 
cancerous lump is removed, might have been sufficient, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Matuschka's experience turned her into an activist for breast  
cancer awareness. She became famous for her graphic sculptures and 
self-portraits, including the award-winning photograph of her 
surgically mutilated chest that appeared on The New York Times 
Magazine on Aug. 13, 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	The title of her forthcoming biography, ``You Can't Look Away  
Any More,'' provided the headline over the magazine article. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 14:57:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Questioned on IOC Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Two congressional leaders asked President  
Clinton on Friday why he hasn't extended federal anti-bribery laws 
to the International Olympic Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Reps. Tom Bliley, chairman of the House Commerce Committee, and  
Michael Oxley, head of its finance subcommittee, noted that the 
White House was asked almost a month ago by the U.S. Olympic 
Committee to include the IOC under the Foreign Corrupt Practices 
Act. 
</P>
<P>
	That request came as an independent USOC investigation, headed  
by former Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, concluded that 
the IOC fostered a ``culture of improper gift-giving'' that led to 
a multimillion-dollar vote-buying scheme in Salt Lake's successful 
quest for the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	``The recent events regarding the ethical lapses concerning the  
IOC raise serious questions that must be addressed promptly,'' 
Bliley, R-Va., and Oxley, R-Ohio, wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Saying they were ``shocked and discouraged'' by the revelations  
of cash, scholarships, medical treatment and other inducements for 
IOC members from Salt Lake bidders, the lawmakers asked the 
president what steps he had taken to make such actions illegal and 
make sure other nations did likewise. 
</P>
<P>
	They gave Clinton until April 13 to either add the IOC to the  
organizations covered by federal international business bribery 
laws or tell them why he had failed to act. 
</P>
<P>
	They also asked him to list what countries the White House had  
contacted to try to have them adopt similar codes ``so as to make 
bribery of an IOC official illegal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bliley and Oxley were primary House architects of the foreign  
bribery laws last year and said Clinton could cover the IOC through 
a stroke of a pen on an executive order. 
</P>
<P>
	``Fairness, clear rules and objectivity are critical in the  
sporting world,'' their letter said. ``The Olympic spirit reflects 
the highest ideals in this respect, or at least it should. 
</P>
<P>
	``Athletes spend years of hard work in training in order to  
pursue the Olympic dream. Their tireless dedication to excellence 
should not be sullied by corruption, or by acquiescence to 
corruption.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The letter from the House members was the latest step by federal  
agencies into the Olympic bribery case, the worst scandal in the 
history of the world's biggest sports event. 
</P>
<P>
	The Justice Department and the FBI are investigating possible  
violations of federal fraud and tax laws, and the Senate Commerce 
Committee has scheduled hearings on the scandal for April 14. 
</P>
<P>
	Pending Senate legislation also would strip the IOC's tax-exempt  
status in the United States, limit the amount of Olympic fees 
sponsors could deduct and place U.S. TV rights fees -- the single 
biggest source of Olympic income -- with the USOC instead of the 
IOC. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC expelled six members last week for accepting bribes and  
started the action on what it described as a series of long-range 
reforms, including a task force to restructure the committee and 
membership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 05:46:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Holdsclaw, Peck Earn AP Awards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Chamique Holdsclaw is leaving Tennessee  
with a lot more in her resume than she expected when she arrived. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I came into Tennessee my freshman year, I said OK,  
hopefully I can play,'' Holdsclaw said. ``I'm going to work hard 
enough to play. Hopefully I can help the team, average 10 points or 
so.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Help the team? Well, Holdsclaw certainly did that. She led  
Tennessee to three national championships and became a first-team 
All-American three times. On Thursday, she became the first woman 
to win The Associated Press player of the year award twice. 
</P>
<P>
	Holdsclaw was an overwhelming choice for the honor in voting by  
AP newspaper and broadcast members nationwide. Purdue's Carolyn 
Peck, who has her team in contention for the national championship 
in just her second season, was named the coach of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a great honor. It's very exciting,'' Peck said. ``But  
I've got to give credit to my team and my staff. It's been a 
complete team effort the last two years. Any coach who walked into 
the situation I did with the players I had would be blessed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Holdsclaw, the most decorated player of her era, also won The AP  
award as a junior last season, when she led Tennessee to a 39-0 
record and its third straight national championship. The Lady Vols 
fell one game short of returning to the Final Four this year, 
losing to Duke in a regional final. 
</P>
<P>
	But the 6-foot-2 Holdsclaw, so fluid that she makes the game  
seem effortless, still had an outstanding season. 
</P>
<P>
	She led Tennessee in scoring (21.3) and rebounding (8.1), shot  
52 percent from the field and left thousands of admiring fans 
something to remember by matching her career high of 39 points in 
her final home game, an 89-62 victory over Boston College in the 
second round of the NCAA tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	Holdsclaw finished with 3,025 points and 1,295 rebounds, No. 1  
on Tennessee's career list in both categories. 
</P>
<P>
	``She has been so special,'' Tennessee coach Pat Summitt said.  
``She has been a low-maintenance player because she does the right 
things off the floor. She makes good decisions. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has been a joy and an honor to coach Chamique, and I have  
to throw in every once in a while that it has been a challenge,'' 
Summitt said. ``But I like the challenge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The challenge for Summitt was to take a great player and help  
make her even better. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I challenged myself immediately when she signed with  
us,'' Summitt said. ``Because I saw this potential for greatness. I 
don't know if I envisioned three national championships and the 
level of notoriety that Chamique received. 
</P>
<P>
	``But I did envision someone very special. So I was very  
challenged because I knew all eyes would be on this player and the 
development of this player.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Peck will join the WNBA's Orlando Miracle as coach and general  
manager when the college season ends, but she has done far more 
than just go through the motions as a lame-duck coach. 
</P>
<P>
	Purdue became No. 1 for the first time in school history and  
will take a 32-1 record and 30-game winning streak into the 
national semifinals against Louisiana Tech tonight. 
</P>
<P>
	It would have been easy for Peck to coast this season, but  
that's not her style. 
</P>
<P>
	``We ask so much of our players,'' she said. ``To feel as a  
staff we were not working as hard as we possibly could would have 
been a disservice to our team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Peck counts Summitt among her influences after spending two  
seasons as an assistant at Tennessee. She also spent one year on 
the staff at Kentucky and one season as an assistant to Nell 
Fortner at Purdue. When Fortner left to coach the U.S. national 
team, Peck was promoted to replace her. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the combination of all of that, plus the staff I have,  
has helped me so much,'' Peck said. ``One thing I've found as a 
head coach, you don't have to feel like you've got to do it all by 
yourself. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a team effort. And I think when our team sees us work as  
a team, they work as a team as well.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 05:46:35 </DATE_TIME>
