<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 14:05:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China Seeks WTO Membership Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- China is holding out the tantalizing prospect  
of opening its huge market to American manufacturers, farmers and 
financial firms in return for membership in the World Trade 
Organization. 
</P>
<P>
	Negotiations between the United States and China over WTO  
membership, which have proceeded in fits and starts over the past 
13 years, have intensified in recent weeks even as anger over 
China's human rights record and alleged nuclear espionage have 
risen in Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Both sides are struggling to complete a deal that could be used  
as the centerpiece for a visit next month by Chinese Premier Zhu 
Rongji. The White House announced Friday that Zhu will hold 
high-level talks with President Clinton on April 8 as part of a 
nine-day visit that will include stops in five other American 
cities. 
</P>
<P>
	Zhu is anxious to capture the WTO prize that has long eluded  
China. U.S. officials say China's market-opening offers have 
improved considerably since Zhu became personally involved in the 
negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States is seeking to break down sizable barriers to  
the sale of American exports of everything from wheat to cars to 
compact discs. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the Clinton administration wants permission for  
American banks, investment houses and insurance companies to expand 
their Chinese operations in order to narrow a U.S. trade deficit 
with China that last year hit a record $57 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	One U.S. official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said  
China had made more progress in opening its markets in past month 
than it had in the past three years. But he said the administration 
feels much more needs to be done. 
</P>
<P>
	A high-level team led by U.S. Assistant Trade Representative Bob  
Cassidy is in Beijing and is expected to continue negotiations over 
the weekend. Commerce Secretary William Daley will arrive in 
Beijing on Monday, leading a trade mission that includes top U.S. 
business executives. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky is thought likely  
to join the talks either in Beijing or when they move back to 
Washington as officials try to close a deal in the days before 
Zhu's arrival. 
</P>
<P>
	In preparation for a possible breakthrough, Barshefsky and other  
administration officials have been briefing members of Congress on 
the accelerated pace of the talks. 
</P>
<P>
	But trade experts said they still believe a WTO deal this year  
would be a long shot, given the current deterioration in 
U.S.-Chinese relations, including recent allegations that Beijing 
stole U.S. nuclear secrets in the 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	``There has been real progress in the negotiations in a number  
of areas,'' said Greg Mastel, a trade expert at the Economic 
Strategy Institute in Washington. ``But the environment is so bad 
right now that it will be a tremendous uphill political struggle to 
sell even a good agreement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The WTO sets the rules for global trade. China first sought  
membership in 1986 in the WTO's predecessor organization, the 
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade. Negotiations for China's 
membership were nearly complete in 1989 when talks were put on hold 
following China's crackdown on the democracy movement. 
</P>
<P>
	To gain WTO membership, China must satisfy the United States and  
other economic powers that it will play by global trade rules by 
opening up its economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The new Chinese offers include proposals to cut high tariffs and  
other barriers restricting the sale of U.S.-manufactured goods and 
agriculture products such as wheat and citrus, to allow greater 
foreign ownership in such areas as telecommunications companies and 
to remove tight restrictions on operations by American banks. 
</P>
<P>
	For China, WTO membership would mean protection against  
unilateral trade sanctions imposed by the United States or other 
WTO members as well as the prestige of being at the table when the 
next round of global trade talks begins this coming November in 
Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
	Barshefsky said Chinese policy-makers would like WTO membership  
as a way to boost foreign investment, which has slowed dramatically 
in the wake of the Asian economic crisis, and to keep up the 
momentum for reform of outdated state-run enterprises. 
</P>
<P>
	``All these factors have combined to engender in China a  
seriousness of purpose that we have never seen before,'' she said 
in an interview. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 22:41:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Army Sec.: Hard To Reinstate Draft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Reinstating a fair military draft to fill U.S.  
military ranks would be harder to do than in the past, and an 
unfair one might do more harm than good, Army Secretary Louis 
Caldera says. 
</P>
<P>
	Conscription also might not be practical, given lower manpower  
needs in the post Cold War era, the volunteer tradition that has 
developed since the draft ended 25 years ago and the high cost of 
training recruits, Caldera said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In a speech at the National Press Club, the Army secretary said  
renewing the draft, which required two years of military service, 
is one possible response to the problems the armed forces are 
having in finding enough recruits to fill its ranks. 
</P>
<P>
	``By its very nature, the draft communicates that military  
service is everyone's obligation,'' Caldera said. ``And it might 
act as a leveling influence in the ranks and in other society,'' 
bringing together young people from differing backgrounds. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the draft would have the added benefit of reducing the  
$100 million a year the Army spends in recruiting advertising. 
</P>
<P>
	``But for today's Army,'' Caldera said, ``a draft may simply not  
be fair or practical'' because the armed forces do not need as many 
young people as they did during World War II. During the Vietnam 
War in the 1960s and 1970s only one in 10 of those eligible to 
serve did so, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today, with our smaller post-Cold War armed forces, our  
stronger volunteer tradition and our need for longer terms of 
service to get a good return on the high, upfront training costs, 
it would be ever harder to fashion a fair draft,'' Caldera said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said a draft that was regarded as unfair ``because too few  
are called, might harden feeling against the military and hurt 
rather than help raise the regard in which military service is 
held.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Almost all male U.S. citizens and male aliens between 18 and 25  
years old living in the United States, must register with the 
Selective Service. But the United States has not drafted the 
nation's youth into the military since the Vietnam War ended. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 08:45:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: Mrs. Clinton's Support Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- New Yorkers aren't as hot on the idea of  
Hillary Rodham Clinton running for Senate as they were a month ago, 
according to a poll released today. 
</P>
<P>
	A Marist College Institute for Public Opinion poll conducted  
among registered voters this week found 45 percent saying she 
should run, down from 56 percent last month. Another 49 percent of 
respondents thought she should not run, up from 37 percent in 
February. 
</P>
<P>
	The results mirror other polls that have found a decrease in  
public enthusiasm for a Senate bid by Mrs. Clinton following a 
spike of support when reports first circulated that she was 
considering a run for retiring U.S. Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan's 
seat. 
</P>
<P>
	Sixty percent of Marist poll respondents believed Mrs. Clinton  
would run. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll of 616 registered voters was conducted March 22-24. It  
has a margin of error of plus or minus 4 percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton is not expected to announce her intentions until  
this summer. The most prominent potential Republican contender, New 
York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, has not announced his plans 
either. 
</P>
<P>
	The Marist poll found a potential matchup between the two  
continues to be close, with 48 percent for Mrs. Clinton and 46 
percent for Giuliani. That was statistically unchanged from a 
Marist poll released March 3 that found Mrs. Clinton with 50 
percent and Giuliani with 46 percent, but a drop-off from the first 
lady's leads of 53-42 in January and 49-38 in February in the same 
poll. 
</P>
<P>
	A poll from the Quinnipiac College Polling Institute released  
Tuesday found the first lady favored by 50 percent of registered 
voters surveyed to 39 percent for Giuliani. A Quinnipiac poll 
released a month ago had Mrs. Clinton leading Giuliani 54 percent 
to 36 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
