<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Whitewater Figure Found Guilty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- There's more prison time in store for  
Whitewater figure David Hale, but not much. 
</P>
<P>
	A Pulaski County jury on Thursday convicted Hale of lying to  
regulators about the solvency of his burial insurance company and 
sentenced him to 21 days in prison. He could serve as little as 3 1/2 
days with good behavior. 
</P>
<P>
	Sentencing was set for April 5. He had faced up to eight years  
in jail. 
</P>
<P>
	Hale was convicted of putting $150,000 into the bank account of  
the National Savings Life Insurance Co. to show it was financially 
stable, then withdrawing the money days later and lying about it 
still later. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense lawyers said the infraction was a technicality and that  
no one lost money as a result. 
</P>
<P>
	The former municipal judge said he would likely appeal, saying  
jurors unfairly considered his Whitewater crimes as part of his 
case. Defense lawyer David Bowden was against the idea. 
</P>
<P>
	Hale pleaded guilty in the Whitewater case to two felonies and  
served 21 months of a 28-month sentence. He was a key witness 
against then-Gov. Jim Guy Tucker and James and Susan McDougal at 
their 1996 fraud trial. All three were convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	The McDougals were business partners with President Clinton and  
Hillary Rodham Clinton in the Whitewater land development. Hale had 
once claimed Clinton pressured him to make an illegal loan. Clinton 
denied the allegation. 
</P>
<P>
	In the insurance case, Hale testified that business dealings  
surrounding the operation of his burial insurance company were 
proper. But he acknowledged a long history of lying about his 
business operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
