<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> K One King Eyes Gallery Stakes Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FLORENCE, Ky. (AP) -- K One King has done all his racing this  
year at Turfway Park rather than face Triple Crown prospects 
elsewhere. After Saturday, he could become a regular shipper. 
</P>
<P>
	``I recognized his ability a long time ago,'' said trainer Akiko  
Gothard, who likes the colt's chances in Saturday's $750,000 
Gallery Furniture.com Stakes. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1 1/8-mile race was known as the Jim Beam Stakes for 17 years  
until Houston furniture dealer Jim McIngvale took over sponsorship 
this spring. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't take him to other tracks for stakes races -- not  
because I didn't have confidence -- but I felt it was better for the 
horse to stay and to have other people come here to compete,'' 
Gothard said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he goes to the Derby ... after the Derby we've got to ship  
him all over the place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	K One King has four wins in six starts. He broke his maiden in  
October at Keeneland, then ran second in an allowance race at 
Churchill Downs and another at Turfway. Since then he's won three 
straight, including a $100,000 stakes on March 6. 
</P>
<P>
	K One King is the Turfway oddsmaker's second pick at 3-1. The  
horse to beat is speedster Straight Man, trained by Bob Baffert and 
8-5 on the morning line. 
</P>
<P>
	Straight Man is owned by Bob and Beverly Lewis, who won't see  
the race live. They are in the United Arab Emirates to watch Silver 
Charm, their 1997 Kentucky Derby and Preakness winner, try to 
repeat in the $5 million Dubai World Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	Gothard was born in Tokyo and has been training horses in  
Kentucky for three decades. She also runs a sales agency that buys 
horses for a predominately Japanese clientele. 
</P>
<P>
	Yoshiko Sato owned K One King until Madeleine Paulson, wife of  
Allen Paulson, bought him earlier this month for an a price 
believed to be between $1 million and $2 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Because the Paulsons have owned many stakes winners, including  
the great Cigar, Mrs. Paulson's interest reinforced Gothard's 
belief that K One King is a legitimate Triple Crown contender. 
</P>
<P>
	``She knows racing very well, and knows horses,'' Gothard said.  
</P>
<P>
	K One King has shown a preference to lay off the pace and make a  
big stretch run. But along with raw ability, Gothard said the colt 
has the demeanor to be a champion. 
</P>
<P>
	``This horse doesn't get excited much about anything,'' she  
said. ``He's a very calm horse. 
</P>
<P>
	``We used to take his temperature all the time because he'd lie  
down in his stall -- he'd be sleeping all the time,'' Gothard said. 
``I wondered if he may have a fever. We now know what he is, so we 
don't worry about him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert will be flying back from Dubai to saddle Straight Man,  
who is 2-for-2 and has shown exceptional speed in both races at 
Santa Anita. Turfway often favors speed, although not as much as 
California tracks. 
</P>
<P>
	Others in the eight-horse field are Aly's Alley, who has not run  
as well as he did as a 2-year-old; Epic Honor, winner of two 
straight at San Francisco-area tracks; Lethal Instrument, runnerup 
to Straight Man in his last race; Machine to Tower, winner of three 
straight, including the Whirlaway Stakes at Aqueduct; and two Nick 
Zito-trained horses -- The Groom Is Red, 0-for-3 since the Champagne 
Stakes at Belmont Park in October, and Stephen Got Even, winner of 
two straight at Gulfstream Park. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 06:07:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Strongest Explosion Ever Observed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- It happened a long time ago in a place far,  
far away, but a gamma ray burst detected in January was the most 
powerful explosion ever observed, releasing in just seconds an 
energy wave equal to billions of years of light from thousands of 
suns. 
</P>
<P>
	In a series of studies published today in the journal Science  
and next month in Nature, a team of international researchers say 
the explosion occurred 9 billion light-years from Earth. 
</P>
<P>
	Just what caused the explosion is still a mystery.  
</P>
<P>
	``It is probably something to do with massive stars,'' said S.  
George Djorgovski, a California Institute of Technology astronomer 
who is co-author of a study in Nature. ``The real truth is, we 
don't know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The gamma ray burst was detected by Italian and U.S. science  
satellites that sent an alert to a network of ground instruments 
and telescopes. Within seconds, telescopes focused on the area of 
the sky where the burst originated and captured views in visible 
light. Later, more powerful telescopes photographed the explosion's 
afterglow. 
</P>
<P>
	The alert enabled astronomers, for the first time in history, to  
capture optical views of a gamma ray burst event as the detection 
was underway. Analyzing this light helped the scientists determine 
that the burst happened so far away that it took 9 billion years 
for the light to reach Earth. Light travels about 6 trillion miles 
a year in space. 
</P>
<P>
	Djorgovski said an analysis of light and other energy spewing  
from the explosion suggests that for a very brief instant the 
explosion was more luminous and energetic than the whole rest of 
the universe. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the gamma rays were emitted equally in all directions,  
their energy would correspond to 10,000 times the energy emitted by 
our sun over its entire lifetime of about 5 billion years,'' he 
said in an interview. ``Yet the burst last only a few tens of 
seconds.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Djorgovski said there is some evidence the energy was detected  
as a concentrated beam that was pointed at the Earth. A beam would 
give an impression of greater energy in the explosion, just as a 
flashlight beam focused on one spot appears to be brighter than an 
uncovered bulb that scatters the same amount of light in all 
directions. 
</P>
<P>
	But even if the gamma ray energy were sent out in a beam, said  
Djorgovski, that would reduce the energy estimate only by a factor 
of 10 to 100. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would still be the most powerful explosion ever observed,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gamma ray bursts were discovered in 1967, but the phenomenon  
remains mysterious. The bursts occur randomly across the sky 
several hundred times a year, lasting for only a few milliseconds 
to a few minutes. Because of the short duration, large telescopes 
in the past could not be focused in time to catch optical views. 
The satellite alert system now makes that possible. 
</P>
<P>
	Djorgovski said there have been more than 150 theories proposed  
to explain gamma ray bursts. The two leading ideas, he said, both 
involve massive stars. One theory proposes that the burst occurs 
when two massive stars merge and form a black hole. Another theory 
proposes that the energy eruption comes from a hypersupernova, a 
stellar explosion much larger than that of an ordinary supernova. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is perfectly possible that the source is even stranger and  
more unusual,'' said Djorgovski, ``but the circumstantial evidence 
suggests it involves massive stars.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 03:53:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Disney Must Pay $9.3M Judgment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- The Walt Disney Co. must pay $9.3 million  
for failing to adequately promote and merchandise a cuddly European 
comic-book character called Marsupilami, a federal appeals court 
ruled. 
</P>
<P>
	The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals on Thursday upheld a  
judge's decision that Disney had broken its promise to make 
Marsupilami a star on network television and in store merchandise. 
</P>
<P>
	Marsupilami is a yellow and black animal, described as a cross  
between a mouse and a marsupial. It's featured in French-language 
comic books in France, Belgium and Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	Parent company Marsu in 1990 signed a contract giving Disney  
worldwide rights. The court said Disney spent years failing to meet 
its obligations. 
</P>
<P>
	Disney failed to produce 13 promised half-hour animated films  
starring the character, never asked networks to show such films and 
used inexperienced executives for a poorly planned merchandising 
campaign, the court said in a 3-0 ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	Disney lawyer Michael Cardozo did not return a call Thursday.  
</P>
<P>
	In a separate case, the California Division of Occupational  
Safety and Health fined Disneyland $12,500 for a Christmas Eve 
accident that killed a tourist waiting to board a cruise ride at 
the Anaheim amusement park. 
</P>
<P>
	The sailing ship Columbia wasn't properly tied off as it docked,  
whipping a 9-pound metal cleat out of the dock and into a crowd. 
Luan Phi Dawson, 33, of Duvall, Wash., was killed. His wife and 
another woman were injured. 
</P>
<P>
	There were ``serious violations'' in training and equipment at  
the ride, the agency said Thursday. The cleat wasn't enough to stop 
the boat. 
</P>
<P>
	The park has announced five steps intended to improve safety at  
the ride, including new equipment and employee training. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 16:23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Duke's Carrawell: Ghetto to Great </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- Chris Carrawell plays a smooth game,  
even though it sometimes looks awkward, his bowed legs and high 
dribble producing a clumsy picture on the court. 
</P>
<P>
	But even more surprising is the story of how Carrawell journeyed  
from the ghettos of St. Louis to the quaint campus of Duke, called 
the ``Ivy League of the South.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``People said I would be on the first train ride back home,''  
the 6-foot-6 junior forward said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	They couldn't have been more wrong. Carrawell has become one of  
the most valuable members of a team that has won 31 straight games 
and plays Michigan State in the semifinals Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the city, you don't learn the fundamentals,'' Carrawell  
said. ``I didn't learn the fundamentals of the game until I got 
here -- how to pivot correctly, how to ball fake. On the playground 
you just play. Everything is done off the dribble.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't the only lesson Carrawell missed. Three weeks ago, he  
was approached by a man before the Atlantic Coast Conference 
tournament who said he was Carrawell's father. 
</P>
<P>
	``I haven't talked to him since then,'' Carrawell said. ``I just  
wanted to send a message like, `Don't come around when it gets 
good. Where were you when things were tough growing up in the inner 
city?' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not like a thing where I'm mad at him, but it's like, `Be  
a real father, be a real man.''' 
</P>
<P>
	After the surprise meeting, Carrawell had a few rough games.  
</P>
<P>
	``It was like, `OK, I'm all right,' but naturally it's going to  
affect you,'' he said. ``I shook it off a little bit against 
Temple'' in the East Regional finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Carrawell said he learned other points about being a man on the  
playgrounds of a St. Louis housing project where he grew up. He 
often played for money against much older men. How much older? 
</P>
<P>
	``I could be 11, these guys 25 or 26 -- and that's no  
exaggeration,'' Carrawell said. ``These guys would play against you 
and beat you up. It's very physical, but you learn how to 
compete.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Carrawell said he favored UNLV growing up. He and his friends  
hated Duke. 
</P>
<P>
	``We couldn't believe that guys that have 3.0 GPAs could play  
like that. It was one of those things ... we were envious,'' 
Carrawell said. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, Carrawell is making grades, averaging 9.8 points and 4.9  
rebounds, and regarded by the Duke coaches as an invaluable cog. 
</P>
<P>
	``Chris is one of the most versatile human beings around,''  
assistant coach Quin Snyder said. ``He is playing his `ghetto role' 
now, which is fine, but there is a lot more to Chris than anybody 
realizes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Chris is a fun guy to have a conversation with, he's  
unbelievably attentive. He's intelligent, he gets along with people 
from all different walks of life. He adds diversity to our team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And so maybe it's not that great a surprise that one of  
Carrawell's best friends on the Duke team is Chris Burgess, a 
suburban kid from Irvine, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	``He kind of jokes around and calls me the surfer guy and I joke  
around and call him the city rat,'' Burgess said. 
</P>
<P>
	But once the ball goes up Saturday night, the only thing that  
will matter to both of them is the chance to win a national 
championship. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 12:36:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Russia Demands To End Bombing Fails </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Russia failed Friday to muster enough  
support to pass a resolution in the U.N. Security Council demanding 
that NATO stop bombing Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Only three of the council's 15 members raised their hands in  
support of the Russian initiative, ensuring the measure's defeat 
even before the United States, Britain and France got a chance to 
veto it, as they did. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia, China and Namibia voted in favor. All other 12 members  
opposed. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine members of the council, including all five veto-wielding  
states, must vote in favor of a resolution in order for it to pass. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia had forced the council to take up its resolution to press  
its case that NATO intervention against its allies in Belgrade was 
illegal because the Security Council hadn't specifically authorized 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russian resolution states that NATO's action constituted a  
``flagrant violation'' of the U.N. Charter as well as a threat to 
international peace and security. 
</P>
<P>
	It demands an immediate halt to the NATO strikes and the urgent  
resumption of negotiations between Serbs and ethnic Albanians. 
</P>
<P>
	``Law and lawlessness are in the balance today,'' Russian  
Ambassador Sergey Lavrov warned the council before the vote. 
</P>
<P>
	Urging the resolution's defeat, the deputy U.S. ambassador,  
Peter Burleigh, said the Russian claim that NATO's actions violated 
the U.N. charter ``turns the truth on its head.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The U.N. charter does not sanction armed assaults upon ethnic  
groups, or imply that the international community should turn a 
blind eye to a growing humanitarian disaster,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia circulated the resolution Thursday to keep its campaign  
against NATO action in the diplomatic spotlight. Moscow, however, 
has offered its allies in Belgrade little tangible support other 
than threats to flout an international arms embargo and provide 
them with weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	While several nations have agreed that the council should have  
authorized the intervention, many council members argued that 
intervention was necessary on an exceptional basis because of the 
humanitarian threat posed by the continued Serb offensive in 
Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	The last time a council resolution was rejected by a lack of  
`yes' votes was on June 29, 1993, after the United States and 
non-aligned countries sponsored a resolution to exempt 
Bosnia-Herzegovina from an arms embargo on Yugoslavia. Six 
countries voted in favor and nine abstained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 12:36:02 </DATE_TIME>
