<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Octuplet Family Accepts Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LEAGUE CITY, Texas (AP) -- The seven surviving Houston octuplets  
and their parents received a new home Friday, courtesy of Federal 
National Home Mortgage Association, known as Fannie Mae. 
</P>
<P>
	The parents, Nkem Chukwu and Iyke Louis Udobi, accepted the keys  
to the six-bedroom, 5,384-square-foot house at a ribbon-cutting 
ceremony outside the home. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's finer inside than outside,'' Ms. Chukwu said.  
</P>
<P>
	The two-story home southeast of Houston was built in 1992 and is  
appraised at $274,000, according to county real estate records. 
Fannie Mae donated the home to a trust for the family after being 
approached by Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee, D-Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	The family plans to move in after the four octuplets who are  
still hospitalized are released. Three girls -- Gorom, Chidi and 
Chima -- and their brother, Ikem, are in serious but stable 
condition. 
</P>
<P>
	Three of the octuplets -- Ebuka, Echerem and Jioke -- went home  
March 3. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Chukwu delivered Ebuka on Dec. 8 and the other seven on Dec.  
20. The eighth baby, Odera, died a week after birth. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 14:35:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> General Cigar Sells Some Brands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- General Cigar is selling its lower-priced cigar  
business that includes brands like Tiparillo and White Owl to a 
Swedish company best known in the United States for Red Man chewing 
tobacco. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale announced Friday comes amid a slowdown in the dramatic  
growth of cigar sales during the mid-90s, a period that spawned 
fashionable cigar bars where men and women could savor a stogie 
despite tobacco's health risks. 
</P>
<P>
	General Cigar is selling what it calls its mass-market cigar  
business that also includes the Garcia y Vega and Tijuana Smalls 
brands to Swedish Match AB from Stockholm for $200 million in cash. 
</P>
<P>
	Swedish Match is among the world's biggest cigar makers but  
sells few cigars in the United States where it is better known for 
smokeless tobacco products like Red Man and Timberwolf. 
</P>
<P>
	News of the deal helped shares of both companies. General Cigar  
rose $1 a share, or by 10.5 percent, to $10.50 on the New York 
Stock Exchange, while the U.S. stock of Swedish Match gained 25 
cents a share to $33 on the Nasdaq Stock Market. 
</P>
<P>
	Included in the sale are two General Cigar manufacturing plants  
in Dothan, Ala., and Santiago, Dominican Republic. 
</P>
<P>
	The hundreds of employees at both plants are expected to  
continue to have jobs after Swedish Match takes control, said Edgar 
M. Cullman Jr., chief executive of General Cigar. 
</P>
<P>
	General Cigar is holding on to its premium cigar business  
including brands like Macanudo, Partagas, Punch and Hoyo de 
Monterrey that accounts for more than half of its overall sales and 
profits. 
</P>
<P>
	It is also keeping its Club Macanudo cigar bars in New York and  
Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of cigars sold in the United States surged 50.8  
percent between 1993 and 1997, including gains of 15.6 percent in 
1996 and 12.5 percent in 1997, according to John Maxwell, analyst 
for Davenport &AMP; Co. in Richmond, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	But growth slowed to 3.5 percent in 1998, Maxwell said, and  
cigar sales revenue dipped to $1.705 billion from $1.720 billion in 
1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of it was just a fad,'' Maxwell said. ``Some cigars that  
were selling for a few bucks are now selling for about 30 cents.'' 
</P>
<P>
	General Cigar, however, has managed to sell more premium cigars  
even as such sales have fallen precipitously industrywide. 
</P>
<P>
	Maxwell said the industry sold 21.8 percent fewer premium cigars  
in the U.S. in 1998, but General Cigar sold 4.3 percent more last 
year and was the leader in the U.S. market for premium cigars. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to concentrate on the premium cigar business where we  
have the great strength,'' Cullman told reporters and analysts in a 
telephone conference. ``We have been in the business of tobacco for 
long time and we think we know how to make a very good cigar.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the company sold the mass-market business because it had  
gone as far as it could on its own in getting its cigars on the 
shelves of larger retail chains. 
</P>
<P>
	Cullman conceded that cigar smoking ``has moderated considerably  
over the last 18 months.'' He said there have been ``hundreds of 
new brands'' introduced over the past five years and added ``there 
is an awful lot of product out there trying to find a smoker.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he said that the brand names consumers already know remain  
valuable properties. 
</P>
<P>
	The company plans to use proceeds from the sale to reduce debt  
and make investments or buy other premium cigar businesses. Cullman 
said his company would be interested in Cuban cigar companies 
should the U.S. embargo on trade with the Caribbean nation be 
lifted. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the agreement, New York-based General Cigar will  
continue to supply tobacco to Swedish Match for the brands being 
sold. 
</P>
<P>
	Swedish Match's sales force, meanwhile, will start selling some  
General Cigar premium brands in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal is subject to approval by regulators but is expected to  
close by the end of April, the companies said in a joint statement. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
