<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No New Deal for Giants' J.T. Snow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. (AP) -- Unable to reach a new contract  
agreement, the San Francisco Giants and J.T. Snow broke off talks 
Friday, raising the possibility the first baseman will become a 
free agent after the season. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're locked in on four or five years. We're at three years  
and an option,'' Giants assistant general manager Ned Colletti 
said. ``We're not inclined to go any farther. They're not inclined 
to take any less so for now at least, we're going to put it 
aside.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Snow, who earned his fourth career Gold Glove award after  
committing just one error last season, gets $3 million this season, 
the last year of his current pact. 
</P>
<P>
	General manager Brian Sabean and Colletti began talks several  
weeks ago with Snow's agent, Dan Horwits. 
</P>
<P>
	Their latest offer to Snow called for a three-year extension  
worth $16 million plus an option for a fourth year that would have 
been triggered automatically if Snow met certain performance 
clauses. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Horwits insisted on a deal comparable to the $24  
million, four-year deal recently signed by Pittsburgh first baseman 
Kevin Young. 
</P>
<P>
	Snow, 31, came to San Francisco two years ago in a trade with  
California. He hit .281 with a career-high 28 homers in 1997 but 
slumped to .248 with 15 homers last season while battling shoulder 
and wrist injuries for most of the season. He also was concerned 
about his terminally ill mother, who died last June. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we all realize what I went through last year and if I  
had my normal amount of at bats, my numbers would have been right 
there,'' Snow said. 
</P>
<P>
	This spring, Snow abandoned switch-hitting after three straight  
years of hitting below .200 from the right side. 
</P>
<P>
	``I won't make a stink about it,'' Snow said. ``I'm not going to  
make a big uproar. My contract is signed through 1999. I'm just 
going to go out and go about my business the way I always have, 
play every game hard.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
