<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Comparison of Fiscal 2000 Budgets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	A comparison of the fiscal 2000 budgets proposed by President  
Clinton and House and Senate Republicans. Numbers are as calculated 
by the Congressional Budget Office, and may not add due to 
rounding: 
</P>
<P>
	--OVERALL: For 2000, Clinton would spend $1.79 trillion and raise  
$1.87 trillion in revenue for an $80 billion surplus. The House 
would spend $1.74 trillion and raise $1.88 trillion for a $141 
billion surplus. The Senate would spend $1.74 trillion and raise 
$1.87 trillion for a $135 billion surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	--TAXES: Republicans would cut taxes next year by up to $15  
billion, and by $778 billion over the next decade. Clinton would 
cut taxes by $81 billion through 2009 but raise others -- chiefly on 
tobacco and businesses -- by $178 billion. Next year, he would raise 
some taxes by $15 billion and cut others by $4 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's tax cuts would be for child care, long-term health  
care, public school construction and other targeted purposes. 
Republicans have made no decisions but say they are considering 
reducing income-tax rates, taxes on some married couples, and other 
reductions. 
</P>
<P>
	--SOCIAL SECURITY AND MEDICARE: Neither side proposes revamping  
either program's revenues or benefits, which many experts say will 
be needed to prepare for the baby boomers' retirements beginning in 
a decade. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton would set aside about $1.65 trillion in Social Security  
surpluses over the next decade for debt reduction, which is 
supposed to strengthen the economy and make it easier for the 
government to raise money to pay benefits. He also would place 
Treasury bonds into the Social Security trust fund, which he says 
would extend the trust fund's solvency for decades. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans would leave all $1.8 trillion in Social Security  
surpluses envisioned for the next decade for debt reduction. That 
is more than Clinton, though he would set aside more than them over 
15 years. Both sides say the money would be available should 
bipartisan deals emerge to overhaul either program. 
</P>
<P>
	--DEFENSE AND DOMESTIC PROGRAMS: Clinton would spend $281 billion  
next year for defense, compared to $289 billion by Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton proposed $67 billion for education and job training, the  
same as Senate Republicans and $2 billion more than House 
Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton would spend $25 billion for natural resources and  
environment, $3 billion more than Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton would spend $27 billion for law enforcement, $3 billion  
more than Republicans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
