<HEADLINE> Feds To Probe Cop Brutality Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Attorney General Janet Reno says the Justice  
Department will investigate allegations of police brutality, but 
she defended cops confronted with the split-second decision of 
whether to open fire. 
</P>
<P>
	Reno's comments during her regular weekly news conference came  
in response to questions about the department's investigation into 
a fatal shooting by four New York City police officers and her 
meeting Thursday with several police organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	Reno did not directly address allegations of excessive force and  
poor judgment against the officers who shot and killed an unarmed 
African immigrant last month. 
</P>
<P>
	She did, however, defend police facing unpredictable  
confrontations on the street. 
</P>
<P>
	``When to shoot and when not to shoot is one of the most  
difficult decisions in some circumstances that anybody could 
make,'' Reno said. 
</P>
<P>
	The police groups and Justice Department officials discussed the  
New York case as an example of the need for better relations 
between police and minorities, said Jim Pasco, executive director 
of the national Fraternal Order of Police. 
</P>
<P>
	At her press conference, Reno would not say whether she will go  
to New York to investigate the killing of Amadou Diallo, as civil 
rights leaders have requested. 
</P>
<P>
	She also refused comment on how New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani  
has handled the case and on the continuing public outcry. 
</P>
<P>
	Giuliani has defended the department since the Feb. 4 shooting  
at Diallo's Bronx home. Four white officers looking for a rape 
suspect fired 41 bullets at Diallo, who was black, and hit him 19 
times. 
</P>
<P>
	A source close to the case said Thursday the officers have been  
charged with second-degree murder. Spokespersons for New York 
police and prosecutors declined comment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
