<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Stocks Finish Week Up / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar rose against the yen today amid  
uncertainty about the Yugoslavian situation as buying was promoted 
by Japanese institutional investors. The Tokyo Stock Exchange's 
main index continued to rise. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average added 30.95 points,  
or 0.19 percent, closing the week at 16,016.99. On Thursday, the 
index rose 470.57 points, or 3.03 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 118.76 yen in the late afternoon, up 0.90 yen  
from late Thursday in Tokyo and also above its late New York level 
of 118.13 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	For much of today's trading in Tokyo, the dollar stayed in a  
narrow range as Japanese investors adjusted positions ahead of the 
weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	But the U.S. currency shot up late in the afternoon as Japanese  
banks covered their short, or oversold, dollar positions amid 
uncertainty about the situation in Yugoslavia, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO aircraft and missiles blasted targets in Yugoslavia  
Thursday for a second day, directing much of their fire on Kosovo 
where fighting raged between Serbs and ethnic Albanians. 
</P>
<P>
	Allied leaders said the airstrikes would continue until Yugoslav  
President Slobodan Milosevic signs up to an internationally 
supervised peace agreement in Kosovo which has been accepted by 
ethnic Albanians. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. currency is often considered a safe haven in times of  
international turmoil. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said another positive factor for the dollar was concern  
that Japanese financial authorities may intervene in the foreign 
exchange market to stem the yen's rise. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar ranged between 117.97 yen and 118.96 yen in today's  
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 128.78 yen, up from  
128.16 yen late Thursday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, there was strong buying interest from  
foreign and individual investors early in the session following an 
overnight 169.55-point gain in the Dow Jones industrial average. 
The Dow Jones average closed Thursday at 9,836.39. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said, however, that profit-taking and position  
adjustment among investors ahead of the weekend were capping the 
market's upside. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the exchange's first section was estimated at 532  
million shares, down from Thursday's 663 million shares. Despite 
the Nikkei's advance, retreating issues outnumbered advancers 633 
to 568, with 107 issues unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 11.95 points, or 0.94 percent, to 1,267.78. 
The TOPIX posted a 22.34-point, or 1.81 percent, gain the day 
before. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the new benchmark No. 211 10-year Japanese  
government bond fell to 1.815 percent from Thursday's finish of 
1.880 percent, driving its price up to 99.87 yen from 99.31 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
