<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 10:02:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Days for an Old Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Mutual-fund investing has come a long way since  
the days of Naumkeag Steam Cotton, Farr Alpaca and the Lowell 
Bleachery Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Those long-forgotten names were three of the 46 stocks in the  
portfolio when the oldest fund of them all, MFS Investment 
Management Inc.'s Massachusetts Investors Trust, was launched with 
$50,000 of capital in 1924. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, as it marks its 75th anniversary, the fund is 240,000 times  
its original size, with assets of more than $12 billion invested at 
last report in 143 stocks. It has 54 younger brother and sister 
funds of all descriptions in the Boston-based MFS family, together 
encompassing almost $100 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	And MFS (the initials originally stood for Massachusetts  
Financial Services), though quite successful, doesn't come close in 
size to some of the competitors that grew up alongside it. The 
biggest fund family, run by Fidelity Investments in Boston, boasts 
assets of $700 billion-plus. 
</P>
<P>
	In its style and strategy, Massachusetts Investors Trust, or MIT  
for short, hasn't changed very much over the decades. It still 
invests with a relatively conservative approach, in the sort of 
well-established companies that Wall Street calls ``blue chips.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One stock that appeared in MIT's original portfolio -- General  
Electric Co. -- also shows up in the latest published list of the 
fund's largest holdings, as of Dec. 31, 1998. At its launching, MIT 
owned five GE shares worth around $1,161. Today, the fund's GE 
position, representing 1.7 percent of a $12 billion portfolio, has 
a market value of around $200 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, what strikes an observer most about a comparison  
between MIT's first portfolio and the stocks it owns today isn't 
the similarities but the differences. They reflect, in microcosm, 
the dramatic ways in which the economy has changed in only two or 
three generations' time. 
</P>
<P>
	MIT's original portfolio contained stocks in three main  
classifications -- railroads and railroad equipment; public 
utilities and ``industrial and miscellaneous.'' In addition, the 
fund owned two stocks in the bank and insurance category: Three 
shares of the Boston Insurance Co. and five shares of Springfield 
Fire &AMP; Marine Insurance. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, financial services makes up the largest stock category in  
the MIT portfolio, accounting for 18.7 percent of assets. The next 
biggest, health care at 14.7 percent, wasn't even considered an 
industry in the early decades of the 20th century. Ditto for 
technology, which represents 10.6 percent of the modern MIT 
portfolio. 
</P>
<P>
	Where today MIT holds big positions in Microsoft and IBM, the  
original portfolio contained shares of enterprises like American 
Radiator, National Lead and Baldwin Locomotive. 
</P>
<P>
	For geographical diversity, the original MIT portfolio relied on  
entities like the Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway Co., the 
Canadian Pacific Railway, and the Texas Co., later to be known as 
Texaco. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, the fund has between 5 percent and 10 percent of its  
money invested in international stocks, though it professes still 
to take a very cautious approach to venturing overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	Says John D. Laupheimer Jr., the present-day portfolio manager,  
in comments published on MFS's World Wide Web Site at www.mfs.com 
(something else the fund's founders surely never envisioned): ``We 
only invest overseas if we find a company that we believe has the 
quality and growth potential equivalent to those of a U.S. company 
and whose stock is selling at a discount sufficient to compensate 
for currency risk.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Amid all the financial progress and upheaval, MIT has amassed a  
strong performance record. Over the past 10 years, according to the 
research firm Lipper Inc., MIT's class A shares have climbed 476.74 
percent, to rank in the top 5 percent of funds tracked by Lipper 
over that stretch. 
</P>
<P>
	A Web site interview recently asked, ``What will the next few  
years hold in terms of how MFS invests and how MIT is managed?'' 
Laupheimer replied: ``It is my hope that there will be little 
change.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 19:52:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 76ers' Iverson Out With Leg Injury </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Allen Iverson, the NBA's leading scorer,  
missed the Philadelphia 76ers' game Friday night against the Boston 
Celtics with a right leg injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Iverson, averaging 28.6 points per game, has a contusion of the  
right quad and is listed as day-to-day. 
</P>
<P>
	Iverson injured himself last Friday against the Los Angeles  
Lakers. Although he played all three games during Philadelphia's 
recent West Coast swing, the injury was aggravated and he was 
forced to miss his first game of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Iverson's backcourt mate Eric Snow also missed the game with a  
sore left hamstring. Philadelphia lost to Boston 90-84. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 12:15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CT Scans Can Check Heart Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Ordinary hospital CT scanners can be  
equipped to snap stop-action pictures of the heart, offering a new 
way of detecting dangerously clogged arteries many years before 
they cause trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	Fatty buildups in the heart's arteries begin in early adulthood,  
but often there is no sign of damage until a heart attack strikes 
in middle age or beyond. 
</P>
<P>
	However, these deposits frequently contain calcium that shows up  
on CT scans. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent years, super-fast CT scanners have been introduced to  
take freeze-frame cross-sectional X-rays of the beating heart. On 
these pictures, fatty deposits show up as white lumps of calcium. 
</P>
<P>
	These specialized machines, called electron beam CT scanners,  
cost about $2 million, and about 50 are installed in hospitals and 
imaging centers across the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, researchers say they have figured out a way to rig up the  
much more common CT scanners found in virtually every hospital so 
they will do the same thing. 
</P>
<P>
	The idea, which involves combining a CT scanner with an EKG  
machine, was developed by Dr. Christopher Woodhouse of Mount Sinai 
Hospital in Miami Beach. The technology was further advanced by Dr. 
Jeffrey Carr and others from Wake Forest University, who presented 
their findings Friday at a medical conference in Orlando sponsored 
by the American Heart Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Carr compared ordinary CT with electron beam CT in 36 patients.  
He found their power to detect calcium in the heart's coronary 
arteries was virtually identical. 
</P>
<P>
	``This should make a difference'' by allowing calcium scanning  
to become much more routinely available, said Dr. Peter Wilson of 
the long-running Framingham Heart Study in Framingham, Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	During every beat, the heart contracts and squirts blood through  
the arteries. Then it rests and refills before contracting again. 
</P>
<P>
	Super-fast CTs are synchronized with the heart so they take an  
X-ray during the resting stage of every other beat. 
</P>
<P>
	About 10,000 ordinary CT machines are installed in hospitals  
across the country, and they shoot pictures more slowly. These 
machines are used to look at the liver, lungs and virtually every 
other part of the body. 
</P>
<P>
	Carr's group hooked patients up to electrocardiogram machines  
while they underwent CT scans of their hearts. The machine shoots a 
continuous stream of pictures, snapping 400 overlapping images in 
35 seconds. This creates a sort of X-ray movie of the heart. 
</P>
<P>
	Afterward, a computer reads the EKG information to select the  
pictures taken during the resting stage, when the heart is still, 
so doctors can look for traces of calcium. 
</P>
<P>
	In the examples shown by Carr, calcium stood out even more  
clearly in the ordinary CT scanners' pictures than it did in those 
shot with the super-fast scanners. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is an important breakthrough, but we still need to know  
more'' about how the scans compare with those taken with the 
super-fast machines, said Dr. Ronald M. Lauer of the University of 
Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	Super-fast scans typically cost between $200 and $400. Whether  
ordinary CTs will make this any cheaper is unclear. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Carr said the new approach should make calcium scanning  
much more available. 
</P>
<P>
	``With this technology, we will be able to finally do  
population-wide screening,'' offering CT scans routinely to people 
suspected of being at high risk of heart disease, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Many doctors believe that screening this way can find heart  
trouble in time to do something about it. People who have calcium 
buildups might be put on cholesterol-lowering drugs at an early age 
or persuaded to lower their blood pressure or quit smoking. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 15:25:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Huskies Enjoying Final Four Ride </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- Connecticut coach Jim Calhoun seems  
so comfortable, so relaxed and in his element at the Final Four, it 
hardly seems possible this is his first. 
</P>
<P>
	Has he practiced this act for the last 27 years? Is it all an  
out-of-character ruse to relax his Huskies before the biggest game 
of their lives -- Saturday's NCAA semifinal against Ohio State? 
</P>
<P>
	``It is the experience of a lifetime. You may not have this  
experience again,'' point guard Khalid El-Amin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nobody has to remind Calhoun of that.  
</P>
<P>
	Maybe it is the relief of getting UConn to the round of four  
after three previous failures in regional finals. Or maybe it is 
shedding the tag of the best team in college basketball never to 
get to the Final Four in 20 previous trips to the NCAA tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	But Friday, just before a spirited workout at Tropicana Field,  
the UConn players were asked if their coach might be ... too loose? 
</P>
<P>
	Calhoun, the man wound tighter than a baseball? He is such a  
chronic complainer that Big East Conference officials intentionally 
don't sit anywhere near him come tournament time. 
</P>
<P>
	``Well, I wouldn't say loose and lighthearted,'' El-Amin said.  
``He's definitely enjoyed making it to the Final Four, but he 
really wants to win the Final Four. He really wants to be a 
national champion. I think that's characteristic of a great coach 
or a competitive person.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Or a coach who's spent a lifetime being reminded that he never  
has been to the finals of the biggest tournament in college sports. 
</P>
<P>
	But while they're putting on a happy face in public, one of the  
messages being preached by the Huskies (32-2) is that this is a 
business trip, not a warm-weather weekend getaway. 
</P>
<P>
	Good idea, too. The Huskies would be well advised to do  
something with an opportunity that their fans -- among the most 
loyal and intense in college basketball -- wondered would ever come. 
</P>
<P>
	The Huskies are expected to reach the national championship game  
Monday against the other expected winner, Duke. It would be a No. 1 
vs. No. 2 showdown of the only two teams to be top-ranked this 
season. Anything less would be a disappointment. And disappointment 
is a word the Huskies are tired of hearing in March. 
</P>
<P>
	``People have talked about nothing but (UConn making the Final  
Four) since Saturday night when the Huskies defeated Gonzaga,'' 
Maryland coach Gary Williams said. ``Now that they have made it, 
they have to watch that there won't be a letdown.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There certainly weren't any letdowns in Final Four practices  
that the Huskies assert were as intense as any all season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our coaches have a game plan,'' center Jake Voskuhl said.  
``They do know what they're doing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During Friday's hourlong session, the competitive El-Amin  
pushed, poked and grabbed Richard Hamilton during a one-on-one 
defensive drill. In another drill, a ball he bounced high above the 
rim from half-court was caught by Edmund Saunders and dunked, 
drawing cheers from the 27,000-plus fans. 
</P>
<P>
	El-Amin offered the tough practices as evidence the Huskies  
aren't too relaxed. He also insisted they aren't looking past Ohio 
State, which already upset regional No. 1 seed Auburn and St. 
John's. 
</P>
<P>
	But, he said, ``We didn't come here to play one game, we came  
here to play two games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At 5:42 p.m. Saturday, they'll play the game Calhoun often  
wondered if his team would ever play. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been an awful lot of excitement, joy and happiness,''  
Calhoun said. ``Our kids have handled it wonderfully. I think we're 
very focused on what we have to do.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
