<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 23:31:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hill Wins 3 Soul Train Music Awards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Lauryn Hill, who won a record-setting five  
Grammy awards last month, took home three awards at the 13th Annual 
Soul Train Music Awards. 
</P>
<P>
	The hip-hop singer and rapper also shared the Sammy Davis Jr.  
Award for entertainer of the year with R. Kelly during Friday's 
awards. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Hill, 23, won best R&AMP;B/soul or rap album of the year for  
``The Miseducation of Lauryn Hill,'' which also won for best female 
R&AMP;B/soul album. Ms. Hill's ``Doo Wop (That Thing)'' captured best 
music video. 
</P>
<P>
	The Quincy Jones Award for career achievement was given to  
Luther Vandross. 
</P>
<P>
	In February, Ms. Hill won five Grammys, the first time a woman  
has done so. 
</P>
<P>
	The Soul Train winners were announced during a ceremony at the  
Los Angeles Shrine Auditorium. The list of winners: 
</P>
<P>
	Best R&AMP;B/soul single, female: ``Nobody's Supposed to be Here,''  
Deborah Cox. 
</P>
<P>
	Best R&AMP;B/soul single, male: ``Anytime,'' Brian McKnight.  
</P>
<P>
	Best R&AMP;B/soul single, group, band or duo: ``Too Close,'' Next.  
</P>
<P>
	Best R&AMP;B/soul album, female: ``The Miseducation of Lauryn  
Hill,'' Lauryn Hill. 
</P>
<P>
	Best R&AMP;B/soul album, male: ``R.'' R. Kelly.  
</P>
<P>
	Best R&AMP;B/soul album, group, band or duo: ``Phoenix Rising,'' The  
Temptations. 
</P>
<P>
	Best R&AMP;B/soul or rap album of the year: ``The Miseducation of  
Lauryn Hill,'' Lauryn Hill. 
</P>
<P>
	Best R&AMP;B/soul or rap new artist: ``Soul of a Woman,'' Kelly  
Price. 
</P>
<P>
	Best R&AMP;B/soul or rap music video: ``Doo Wop (That Thing),''  
Lauryn Hill. 
</P>
<P>
	Best jazz album: ``Gershwin's World,'' Herbie Hancock.  
</P>
<P>
	Best gospel album: ``The Nu Nation Project,'' Kirk Franklin.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
