<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Refuses To Cut Tyson Sentence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROCKVILLE, Md. (AP) -- Mike Tyson was turned down today in his  
bid to have his jail sentence in Maryland reduced from one year to 
eight months. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision means the earliest the former heavyweight champion  
could be released from jail is June. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a huge setback,'' Tyson lawyer Paul Kemp said.  
</P>
<P>
	Montgomery County Circuit Judge Stephen Johnson, who imposed the  
original sentence last month, said at today's hearing he still 
considers the sentence ``fair and appropriate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It is in the best interest of Mr. Tyson that his current  
treatment be maintained,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson, who had waived his right to attend the hearing, was  
brought to the Montgomery County courthouse before the hearing 
began. But jailers realized their error and immediately took him 
back. His wife, Monica, was present when the judge announced his 
decision. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson must still serve 60 days for violating probation for a  
1992 rape conviction in Indiana. 
</P>
<P>
	He is undergoing counseling, had a change in his antidepressant  
medication and is studying for a high school equivalency diploma in 
the Montgomery County jail. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson he is serving a one-year sentence after pleading no  
contest to misdemeanor assault charges in connection with a minor 
traffic accident in suburban Gaithersburg last August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 13:35:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hawks' Gray Arrested for DUI, Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Atlanta Hawks backup guard Ed Gray was charged  
with drug possession and driving under the influence after a state 
trooper stopped him for minor traffic violations. 
</P>
<P>
	The trooper stopped Gray's 1991 BMW about Thursday night near  
downtown Atlanta after noticing that the car's windows were tinted 
darker than state law allows and that his California tags had 
expired, spokesman Gordy Wright of the Georgia Department of Public 
Safety said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the trooper found less than an ounce of marijuana and an  
open container of alcohol in the car. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to drug possession and DUI, Wright said Gray was  
charged with driving with an open container and driving on a 
suspended and revoked license. Blood-alcohol tests were pending on 
the DUI charge, Wright said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hawks general manager Pete Babcock said the team can't take any  
action against Gray unless he is convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	``We take these issues extremely seriously,'' he said. ``We met  
with our team this morning and told them we'll support anybody who 
is in our family 100 percent with legal help, counseling, 
whatever's necessary. 
</P>
<P>
	``But if in fact any of our guys are found guilty of a  
misdemeanor or felony, we would take the harshest measure allowed 
by collective bargaining.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gray was a first-round draft pick of the Hawks in 1997. He spent  
part of his rookie season on injured reserve after breaking a foot. 
This season, he is averaging 4.5 points per game. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
