<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 03:14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Unsafe Rail Crossings To Be Listed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Three rail unions are urging their members to  
report dangerous railroad crossings in an effort to prevent crashes 
like the one that killed 11 Amtrak passengers last week in 
Illinois. 
</P>
<P>
	The unions eventually hope to map all rail crossings they  
consider unsafe. 
</P>
<P>
	``We intend to compile this information and let the political  
leadership in every state and in Washington know where the problem 
spots are located,'' said Charles Little, president of the 
125,000-member United Transportation Union. 
</P>
<P>
	The UTU and the 56,000-member Brotherhood of Locomotive  
Engineers, both based in Cleveland, and the 10,000-member 
Brotherhood of Railroad Signalmen, based in Mt. Prospect, Ill., 
announced the plan Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Little said the goal is to ``cut through the red tape and find  
quick and sound solutions to these problems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eleven people were killed and more than 100 injured March 15 in  
Bourbonnais, Ill., when an Amtrak train crashed into a truck 
carrying steel. 
</P>
<P>
	A Rail Crossing Task Force will have office space at the UTU  
headquarters, and rail workers will be urged to report dangerous 
crossings to the task force through a telephone hot line or e-mail. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 07:25:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
