<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fisher To Coach San Diego State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Steve Fisher, with one national title and two  
other Final Four appearances on his resume, will be San Diego 
State's new coach, The Associated Press has learned. 
</P>
<P>
	San Diego State called a news conference for 6:15 p.m. EST today  
to make the announcement. 
</P>
<P>
	Athletic director Rick Bay wouldn't comment other than to say,  
``I don't want to take the sizzle from the press conference.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fisher, an assistant with the NBA's Sacramento Kings, was  
expected to return to Los Angeles for tonight's game against the 
Lakers, a source familiar with the job search, said. 
</P>
<P>
	The hiring caps Bay's month-long search for a successor to Fred  
Trenkle, who resigned following a 4-22 season. Although Trenkle had 
losing records in four of his five years, he had the school's only 
winning season since its last NCAA tournament appearance, in 1985. 
</P>
<P>
	By comparison, Fisher was 184-82 at Michigan, and had a 20-6  
record in the NCAA tournament. San Diego State has made only three 
NCAA tournament appearances, never winning a game. 
</P>
<P>
	Fisher was fired by Michigan on Oct. 10, 1997, shortly after a  
Kansas law firm hired by the university issued a report that called 
into question his role in arranging complimentary tickets for a 
booster. The NCAA accepted the school's self-imposed penalties. 
</P>
<P>
	When asked about that incident Thursday night, Bay said:  
``People make their own judgment. Without having confirmed or 
denied that I've talked to Steve, if I would hire a coach, I would 
check everything out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fisher's tenure as Michigan's coach began almost as abruptly,  
when he was promoted on an interim basis on the eve of the 1989 
NCAA tournament after Bill Frieder accepted a job at Arizona State. 
</P>
<P>
	Michigan won the national title that year and Fisher had the  
interim label removed about three weeks later. Fisher coached the 
Wolverines to the title game in 1992 and 1993, losing both times. 
</P>
<P>
	Fisher returns to college ball on a six-game winning streak,  
having won his final regular-season game at Michigan in 1997, then 
leading the Wolverines to the NIT title. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
