<DOCNO> APW19990326.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 09:45:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rubin Criticizes GOP Tax Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin criticized  
Republicans today for planning to use large parts of expected 
federal surpluses for a tax cut, saying they would squander a 
chance to strengthen the economy and buttress federal retirement 
programs. 
</P>
<P>
	When asked by a reporter whether GOP tax-cutting plans were  
``going nowhere,'' Rubin responded: ``I know where I think they 
should go. The place where you suggested.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin spoke a day after the House and Senate approved similar  
GOP-written budgets for fiscal 2000 calling for $778 billion in tax 
reductions over the next decade. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin did not say President Clinton would veto a tax bill that  
large. But his comments underlined the administration's preference 
to use large parts of projected surpluses for more domestic 
spending and a far smaller tax cut. 
</P>
<P>
	``I do not think a tax cut contributes to our economic  
well-being,'' Rubin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the GOP plan would move in the ``precise opposite  
direction'' from needed debt reduction and help for Social Security 
and Medicare, Rubin said. 
</P>
<P>
	In competing budget plans, Clinton and Republicans both  
emphasize tax relief, helping Social Security and Medicare, and 
beefing up education and defense spending. But there's a wide chasm 
on major details, and each side insists it does more than the 
other. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite intense partisan debate Thursday in Congress, lawmakers  
of both parties were optimistic that some of gaps can be bridged in 
this new era of projected budget surpluses. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody pretty much agrees on where it ought to go,'' said  
Sen. James Jeffords, R-Vt. ``The difference is on how much goes 
where.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A few hours after the House passed its version of the GOP  
budget, 221-208, the Senate put the finishing touches Thursday 
night on a similar plan, 55-44. Both votes broke mostly along party 
lines. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans were triumphant, particularly in the House, where  
new Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., made passage of the budget his 
first major priority while dealing with a slender 11-seat edge over 
Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	Hastert said the GOP prescription actually saves more than  
Clinton proposed over 10 years for Social Security and Medicare, 
which are both in danger of insolvency as baby boomers age, and 
provides an unspecified tax cut of nearly $800 billion -- far more 
than the president's targeted tax relief. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have the largest surplus in history, which means the  
taxpayers are being overcharged,'' the speaker said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Clinton was quick to criticize the proposals as ``a series  
of missed opportunities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``While this budget marks a reversal from last year's failed  
effort by Republicans to drain the entire surplus for a tax cut, it 
still does not do enough to pay down the debt and strengthen Social 
Security and Medicare,'' the president said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Their exchange mirrored the debate that echoed through both  
sides of the Capitol all day Thursday. House and Senate Republicans 
will meet later this spring to produce a compromise budget, which 
sets tax and spending guidelines that will be filled in later in 
the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, the House plan for fiscal 2000, which begins Oct. 1,  
calls for $1.74 trillion in spending and forecasts a surplus of 
$141 billion. The Senate proposal projects spending of $1.74 
trillion and a $135 billion surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans want to cut taxes next year by up to $15 billion and  
by $778 billion over the next decade. While the budget outlines no 
specifics, Republicans have talked of such relief as eliminating 
the so-called marriage penalty, cutting income tax rates broadly 
and eliminating inheritance taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	By contrast, Clinton's budget envisions spending of $1.79  
trillion and would leave an $80 billion surplus. Clinton wants tax 
cuts totaling $81 billion through 2009, but he recommended 
increasing tobacco and other taxes by $178 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	In other areas, Clinton would spend $281 billion next year for  
defense, compared with $289 billion by Republicans. Senate 
Republicans matched Clinton's proposal for education and job 
training, exceeding the House total by $2 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's budget had scant support in either house of Congress --  
so little that the House buried it, 426-2, with one lawmaker voting 
present. The Senate rejected it Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Two Democratic alternatives were rejected in the House.  
</P>
<P>
	One called for smaller tax cuts than the GOP plan and more money  
for selected domestic programs. Supporters said it also would 
extend the life of Social Security until 2050 and of Medicare until 
2020. It failed on a vote of 250-173. 
</P>
<P>
	The second, crafted by a group of moderate to conservative  
Democrats, set aside more money than any other alternative for debt 
reduction and had the smallest tax cuts. It was rejected, 295-134. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Senate, Republicans defeated an effort by Sen. Edward  
Kennedy, D-Mass., to reserve 15 percent of the surplus for 
Medicare, as Clinton wants. 
</P>
<P>
	But Republicans pushed through a measure directing the Senate  
Finance Committee to consider a Medicare reform plan pushed by Sen. 
John Breaux, D-La., chairman of a Medicare commission that recently 
deadlocked. ``Let's quit talking about Medicare,'' said Senate 
Budget Committee Chairman Pete Domenici, R-N.M. ''Let's fix it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
