<HEADLINE> Jazz Legend Honored by Hometown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Nearly 45 years after his death, Charlie  
Parker is finally being embraced by his hometown. 
</P>
<P>
	A bronze sculpture of Parker is to be unveiled Saturday in the  
historic 18th &AMP; Vine District where Parker's saxophone wailed into 
the wee hours as he helped develop bebop in the 1940s. 
</P>
<P>
	Musicians, jazz scholars and family members of Parker are also  
gathering this week to pay tribute to Parker during a two-day 
symposium. Parker, who was born in bordering Kansas City, Kan., 
died in New York in 1955 at age 34. 
</P>
<P>
	Parker's family has said that he did not feel he was well  
received in his hometown until after he became famous elsewhere. 
Mayor Emanuel Cleaver said the tribute is a way to right a wrong. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kansas City has never really opened its heart to Charlie  
Parker, but we're trying to reverse that,'' Cleaver said Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
