<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Olympic Drug Tests Due This Summer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The first drug tests of American Olympic  
athletes by an independent agency are expected this summer, a top 
U.S. Olympic Committee official said. 
</P>
<P>
	USOC executive director Dick Schultz said Friday the committee  
had heard from nine companies that wanted to do the testing, which 
currently is handled by the Olympic panel and has been criticized 
for a potential lack of objectivity. 
</P>
<P>
	The list will be pared to 2-3 finalists, with the choice made in  
time for the first tests to be conducted by mid or late summer 
using International Olympic Committee-approved labs in Indianapolis 
and Los Angeles, Schultz said. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the companies also has drug-test connections with the  
NCAA, Schultz said, and chances remain that the USOC program could 
be run in conjunction with the college-sports authority and the 
NFL. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is something I feel strongly about and something that we  
have to move on at a good pace,'' he said in a telephone interview 
from his Colorado Springs office. 
</P>
<P>
	A USOC task force recommended last year that the testing of U.S.  
Olympic athletes for banned performance enhancers be removed from 
the committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The task force, headed by former executive director Baaron  
Pittenger, noted that no other national Olympic committee 
administered its own drug tests and that a change was needed to 
avoid the perception of conflict of interest. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very difficult in the international arena to have a high  
degree of credibility when you're running your own program,'' 
Pittenger said. 
</P>
<P>
	Schultz said the USOC was able to quickly set up an  
independent-testing program within existing rules, but that it 
would take longer to come up with new procedures for handling 
disputes and appeals. 
</P>
<P>
	For the time being, he said, existing rules will be used, with  
new ``checks and balances'' added for tests involving testosterone 
and other drugs where results are frequently challenged. 
</P>
<P>
	Schultz said he hoped to report on the status of the legal  
review process and cost of the new program at the USOC board of 
directors meeting in New Orleans next month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
