<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Orioles Defend Motive in Cuba Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Baltimore Orioles owner Peter Angelos denied  
that his team's game Sunday against the Cuban national team would 
lay the groundwork for recruiting future players. 
</P>
<P>
	Angelos, who was leaving for Havana on Friday, said the goal for  
the game was to seek normalization of relations between the two 
countries and a better standard of living for the Cuban people. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is important for all of us to open our minds and open our  
hearts to people of other countries. This is a wonderful thing that 
is happening throughout the world,'' he said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles will play Sunday in Havana. No major league baseball  
team has played in Cuba in 40 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Angelos, a wealthy lawyer and a major Democratic contributor,  
has been criticized by several Cuban-American political groups, and 
his team has been the target of demonstrations during spring 
training in Fort Lauderdale, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	But Angelos said most of the letters and calls he's received  
were positive. 
</P>
<P>
	The protesters, mostly members of the Cuban-American exile  
community, have complained that the game supports the government of 
Fidel Castro. But the pope's visit to Cuba last year demonstrated 
that the more contact, the better, Angelos said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know of anything that has ever been done for a  
constructive purpose that didn't generate controversy,'' Angelos 
said. ``Anything that departs from what is customary is going to 
generate a difference of opinion, but it's a worthwhile endeavor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baltimore director Barry Levinson is also going to Cuba with the  
Orioles with a documentary film crew. 
</P>
</TEXT>
