<DOCNO> APW19990326.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 14:25:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Investors Still Believe in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Sitting in a crowded seminar on China's  
economy, businessman David Fries listens carefully for hints that 
the world's most populous nation can fend off the economic turmoil 
that afflicts many of its Asian neighbors. 
</P>
<P>
	The question is a big one for Fries' company, Lubrizol Corp. of  
Wickliff, Ohio, which has launched two joint ventures in China to 
manufacture and market chemical additives for motor oil and other 
lubricants. 
</P>
<P>
	For Lubrizol, like dozens of other American companies, the vast  
potential market represented by Asia's growing population make it 
the place to be, even if financial trouble and the growing 
political tension between the United States and China could mean a 
rocky ride in the short run. 
</P>
<P>
	``It certainly worries us with the focus on delivery of  
quarterly results,'' said Fries, one of more than 300 business 
people and scholars who gathered at the University of Southern 
California this week for the annual Asia/Pacific Business Outlook 
conference. 
</P>
<P>
	``But most of the world's people are there, and my impression is  
it's only a matter of time until things will turn around and 
improve,'' said Fries, director of Lubrizol International 
Management Corp., the company's overseas business unit. 
</P>
<P>
	As the second anniversary of the economic crisis nears, American  
companies are again trying to get a greater foothold in Asian 
markets. U.S. investments in Asia rose during 1998 despite Asia's 
crisis. But Americans are more careful about where they put their 
money, with growth shifting from stocks to harder assets like 
factories, real estate and joint ventures for marketing and 
manufacturing. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. companies' direct investment in Asia -- money spent to buy  
foreign companies, establish overseas subsidiaries or enter joint 
ventures -- reached $14.9 billion in Asia during 1998. That's up 
more than $1 billion from the $13.8 billion invested during 1997, 
the year the crisis began, according to Department of Commerce 
figures. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Americans poured more than $10 billion into a new  
Asian market: the purchase of bad loans portfolios and distressed 
properties, primarily in Japan, Korea and Thailand, during 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Americans were less aggressive in Asian stock markets, but still  
were net buyers. They paid $7.4 billion for securities in Asian 
countries, down from $13.1 billion a year earlier and $16.9 billion 
in 1996, according to the Securities Industry Association. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest decline in stock investing was in Japan, where  
purchases fell to $3.6 billion in 1998 from $9.5 billion in 1997, 
according to figures compiled by the association, a trade group 
representing 750 companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest stock purchases went to countries that have fared  
relatively well through the crisis, such as Singapore, Taiwan and 
China, or those, such as Korea, Hong Kong and Thailand, where the 
crisis drove down prices far enough to create bargains. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, in 1997 U.S. investment in Hong Kong stocks fell to  
a net selloff of $139 million. Last year, Americans reversed 
directions and bought $974 million worth of securities. 
</P>
<P>
	``Selectively, Asia is still a good place to invest,'' said  
Denny F. d'Alelio, vice president for Asian business development at 
TRW Systems &AMP; Information Group. ``What you have to do is go back 
to the basics. You can't take any shortcuts. Do you have what the 
customer wants? Does the customer have the money to buy it?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Investment growth is likely to continue this year as markets  
recover and more countries are changing laws to encourage foreign 
ownership of businesses -- a dramatic change that could create big 
long-term opportunities for U.S. companies, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everywhere I turn around there are U.S.-based companies buying  
into markets that were previously closed to foreigners,'' said Jack 
Rodman, director of international business for E&AMP;Y Kenneth 
Leventhal Real Estate Group. ``This is a sea change in direction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asia's financial crisis began in July 1997 after Thailand  
devalued its currency. Within days, its neighbors followed suit, 
sending most of the region into deep recession. Underlying reasons 
for the crisis included overvalued currencies, banks overburdened 
by debt and heavy dependence on foreign loans. 
</P>
<P>
	Compounding the economic uncertainty are other problems.  
Financial systems in many Asian countries lack ``transparency,'' 
meaning it is difficult to get reliable information about a 
venture's real value and liabilities. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, interest among American companies is growing, said  
Baizu Chen, a USC economist specializing in Asia. When the 
professor began teaching the China seminar three years ago, 10 
people attended. A year ago there were 20. This week, about 40 
people crowded into Chen's classroom, while others listened from 
the foyer outside. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course, you have to be cautious,'' said Chen. ``But Asia  
eventually will come back. That's for sure. When it really comes 
back, it will be too late to get in. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 14:55:07 </DATE_TIME>
