<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T: No At Home-Road Runner Merger  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- AT&AMP;T-controlled At Home, a leading provider of  
high-speed Internet access over cable TV lines, doesn't plan to 
merge with rival Road Runner despite persistent rumors about such a 
deal, a top AT&AMP;T executive said today. Leo Hindery, president and 
CEO of AT&AMP;T Broadband and Internet Services, said: ``It's not on 
the table. It's not being discussed.'' He conceded that such a 
merger might make sense. AT&AMP;T recently acquired cable giant 
Tele-Communications Inc. and as a result, TCI's controlling stake 
in At Home, which also is owned by Cox Communications and several 
other investors. AT&AMP;T shares were at 83 1/16 up 1 3/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks End Lower; Dow Down 14.15  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices drifted lower today in sluggish  
trading as investors adjusted their holdings before the end of the 
quarter and kept an eye on NATO air strikes in Kosovo. The Dow 
Jones industrial average closed down 14.15 at 9,822.24. The 
blue-chip index was down 89 points in early trading before trimming 
most of its losses. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 7.19 to 
