<P>
	China Seeks WTO Membership Deal  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- China is holding out the tantalizing prospect  
of opening its huge market to American manufacturers, farmers and 
financial firms in return for membership in the World Trade 
Organization. Negotiations between the United States and China over 
WTO membership, which have proceeded in fits and starts over the 
past 13 years, have intensified in recent weeks even as anger over 
China's human rights record and alleged nuclear espionage have 
risen in Congress. Both sides are struggling to complete a deal 
that could be used as the centerpiece for a visit next month by 
Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji. 

</P>
<P>
	Woman Awarded $1.78M in Patent Suit  
</P>
<P>
	MISSOULA, Mont. (AP) -- A federal jury has awarded a Bigfork,  
Mont., woman $1.78 million, finding that Deckers Outdoors Corp. 
infringed on the patent for her Yeti cold-weather boots. Molly 
Strong and her company, Yeti by Molly Ltd., won their lawsuit in 
U.S. District Court in Missoula, Mont. Deckers, the maker Teva, Ugg 
and Simple brand footwear, plans to appeal the decision, which was 
handed down last week after a 10-day trial. 

</P>
<P>
	Safety of Diabetes Drug Reviewed  
</P>
<P>
	BETHESDA, Md. (AP) -- Federal officials said today they have  
linked 38 cases of acute liver failure to the diabetes drug Rezulin 
and believe the risk of liver problems grows over time as patients 
take the drug. In all, Food and Drug Administration officials have 
discovered 43 cases of acute liver failure among Rezulin patients, 
38 of which were probably caused by the medicine, the officials 
told a panel of scientific advisers weighing the drug's safety. Of 
those 43 people, seven had a liver transplant and survived, five 
survived without a transplant and 28 died. Officials did not know 
the outcome of the other three cases. 

</P>
<P>
	Tractor-Trailer Reflectors Required  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After years of study and debate, the  
government moved today to require that tractor-trailer trucks carry 
reflectors that outline the bottom edge of their trailers. The 
Federal Highway Administration said that the change should reduce 
the chance that a vehicle will smash into or drive under a trailer. 
The agency estimated the change will save more than 100 lives and 
prevent 1,700 injuries in the next decade. Since January 1, 1993, 
the government has required that the bottom edge on all new 
trailers be rimmed with red-and-white reflective tape or with 
so-called reflex reflectors, like the red plastic devices used on 
bicycles. 

</P>
<P>
	McDonald's Begins Selling Furbys  
</P>
<P>
	OAK BROOK, Ill. (AP) -- Furby and fries, please. McDonald's  
launched a Happy Meal promotion featuring one of the hottest toy 
sellers during last year's holiday season -- Furby -- hoping to enjoy 
the same success it has had with Teenie Beanie Baby promotions. 
Customers buying a children's meal will get one of 80 different 
varieties of Furby, an odd-looking creature that will either blink, 
wiggle its ears, growl or move its feet. Unlike the larger versions 
manufactured by Tiger Electronics, however, the McDonald's toy is 
not electronic and does not speak. 

</P>
<P>
	McDonald's Enters Coffee Bar Craze  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- McDonald's Corp. has moved to cash in on the  
explosive growth in British coffee bars. It has purchased Aroma 
Ltd., a chain of 23 shops that sell coffee concoctions and 
sandwiches in a lively atmosphere of recorded Caribbean music and 
bright yellow and orange decor. The deal, announced yesterday, is 
reportedly worth between $16 million and $24 million, and marks the 
first time McDonald's has ever invested in anything but a hamburger 
chain outside the United States. 

</P>
<P>
	First Union Helps Minority Business  
</P>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE (AP) -- First Union is putting $5 million into a fund  
that invests in minority-owned businesses, joining a partnership of 
major corporations started by Earl Graves, the founder of Black 
Enterprise magazine. The fund, Black Enterprise/Greenwich Street 
Corporate Growth Partners, recently received $86 million in 
commitments from other companies such as J.P. Morgan, Citigroup, 
IBM, Bell Atlantic and DaimlerChrysler. Graves once served as 
chairman and chief executive of Pepsi-Cola of Washington, D.C., the 
nation's largest minority-owned Pepsi bottler. 

</P>
<P>
	Iberia Airlines Pilots Strike  
</P>
<P>
	MADRID, Spain (AP) -- More than 50 Iberia airline flights were  
canceled today as the carrier's pilots began a planned eight-day 
strike that threatens to create havoc for travelers during the 
Easter holiday period. The flights canceled included 11 to Germany, 
Switzerland, Portugal and the Netherlands. The remainder were 
domestic flights, Iberia spokeswoman Consuelo Arias said. An 
agreement between the company and the Spanish Airline Pilots Union, 
SEPLA, will ensure that 95 percent of Iberia's roughly 800 daily 
flights will not be affected. The two sides met today in the 
dispute over delays in signing a new labor agreement. 

</P>
