<HEADLINE> Stocks Fall; Dow Down 47.45 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell today amid renewed investor  
uneasiness about the NATO air strikes in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	A bout of profit-taking also depressed prices as investors  
cashed in after Wall Street's latest rally. 
</P>
<P>
	At 11 a.m., the Dow Jones industrial average was down 47.45 at  
9,788.94, erasing more than a quarter of the Dow's 169-point climb 
on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were also lower this morning.  
</P>
<P>
	The market, whose advance Thursday came partly on relief about  
the military action in Kosovo, seemed to have a change of heart 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks fell after NATO aircraft and missiles blasted targets in  
Yugoslavia for a second night, directing much of their fire on 
Kosovo, where fighting continued between Serbs and ethnic 
Albanians. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors worried today about what could transgress over the  
weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of the people who believed that one or two air strikes in  
Kosovo would solve our problems over there are having second 
thoughts,'' said Alan Ackerman, senior vice president at Fahnestock 
&AMP; Co. ``Now many people are concerned with whether or not we will 
have to commit ground troops.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Profit-taking also sent stocks lower. Just last week, the Dow  
traded above 10,000 for the first time, and for the year, the 
blue-chip index is up about 7 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	While stocks fell today, bond prices rose as investors,  
concerned about the situation in Kosovo, sought the safety of U.S. 
Treasurys. The yield on the Treasury's 30-year bond fell to 5.54 
percent from 5.58 percent late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 7.92 at 1,282.07, and  
the technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index was off 6.67 at 
2,428.13. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 9-to-5 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 214.83 million 
shares, down from 262.37 million shares on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was down 3.75 at 601.11, and the  
American Stock Exchange composite index was down 1.16 at 712.56. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.19 percent. In  
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 1.7 percent, 
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 1.1 percent, and France's CAC-40 was 
down 0.7 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
