<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nestle Net Profit Up 2.6 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VEVEY, Switzerland (AP) -- Swiss food giant Nestle SA's group  
profit rose 2.6 percent in 1998, beating analysts' estimates. 
</P>
<P>
	Nestle reported today it earned 4.29 billion Swiss francs, or  
$3.15 billion, up from a revised 4.18 billion francs for 1997. The 
1997 figure was previously reported as 4.0 billion francs. 
</P>
<P>
	Many analysts expected net profit of between 3.8 billion francs  
and 4 billion francs, based in part on the company's sales slump 
late last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales amounted to 71.7 billion Swiss francs, or $52.72 billion,  
for 1998 versus 70 billion francs in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Nestle products include Nestle Quik chocolate drinks, Taster's  
Choice coffee, Carnation condensed milk, Libby foods and Alpo pet 
food. 
</P>
<P>
	Nestle said it maintained profits by rapidly adapting to last  
year's volatile conditions in many markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Operating profit last year was 7.1 billion francs, up slightly  
from a restated 1997 operating profit of 7.057 billion francs, 
which the company reported originally as 6.88 billion francs. 
</P>
<P>
	For 1999, the company expects more volatile business conditions,  
but higher profit and sales. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said it had revised 1997 figures due to an  
accounting change which uses the historical value system for 
amortization of tangible fixed assets rather than replacement value 
accounting. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman said Nestle used replacement value accounting when  
many countries had high inflation rates. It decided to change back 
to the historical system used by most companies because many 
economies now have much lower rates of inflation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
