<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Owens Corning Can't Bar Lawsuits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- A judge has ruled that supposed physiological  
differences between races should not prevent black plaintiffs from 
suing Owens Corning over the health effects of asbestos. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for the company had argued that because blacks score  
consistently lower on tests to determine lung capacity, they should 
have to meet a higher standard to prove asbestos caused lung 
damage. 
</P>
<P>
	But Circuit Judge Joseph H.H. Kaplan on Thursday reversed a  
guideline he wrote in 1992 that established who was eligible to 
sue. 
</P>
<P>
	The plaintiffs, many of them former steelworkers and shipyard  
workers, claim they have diminished lung capacity because of their 
exposure to asbestos contained in fiberglass made by Owens Corning. 
</P>
<P>
	A lawyer for the plaintiffs said the company's argument about  
differing lung capacity was based on phony science. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't apply a different standard to the races,'' said  
Peter Nicholl. ``You're talking about the fundamental right to have 
access to the courts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Owens Corning stopped manufacturing products containing asbestos  
in 1972. Since then, the company has been hit with hundreds of 
thousands of lawsuits from people who worked with products 
containing asbestos and developed a lung disease called asbestosis. 
The disease shrinks the lungs, among other symptoms. 
</P>
<P>
	Last December, the company announced a $1.2 billion settlement  
resolving about 176,000 cases. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1992, Kaplan set guidelines to cope with the 12,000 asbestos  
cases filed in Baltimore's courts. He wrote that predicted lung 
test values ``shall be corrected for race or ethnic origin as 
appropriate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But after hearing testimony from medical experts, Kaplan decided  
there was no reason to use a different medical standard for whites 
and blacks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not convinced of the validity of race correction for this  
purpose,'' Kaplan concluded. 
</P>
<P>
	Owens Corning spokeswoman Tricia Ingraham and defense attorney  
Steve Vaccaro declined comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Owens Corning based its argument largely on a 1991 report by the  
American Thoracic Society, the medical branch of the American Lung 
Association, that found blacks consistently score lower on 
pulmonary function tests. The Lung Association declined to comment 
further on the 1991 report Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Paul Epstein, a pulmonary specialist with the University of  
Pennsylvania, testified on the company's behalf that scientific 
data shows whites and blacks have different lung capacities. 
</P>
<P>
	But Dr. Stephen Zimmen, a pulmonary specialist in Virginia who  
testified for the plaintiffs, said there are a number of other 
factors more important than race in determining someone's lung 
capacity, such as age, height, gender, socioeconomic conditions and 
nutrition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
