<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> B-2 Bomber Pilots Happy To Be Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KNOB NOSTER, Mo. (AP) -- The pilots who flew the B-2 stealth  
bombers in Yugoslavia -- their first use in combat -- were happy with 
the jet's performance after traveling for 31 hours straight to 
deliver their payload. 
</P>
<P>
	``This first use of the B-2s in combat has got every heart on  
the base thumping and pride swelling across this entire state and 
across the nation,'' said Gen. Leroy Barnidge, commander of the 
509th Bomb Wing at Whiteman Air Force Base, 50 miles east of Kansas 
City. 
</P>
<P>
	Two decades after its conception as a highly sophisticated  
stealth bomber, America's B-2 got its first taste of combat this 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	Four B-2s flew 13 hours -- with several refuelings in the air --  
to reach their targets. They spent a few hours in the target area 
before returning home unscathed. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were nervous going in, as you would be on the first time  
a new weapon system is used in combat, just like the F-117 pilots 
were nervous in the Gulf War,'' said Rep. Norm Dicks, D-Wash. ``But 
they're back and it's a great team effort.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dicks, a member of the House Appropriations Committee, has  
supported billions of dollars in military spending for the B-2 
bomber. 
</P>
<P>
	Each bat-winged, radar-evading plane carried 16 one-ton weapons  
for hits on targets such as command bunkers and air-defense 
systems, according to a senior defense official who spoke on 
condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	The official said the B-2 was selected because of its ability to  
attack many targets and its heavy payload. The F-117 Stealth 
bomber, also used in the fighting, carries only two bombs. 
</P>
<P>
	With only a pilot and co-pilot aboard, the B-2 also puts fewer  
crewmen at risk than the B-52, which unleashed cruise missiles from 
launch points outside Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Dicks said the pilots were upbeat and relieved to be back  
safely. One returned from the trip Thursday morning and mowed his 
lawn that afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	``He came home and his wife said, `You've got to mow the lawn,'  
and he did,'' Dicks said with a grin. ``I thought that was very 
funny.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
