<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 17:52:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NHL Draft Expanded to Two Days </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CALGARY, Alberta (AP) -- The young stars who will guide the NHL  
into the new century will be unveiled in Calgary in 2000 -- with a 
new twist. 
</P>
<P>
	The NHL announced Friday that Calgary was selected ahead of six  
other cities to stage the 2000 entry draft. And with NHL expansion 
swelling membership to 30 teams by then, the event will be held 
over two days for the first time ever. 
</P>
<P>
	``It takes a lot longer to conduct a draft than it did back at  
the turn of the decade when we had 21 teams,'' said Frank Supovitz, 
NHL vice president of special events. ``It's sheer arithmetic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Atlanta Thrashers begin play in 1999-2000, one year ahead of  
both the Columbus Blue Jackets and Minnesota Wild. The addition of 
the three means 30 franchises will participate in the nine-round 
draft June 24-25, 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	The first three rounds will be held June 24. The remaining six  
rounds will go the following day. 
</P>
<P>
	The NHL also announced it will hold the 2000 expansion draft in  
Calgary the day before the entry draft. That will allow both 
Columbus and Minnesota to stock their rosters with experienced 
players. 
</P>
<P>
	The NHL's announcement Friday is a big deal considering the top  
hockey officials and prospects will all be gathered in Calgary. The 
economic impact of the draft to the Alberta city is estimated at 
more than $5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The annual entry draft has turned into a bonanza since its  
humble beginning in 1963, when it was held at the Queen Elizabeth 
Hotel in Montreal and only 21 players were chosen. 
</P>
<P>
	This will mark the second time the draft has been held in  
Alberta. Edmonton staged the '95 event. 
</P>
<P>
	This year's entry draft will be held in Boston on June 26.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
