<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Saint Louis Hires Basketball Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Lorenzo Romar has earned a reputation as a top  
recruiter. On Friday, after being introduced as Saint Louis' 
basketball coach, Romar seemed intent on landing a 59-year-old 
recruit. 
</P>
<P>
	``I spoke to Charlie Spoonhour this morning,'' Romar said. ``I  
hope that he continues to stay close to this program.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Spoonhour, who retired March 5, was 122-90 in seven seasons at  
Saint Louis. He led the Billikens to three NCAA tournament 
appearances and one National Invitation Tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I was at UCLA (as an assistant coach), I developed a  
relationship with John Wooden,'' Romar said. ``I'd love to be able 
to do the same thing with Charlie Spoonhour. He made this 
program.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Spoonhour, through a combination of his on-court success and  
homespun humor, remains a popular figure in St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	In three years as coach at Pepperdine, Romar took a struggling  
program and turned it around. The Wave were 10-18 the year before 
Romar arrived. He went 6-21 his first year, but followed that with 
17-10 and 19-13 seasons. This year's team earned a berth in the 
NIT, losing to Colorado in the first round. 
</P>
<P>
	But Saint Louis officials and players seemed equally as  
impressed with Romar's work as an assistant under Jim Harrick at 
UCLA. Romar was credited with helping to recruit players such as 
Toby Bailey, Cameron Dollar and Charles O'Bannon, the core group of 
the 1995 national championship team. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully he can take us to the next level,'' guard Troy  
Robertson, who was part of the search committee, said. ``They say 
that recruiting is 75 percent of your program. His recruiting 
speaks for itself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Los Angeles Times reported that Romar will earn about  
$400,000 annually, including shoe and television-radio deals. Romar 
reportedly made about $125,000 at Pepperdine. 
</P>
<P>
	Romar, 40, played at Cerritos (Calif.) Community College and  
Washington, before beginning his pro basketball career with Golden 
State, where he played from 1980-1983. 
</P>
<P>
	Romar finished his NBA career with the Milwaukee Bucks in 1984,  
then joined Athletes in Action. He became player/co-coach of 
Athletes in Action in 1989 and continued in that capacity until 
joining Harrick's staff at UCLA in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	``This, to me, is a coach's dream,'' Romar said. ``I said it  
would take something pretty special to make me leave Malibu.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Saint Louis was 15-16 this season under Spoonhour.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
