<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Bombings Worry Soccer Players </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MADRID, Spain (AP) -- Yugoslav soccer players, many of them stars  
for top European clubs, are questioning whether they should play 
during the NATO bombing of their homeland. 
</P>
<P>
	Pedrag Mijatovic of Real Madrid said that if he had a game in  
the next few days, ``I wouldn't be able to play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He stressed he and his compatriots are not calling for a strike  
or boycott but want to draw attention to their country's plight. He 
said each player must decide for himself how to act. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, the Yugoslav soccer federation was reported to have  
backed a call by Mijatovic, Dragan Stojkovic of Japan's Grampus 
Eight and Dejan Savicevic of Yugoslavia's Red Star, urging Yugoslav 
players in NATO member-nation clubs to strike. 
</P>
<P>
	On returning to Madrid on Thursday following the cancellation of  
Yugoslavia's European qualifier against Croatia because of the 
conflict, Mijatovic said: 
</P>
<P>
	``Together with our federation we have to help our compatriots.  
Right now, I couldn't concentrate on a soccer game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I have seen the bombs fall, I have seen the fear in people,''  
he added. 
</P>
<P>
	Any such protest could severely affect clubs across Europe,  
particularly in Spain and Italy, where some 20 Yugoslav players 
play. But on Friday few players appeared determined to strike. 
</P>
<P>
	Dozens of Yugoslavs also star for western European clubs in  
other sports, particularly basketball and handball. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm worried for my parents. ... I have not taken any decision.  
I will discuss it with my teammates,'' Dejan Stankovic of the 
Italian soccer team Lazio told a radio station. 
</P>
<P>
	In England, Sheffield Wednesday's Dejan Stefanovic was reported  
to be considering a boycott. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, two Yugoslav handball stars, Nenad Perunicic and  
Goran Stojanovic, who play for Germany's Kiel, said they'd miss the 
German cup final because they are trying to go home to see their 
relatives. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the Yugoslav soccer players who returned to Spain on  
Thursday were open about their feelings. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clearly in life there are priorities. The bombing continues  
and neither I nor my companions are in condition to play soccer,'' 
Tenerife's Slavis Jokanovic told the newspaper El Pais. 
</P>
<P>
	Referring to his family in the Yugoslav town of Novi Sad,  
Jokanovic said: ``They are filled with fear. But they know they are 
right. 
</P>
<P>
	``My people have their ideas, in Spain you have yours, which  
come from the United States and, as they are the most powerful, 
they're (considered) right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Veljko Paunovic, who plays for Mallorca, was equally critical.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't understand it. They (NATO) are punishing a country  
that is fighting terrorists just as Spain fights ETA,'' he said, in 
reference to Spain's conflict with the armed Basque separatist 
group that has killed nearly 800 people in its bid for 
independence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
