<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton Maintains Military Style </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As he guides the U.S. role in the NATO  
airstrikes on Yugoslavia, President Clinton is not hunched in a war 
room, surrounded by maps and stern generals in uniform. 
</P>
<P>
	His preferred setting is the Oval Office, with foreign policy  
advisers in business suits -- and at least one in uniform -- settled 
back on yellow sofas. He's not drawing ``a line in the sand'' as 
President Bush did with Iraq. 
</P>
<P>
	With no military experience, Clinton avoids the image of the  
saber-rattling commander-in-chief. 
</P>
<P>
	``The style seems to be to bring the two sides together, then  
carry a big stick,'' said John Mueller, a University of Rochester 
political scientist who has written about presidents and war. ``The 
hope is that the threat would be enough. That works fine if they 
capitulate. If they don't, you're left with the dilemma of using 
the stick or looking foolish.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the assault two days old, the president had a videotaped  
message beamed into Yugoslavia by satellite and sent on the 
Internet Friday. That tactic -- friendly words for a nation's people 
while military action is focused against its leader -- is one 
Clinton has used before, with Iraq. 
</P>
<P>
	This time, Clinton also had Secretary of State Madeleine  
Albright -- whose father was a Czech diplomat in Belgrade prior to 
World War II -- deliver a message in the Serbs' own language. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hello. I am glad to have this opportunity to speak directly to  
the people of Serbia at this critical time,'' she said. ``As you 
can see, I remember a little Serbian, albeit with a Czech accent. 
... '' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton is the first president in a half-century to lack a  
military background. He seemed uncomfortable about that during his 
first term, even going to the lengths of taking lessons in saluting 
from former National Security Adviser Tony Lake. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because of his lack of experience and because he is the first  
of the post-World War II, Vietnam-generation presidents, he has 
tended to be more deferential to military points of view than 
others,'' said Ivon Daalder, who served as the National Security 
Council's director of European affairs during Clinton's first term. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has not been willing to take on the military, even if it  
was evident that doing so may have served his purposes, foreign 
policy and otherwise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But when delivering a sensitive foreign policy message, such as  
his address to the nation from the Oval Office earlier this week, 
Clinton doesn't simply recite the lines his security experts hand 
him. He constantly reworks the texts. 
</P>
<P>
	During his first term, Clinton oversaw U.S. intervention in  
Somalia, where 18 soldiers died, and oversaw the humiliating 
withdrawal of American forces. He sent troops to Haiti in a 
successful mission to reinstate elected President Jean-Bertrand 
Aristide, then passed off command to a multinational peacekeeping 
force. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, there were the airstrikes over Bosnia. There were no  
American fatalities. 
</P>
<P>
	Well into his second term, Clinton is more at ease. Last fall,  
he ordered airstrikes on Afghanistan and Sudan in retaliation for 
bombings at American embassies in Kenya and Tanzania. There have 
been several flare-ups with Iraq, and earlier this year nearly 
daily bombings on Iraqi sites. 
</P>
<P>
	As commander-in-chief, Clinton is ``detail oriented,'' said  
David Leavy, spokesman for the National Security Council. ``He asks 
a lot of questions and demands a lot of answers. He has made clear 
that he wants to be briefed on any and all important developments. 
He wants to think two or three moves down the chessboard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In times like these, aides say, Clinton is a hands-on manager --  
but not so hands-on that he feels he should select bombing targets 
as Lyndon Johnson sometimes did during the Vietnam War. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
