<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Peterson Leads Michigan State Bench </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- He's the team's leading scorer. He's  
all-Big Ten. Morris Peterson can do it all for Michigan State. He 
just can't start. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's all about what's best for the team,'' Peterson said  
Friday. ``We all check our egos at the door. That's what makes us 
successful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Spartans (33-4) have won 22 straight games to reach the  
Final Four for the first time in 20 years. But if they want to 
match the national championship of Magic Johnson's 1979 team, 
they'll have to beat top-ranked Duke (36-1) in the semifinals 
Saturday night at Tropicana Field. 
</P>
<P>
	Through their 37 games, the Spartans' bench has averaged 26.5  
points, outscoring the opponents' reserves 982-553. In their 
comeback win over Kentucky in the Midwest Regional, the Spartans 
bench had a 35-27 edge over the Wildcats. 
</P>
<P>
	The key is Peterson, the only sixth man in the Big Ten to earn  
first team all-conference honors. Peterson is averaging 13.5 points 
and is second on the team in rebounding, averaging 5.6 per game. 
</P>
<P>
	So why doesn't he start?  
</P>
<P>
	``Because I think it's what's best for the team,'' coach Tom  
Izzo said before putting the squad through practice. ``He's an 
exceptional player. He can play maybe four positions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Plus, he brings such instant offense to our team. There are  
times we just need that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No kidding.  
</P>
<P>
	The Spartans' offense frequently shuts down for minutes at a  
time. They needed seven free throws over the final 44 seconds to 
hold off Oklahoma 54-46 to advance to the regional finals. They 
fell behind Kentucky, 17-4, but Peterson, who had 19 points and 10 
rebounds, hit six straight free throws in the final 29 seconds to 
seal a 73-66 comeback win. 
</P>
<P>
	He was selected outstanding player of the Midwest Regional for  
that effort. 
</P>
<P>
	``We depend on our bench players,'' said point guard Mateen  
Cleaves, the team's charismatic leader. ``Other teams, they hope 
their bench is going to come in and play well. We depend on ours to 
do that -- to pick us up, to play defense and to score some big 
points for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Duke beat the Spartans 73-67 in the Great Eight in Chicago. That  
was back in December, but the Blue Devils remember that Peterson 
scored 24 points against them. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not sure if it's because he's fresher, or if he helps the  
team's flow,'' Duke forward Elton Brand said. ``But he really 
sparks that team. We're going to have to be very aware of him when 
he comes in, because he's a great player.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Because he has eight players averaging 15 or more minutes a  
game, Izzo is confident his team will be strong to the very end. It 
is one reason the Spartans have won six games by five points or 
less. 
</P>
<P>
	And it's why Izzo isn't afraid of Duke.  
</P>
<P>
	``There's probably been bigger upsets than Michigan State  
against Duke,'' Izzo said. ``But I don't lie to our guys. If they 
don't play their `A' game, there's not many teams that can beat 
Duke. Our job is to see that THEY don't play their `A' game.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
