<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 14:25:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CBS To Sever Online Sportsbook Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- In response to concerns raised by  
the NCAA, an Internet company partially owned by CBS will sever 
ties to an online sportsbook. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will continue to support the NCAA's aggressive  
anti-gambling efforts,'' CBS spokeswoman LeslieAnn Wade said 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	A day earlier, NCAA executive director Cedric Dempsey had  
expressed unease over broadcast partner CBS' ties to 
Sportsbook.com, a popular Web site that takes offshore bets on the 
NCAA tournament. With the TV contract running through 2002, Dempsey 
said the NCAA could do little to force the network's hand. 
</P>
<P>
	``But as we look toward renewing a contract, or negotiating a  
new one, any relationship to gambling would certainly influence our 
thinking,'' Dempsey said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wade said CBS was unaware of the relationship between Sportsline  
USA, a Fort Lauderdale, Fla.-based Internet company that produces 
the CBS Sportsline site and Sportsbook.com. 
</P>
<P>
	Sportsline USA president Michael Levy confirmed that his company  
leased the Sportsbook.com Web site address -- known as an URL, or 
universal resource locator -- to a gambling operation run by Global 
Internet, a company based in the Caribbean. Although CBS owns a 20 
percent stake in Sportline USA, Levy said he was uncertain whether 
he had informed his corporate partner of the lease. 
</P>
<P>
	Dempsey said even though the connection to CBS was distant, the  
NCAA was sensitive to the appearance of impropriety. The 
organization has been rocked by point-shaving and gambling scandals 
in recent years, including the indictment of Northwestern 
basketball players on the eve of last year's Final Four. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this week, NCAA officials threw their support behind a  
U.S. Senate bill designed to limit gambling on the Web. 
</P>
<P>
	Wade said once the network became aware of the connection  
between its internet operation and Sportsbook.com, CBS took 
immediate action to sever it. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sportsline USA has assured CBS that the URL currently leased  
to Sportsbook.com will be sold,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked for a time frame, Wade replied, ``It's imminent.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
