<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Knowing When To Buy and Sell Stock / On the Money  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- As the stock market fluctuates and paper profits  
roll in and out, investors may be wondering whether they should 
sell or keep certain shares. Knowing how to pick and choose can be 
a challenge. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you do not have seasoned tools -- which most people don't --  
in order to gauge the market in good and bad times, it becomes 
important to stick to the fundamentals,'' said A.C. Moore, chief 
investment strategist for Dunvegan Associates in Santa Barbara, 
Calif. ``We like to associate with issues that have an inherent 
value. 
</P>
<P>
	``That value will see an investor through turbulent times.''  
</P>
<P>
	The ``fundamentals,'' which market watchers look for, are the  
basic tenets of a company, like its business objectives, management 
team, products and investment strategies, along with its earnings, 
market share and standing within an industry. In other words: what 
makes it tick. 
</P>
<P>
	Good fundamentals are often reflected in a company's stock  
price, but that's not always the case. Sometimes, a stock can get 
caught up in market frenzy, rising and falling based simply on 
emotion or other factors that have little to do with how a company 
is performing. 
</P>
<P>
	The stock market can be a fickle place, as was evidenced  
recently with the Dow Jones industrial average. The blue-chip index 
crossed over the milestone 10,000 mark on three separate days last 
week, but in each case retreated before the day was done. 
</P>
<P>
	A similar scenario occurred about nine years ago: The Dow  
briefly crossed a then-record 3,000 twice in mid-July 1990, but 
didn't actually close above that level until mid-April 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	Average investors, therefore, should avoid ``timing'' the  
market, or trying to profit from short-term fluctuations in share 
prices. That's something best attempted by professionals using 
sophisticated ``technical'' analysis. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got to be willing to accept short-term ups and downs if  
you want to be there for the long-term,'' said Larry Elkin, a 
financial consultant from Hastings-on-Hudson, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	At some point, though, it may be prudent, or necessary, to sell  
a stock. You may simply need the money -- so, why not collect a tidy 
profit from a rising issue? Changing investment objectives also 
must be considered. 
</P>
<P>
	Another reason to sell is because a company's business has  
deteriorated, and that can be due to changing fundamentals. 
</P>
<P>
	There may be new management or lower profits because of poor  
sales or economic conditions. A company also may come under 
pressure because of a crippling legal liability, or an entire 
industry may get into trouble due to unfavorable market trends. 
</P>
<P>
	One piece of bad news is often followed by more, so it's  
important for investors to keep current on media and professional 
analysts' reports. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial advisers say it's usually better to bite the bullet  
and sell if a company is consistently underperforming, and most 
prefer to give a stock at least 12 weeks from the time it was 
purchased before making a move. After all, hefty losses can drag 
down overall performance of a portfolio for years. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the American Association of Individual Investors,  
when a stock drops 10 percent, investors will need an 11 percent 
gain from another stock to break even. With a 50 percent loss, the 
break-even point rises to a 100 percent gain, it says. 
</P>
<P>
	``When picking stocks, the first thing you need to do is decide  
what your downside loss to aggregate profit is going to be. How 
much can you afford to lose?'' said Hank Madden, who runs a 
financial consulting firm from Jacksonville, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	Diversifying can help dilute the losses. Madden advises clients  
to keep between 12 to 15 different stocks in their portfolio, and 
each issue should represent no more than 15 percent of the 
portfolio's value. 
</P>
<P>
	The price-earnings ratio, which is a stock's current market  
price divided by the company's earnings per share for the past 12 
months, should also be watched. A high ratio indicates investors 
are expecting strong future earnings, while a low ratio usually 
means less optimism. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore says many stocks these days have a higher than normal  
price-earnings ratio, which he believes shows the stock is 
overpriced and has room to fall. Ironically, some Internet stocks, 
which have been soaring in price in recent months, actually have no 
price-earnings ratios since the companies have yet to post a 
profit. And that also makes many financial advisers nervous. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore says he's staying away from the Internet bubble,  
preferring ``staple'' companies, like food processors, grocers and 
distributors. 
</P>
<P>
	And he says he's taking in stride all the recent the ups and  
downs of the Dow and Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
