<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Players Championship Notebook  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- A sore hip and a bad round forced  
John Daly out of The Players Championship on Friday, a far 
different scene than when he withdrew after a drinking binge in 
1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Daly dropped out before the second round began. He shot an  
11-over-par 83 in the opening round Thursday and appeared headed 
for an early exit either way. 
</P>
<P>
	His left hip has been bothering him since the PGA Tour began its  
swing through Florida earlier this month. 
</P>
<P>
	``He first injured his hip at Doral,'' said Daly's agent, John  
Mascatello. ``It flared up again at Honda. He took off Bay Hill 
because he wanted to be rested for TPC.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The strategy didn't work, so Daly opted to visit the athletic  
trainer at the University of Arkansas, where he played college 
golf, for further treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	Mascatello didn't think the injury would force Daly to miss the  
Masters. Still, there was no sense in playing another round when it 
seemed clear he would not make the cut here. 
</P>
<P>
	It was two years ago that Daly withdrew from the Players after  
an all-night drinking session during which he damaged his hotel 
room and was hospitalized for chest pains. 
</P>
<P>
	A former British Open and PGA champion, Daly has finished no  
higher than 14th in seven events this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, he had only two top-10 finishes. His most lasting  
image came in the Greater Vancouver Open, when he burst into tears 
and began shaking during the opening round. He said it was a result 
of his continuing battle with alcoholism. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *DUVAL HOT STREAK:* Each year, this is one of Bob Duval's  
toughest decisions. 
</P>
<P>
	Does he stay near home to watch his son, David, in the Players,  
or does he travel west to play in the Emerald Coast Classic, the 
senior-tour event in Pensacola? 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Duval decided to travel and was rewarded by shooting a  
career-low, 9-under-par 61 in the first round at the Moors Golf 
Club. The round was one stroke off the senior tour record. 
</P>
<P>
	``How about that, he took me by eight,'' David Duval said after  
a round of 69 left him in second place. ``I don't think the golf 
course is as hard, though.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dad also has some work to do to catch David Duval's record-tying  
59 in the Bob Hope Classic in January. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *JOE'S CADDIE:* Drake Oddy doesn't understand everything the  
Japanese-speaking Joe Ozaki says. 
</P>
<P>
	He does, however, understand the second-round leader's game and  
American golf courses. That's how he landed a part-time gig as 
Ozaki's caddie for tournaments in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once he came over here on tour full-time, he needed someone  
who understood the differences between California, Arizona and 
Florida -- the different grasses and things you run into,'' Oddy 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The two hooked up in 1993 after Oddy spent about five years on  
Mark Calcavecchia's bag. 
</P>
<P>
	Ozaki plays between 15 and 20 tournaments in the United States  
each year, enough to ensure he keeps his PGA card. He returns to 
Japan for another 12 or so. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Ozaki dropped Oddy for his first few events in the  
United States, opting for a Japanese caddie who helped him to a hot 
streak in the Far East at the end of 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Ozaki shared the lead in the Players after the first two rounds,  
but ended up finishing 18th. Later in the season, he re-upped with 
Oddy. 
</P>
<P>
	``The caddies in Japan are really more willing to go with  
whatever the player says,'' Oddy said. ``If the player says, `It's 
210 yards over water, it's into the wind, is an 8-iron OK?' They'll 
say, OK. I don't say much, unless it's really obvious. But we talk 
a lot about yardages.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *LOOSE BRUCE:* Maybe Bruce Lietzke has the right idea.  
</P>
<P>
	Every few weeks, he packs up the golf bag, heads to the Dallas  
airport and travels to the upcoming PGA tour site for a couple 
rounds of golf. 
</P>
<P>
	If he happens to play well, he makes a few thousand dollars, but  
he claims that's almost incidental. 
</P>
<P>
	``For me, it's mostly a self-motivational deal,'' said Lietzke,  
who shot a 68 to finish at 5-under, two strokes behind Ozaki. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't really play golf to impress other people,'' he said.  
``I try to find out what I'm capable of doing myself. I love 
getting into a position like this, pulling off good shots, getting 
into positions to win tournaments.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He hasn't won since 1994, but then again, he hasn't been killing  
himself. 
</P>
<P>
	Lietzke, 47, played in 10 tournaments last year and earned  
$377,000. His best finish was second in the Bob Hope Classic. 
</P>
<P>
	The year before, he played in nine events. He hasn't played as  
many as 20 tournaments since 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	He isn't known to practice too hard.  
</P>
<P>
	``My golf game doesn't seem to change a bit,'' Lietzke said.  
``My swing and my short game are consistent week in, week out. I 
seem to play better when I'm mentally fresh and I'm usually pretty 
mentally fresh.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *STEWART-LYNX:* Payne Stewart can get rid of that bag he bought  
at the golf store. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart, whose contract with Top-Flite was not renewed this  
year, wound up going to an Edwin Watts golf store to buy a bag. He 
used it when he won at Pebble Beach in February for his first 
victory in four years. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, Stewart said he was in no rush to sign a deal.  
Still, it didn't take long. 
</P>
<P>
	Under a three-year contract he signed with Golfsmith  
International Inc., the former PGA and U.S. Open winner began using 
a Lynx golf bag Friday. He should be carrying a newly designed set 
of forged-blade irons in the next few months. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've enjoyed my greatest success with a traditional  
forged-blade clubhead design,'' Stewart said. 
</P>
<P>
	He'll continue to use his Mizuno irons until the design on the  
Lynx set is perfected. 
</P>
<P>
	The signing was part of Golfsmith's effort to bring Lynx back  
into the forefront after buying its assets last year following the 
company's filing for Chapter 11 bankruptcy. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SHARK TANKED:* Greg Norman headed the list of notables to miss  
the cut. He shot a 5-over 77 and finished the day at 5-over 149, 
missing the cut by one stroke. 
</P>
<P>
	Other notables to miss the cut included U.S. Open champion Lee  
Janzen. Tim Herron, who won at Bay Hill last week, also missed, as 
did the player he beat in a playoff, Tom Lehman. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *DIVOTS:* Bob Friend aced the par-3 eighth hole to mark the  
second straight day the TPC Stadium Course has given up a 
hole-in-one. Joey Sindelar aced the par-3 17th island hole 
Thursday. ... Fulton Allem got off to a sizzling start, going 
eagle-birdie-eagle-birdie on Nos. 2-5. He shot a 67 and finished at 
1-under. ... For the second straight day, Brian Henninger asked the 
volunteer carrying the score placard to remove his score from the 
display. He shot back-to-back 79s and missed the cut with a score 
of 14-over. ... First-round co-leaders Bob Estes and Brian Watts 
each shot 74 to finish at 2-under. 
</P>
</TEXT>
