<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets closed mixed Friday as  
Japanese shares ended higher but other exchanges stumbled. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tokyo, strong overnight gains on Wall Street supported the  
225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which rose 30.95 points, or 0.19 
percent, to close the week at 16,016.99. On Thursday the index had 
gained 3.03 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Australian shares closed at an all-time high, driven by a strong  
rise in telecommunications and resources stocks, particularly oil 
and gold. The All Ordinaries index closed at 2996.6, up 9.7 points, 
or 0.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, shares closed marginally lower, pulled down by  
selling in shares of property companies that recently reported poor 
profits. The blue-chip Hang Seng Index shed 22.82 points, or 0.21 
percent, to close at 10,803.31. On Wednesday, the Hang Seng had 
gained 1.1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	On currency markets, the dollar bought 118.92 yen at  
midafternoon, up 1.06 yen from late Thursday in Tokyo and also 
above its late New York level of 118.13 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai shares ended mixed in light directionless trading  
ahead of the government's announcement of new economic stimulus 
measures. The benchmark SET index ended up 0.3 percent, or 1.21 
points, to 366.91 points. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian shares closed lower on continued  
profit-taking despite approval from the International Monetary Fund 
for a further loan. The JSX Composite Index closed down 2.881 
points, or 0.7 percent, at 392.948. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian shares ended mixed, with the benchmark  
index closing a hair higher. The Composite Index rose 1.02 points, 
or 0.2 percent, to 500.16 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine shares rebounded, driven by bargain hunting  
after Wall Street's overnight rally. The PSE index fell 22.80 
points, or 1.1 percent, to 2,022.07. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: South Korean shares closed marginally lower, with many  
investors on the sidelines due to the yen weakening against the 
dollar. The Kospi index dropped 1.28 points, or 0.2 percent, to 
close at 609.79. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Shares closed generally lower with the benchmark  
index falling below the key 1,500-point level. The Straits Times 
Index fell 2.87 points, or 0.2 percent, to end at 1,497.50. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Taiwan shares closed higher for the second straight  
session on speculation that commodity prices are headed higher. The 
Weighted Price Index rose 91.87 points, or 1.32 percent, to 
7,033.25 . 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand stocks finished slightly higher,  
underpinned by strength in brewing concern Lion Nathan Ltd. The 
NZSE-40 capital index gained 8.50 points, or 0.4 percent, to close 
at 2123.16. 
</P>
</TEXT>
