<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Angelos: No Ulterior Motive in Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Owner Peter Angelos again insisted that his  
Baltimore Orioles' exhibition against the Cuban national team in 
Havana on Sunday is not meant to pave the way for future player 
recruitment. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've said from the outset that there was never an ulterior  
motive -- just a free exchange between the people of the two 
countries,'' Angelos told The (Baltimore) Sun for a story in 
today's editions. ``The notion that this initiative will somehow 
give the Orioles an advantage recruiting Cuban players in the 
future is more born of cynicism than fact.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No big league baseball team has played in Cuba in 40 years.  
</P>
<P>
	Angelos, who was to leave for Havana today, said the goal for  
the game was to seek normalization of relations between the two 
countries and a better standard of living for the Cuban people. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawyer and major Democratic contributor has been criticized  
by several Cuban-American political groups, and his team has been 
the target of demonstrations during spring training in Fort 
Lauderdale, Fla. But Angelos said most of the letters and calls he 
received were positive. 
</P>
<P>
	The protesters, mostly members of the Cuban-American exile  
community, have registered the complaint that the game supports the 
government of Fidel Castro, he said. But the pope's visit to Cuba 
last year demonstrated that the more contact, the better, Angelos 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know of anything that has ever been done for a  
constructive purpose that didn't generate controversy,'' Angelos 
said. ``Anything that departs from what is customary is going to 
generate a difference of opinion, but it's a worthwhile endeavor.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
