<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Spring Could Be Special for MSU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- Beaches around the Tampa Bay area  
are packed with college kids on spring break. Mateen Cleaves and 
some of his Michigan State pals are here, too. 
</P>
<P>
	But they're not here primarily for sun and fun. They're here to  
win a national championship. 
</P>
<P>
	The Spartans arrived at the Final Four on Thursday and got  
comfortable in the team hotel on Sand Key, off the coast of 
Clearwater Beach. That's about a 40-minute drive from Tropicana 
Field, but it might as well be 40 light years away. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is nice,'' senior guard Thomas Kelley said as he watched  
the sun go down over the Gulf of Mexico. ``You could get used to 
this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Girls in cutoffs and bikini tops walked by. They smiled,  
obviously aware that these were basketball players. And even if 
they weren't, the dark green T-shirt with ``St. Petersburg, Final 
Four'' on the front would have tipped them off. 
</P>
<P>
	The Spartans (33-4), who are in the Final Four for the first  
time in 20 years, play top-ranked Duke (36-1) on Saturday night at 
Tropicana Field. On their way, they won the Big Ten championship, 
the Big Ten tournament and an NCAA regional title. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, they know the Blue Devils are a formidable foe. If the  
Spartans are to have a chance, coach Tom Izzo feels Cleaves will 
have to be at his best. 
</P>
<P>
	Michigan State fell behind Kentucky 17-4 in St. Louis last  
weekend, but a long 3-pointer by Cleaves just before the half got 
the Spartans to within a point and they took control in the second 
half. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've always felt it was important to have someone quarterback  
your team and be somewhat of an extension (of the coach),'' Izzo 
said. ``Once the game starts, even though we can make adjustments, 
there's things a guard does on the floor that I just don't think 
you can do from the bench.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cleaves didn't become an extension of Izzo overnight. Still,  
during his three years of playing for Izzo, they have found a way 
to become friends. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can call him up at three in the morning,'' Cleaves said. ``I  
can just say, `I can't sleep right now, I need somebody to talk 
to.' And that's the kind of guy he is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	They are active in community affairs in East Lansing. They feed  
the homeless together, visit children in hospitals, and drive out 
to counsel young offenders in a prison near the campus. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's helped me grow up as a person,'' Cleaves said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
