<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Begins More Airstrikes  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- American-led NATO forces launched a third  
night of airstrikes against Yugoslavia today, targeting Serb 
military sites with air-launched cruise missiles and U.S. stealth 
fighter jets, the Pentagon said. Belgrade radio said NATO was 
hitting numerous targets in the Yugoslav capital Belgrade's suburbs 
in what appeared to be the strongest attack so far. The NATO attack 
began with cruise-missile-equipped B-52 bombers leading the 
assault. Also in the mix were F-117 stealth fighter jets equipped 
with laser-guided munitions. 

</P>
<P>
	Fighting Rages in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	UNDATED (AP) -- Yugoslav forces were reportedly targeting ethnic  
Albanians today in Kosovo in retaliation for the NATO airstrikes. 
The rebel Kosovo Liberation Army said fighting continued throughout 
the province, with reports of more than 30 killed in ``mass 
executions.'' Thousands of ethnic Albanians were also being used as 
human shields, forced to march into a military factory in the 
central town of Srbica, it said. Kosovo refugees told the U.N. 
refugee agency that 20 men were shot to death by Serb forces as 
they evacuated the Kosovo border village of Goden yesterday. 

</P>
<P>
	Anti-NATO Protests Target Embassies  
</P>
<P>
	ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- Protesters opposed to NATO attacks on  
Yugoslavia directed their anger at American sites around Europe 
today, drenching olive branches in red dye and calling President 
Clinton a ``fascist.'' Up to 10,000 people in Bulgaria gathered in 
the nation's capital of Sofia to protest the NATO airstrikes. In 
Greece, a NATO member, 15,000 protesters marched to the U.S. 
Embassy. The U.S. and British embassies in Moscow were also the 
scene of demonstrations. And riot police blocked demonstrators 
trying to reach the American Embassy in Skopje, Macedonia. 

</P>
<P>
	Kevorkian Convicted of Murder  
</P>
<P>
	PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) -- Dr. Jack Kevorkian was convicted of  
second-degree murder today for giving an ailing man a lethal 
injection and putting it all on videotape. Kevorkian, 70, could get 
a life term at sentencing April 14 for the death of 52-year-old 
Thomas Youk, who suffered from Lou Gehrig's disease. Prosecutor 
David Gorcyca said he believes sentencing guidelines call for a 
minimum of 10 to 25 years on the murder charge. Kevorkian also was 
convicted of delivery of a controlled substance, which carries up 
to seven years. 

</P>
<P>
	Pastor Found Guilty in Gay Marriage  
</P>
<P>
	DOWNERS GROVE, Ill. (AP) -- A Methodist minister who officiated  
at the ``marriage'' of two gay men was convicted in a church trial 
today of disobedience in the first test of the denomination's ban 
on same-sex ceremonies and could be defrocked. The jury of 13 
pastors decided 10-3 that the Rev. Gregory Dell disobeyed church 
law when he presided over the ``holy union'' of the Chicago men 
last September. Immediately after the verdict, the penalty phase of 
the trial began. 

</P>
<P>
	Baby Born From Dead Father's Sperm  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- In the first known birth of its kind, a woman  
in California has had a baby using sperm that had been extracted 
from her dead husband. Gaby Vernoff, who is in her 20s, gave birth 
to the girl on March 17. Ms. Vernoff was impregnated in July with 
sperm that been taken from her husband, Bruce, 30 hours after he 
had died suddenly of an allergic reaction. 

</P>
<P>
	CBS To Sever Online Sportsbook Ties  
</P>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- In response to concerns raised by  
the NCAA, an Internet company partially owned by CBS will sever 
ties to an online sportsbook. A day earlier, NCAA executive 
director Cedric Dempsey had expressed unease over broadcast partner 
CBS' ties to Sportsbook.com, a popular Web site that takes offshore 
bets on the NCAA tournament. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Falls 14.15 to 9,822.24  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices drifted lower today in sluggish  
trading as investors adjusted their holdings before the end of the 
quarter and kept an eye on NATO air strikes in Kosovo. The Dow 
industrials closed down 14.15 at 9,822.24. Declines on the NYSE 
beat advances 1,609-1,358. The Nasdaq finished at 2,419.17, down 
15.63. 

</P>
<P>
	Serena Beats Hingis in Lipton Match  
</P>
<P>
	KEY BISCAYNE, Fla. (AP) -- Serena Williams overcame a slow start  
today to beat top-ranked Martina Hingis and advance to the final of 
the Lipton Championships, where she awaited a possible matchup with 
her older sister, Venus. Williams beat Hingis 6-4, 7-6 (7-3). 
Defending champion Venus Williams, 17, will play five-time Lipton 
champ Steffi Graf tonight. A victory by Williams would result in 
the first all-sister women's final in the Open era, which began in 
1968. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by JEROME MINERVA  
</P>
</TEXT>
