<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baltimore Students Depart for Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAVANA (AP) -- Within hours after landing on Cuban soil, about  
100 American students hit the ball field, teaming against Cuban 
kids their own age as a kind of warmup to Sunday's exhibition 
between the Baltimore Orioles and a Cuban national team. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's great out here,'' said Clarence Collier, 11. ``The kids  
who play baseball here are really challenging.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The students from the Baltimore-Washington area arrived in  
Havana on Thursday on a plane chartered by Baltimore Orioles owner 
Peter Angelos. With the exception of more than 400 foreign 
correspondents, they will be among the few foreigners to watch the 
exhibition match in person. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be great. I have loved baseball longer than I  
can remember,'' said Jimmy Petrila, 12, of Washington D.C., whose 
parents paid for his trip. ``And the Orioles are definitely my 
favorite team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As for the Cubans, only those who receive invitations will be  
able to attend, the government confirmed on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though it had not been announced yet by Cuba's  
government-controlled media, the news was spreading Thursday 
throughout government workplaces, schools, parks, and along 
Havana's famous seawall, the Malecon. 
</P>
<P>
	``There will be no sale of tickets at the stadium,'' said  
Reinaldo Calviac, director of the International Press Center. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said invitations probably would go to organizations  
such as schools and sports clubs. 
</P>
<P>
	In a city as baseball-mad as Havana, such invitations will be  
highly coveted. 
</P>
<P>
	The rustic Latinoamericano stadium built in 1946, where Sunday's  
game will be played, holds 50,000 fans. 
</P>
<P>
	It will be the first time in 40 years that a major league team  
has played in Cuba. Big leaguers used to come to the island 
regularly before the 1959 revolution that brought Fidel Castro to 
power. 
</P>
<P>
	Because it is only an exhibition game, Cuban officials are  
downplaying its importance. 
</P>
<P>
	``The most important game, the most interesting games right now  
in Cuba are our playoff games,'' Juan Gomez, coach of the hometown 
favorites, the Industriales, said Wednesday night before his team 
beat Isla de Juventud to earn a spot in the final. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the Sunday match between the Orioles and the Cubans is a  
big deal for the American kids. 
</P>
<P>
	``For our four days here we are going to see some of the most  
exciting things that baseball has to offer,'' Jim Mauro, president 
of the Northwest Washington Little League, said Thursday as the 
kids played on a sandlot near the Plaza of the Revolution. 
</P>
<P>
	Soon, they were already getting a sense of what Sunday's game  
might be like. 
</P>
<P>
	``The kids here play a more exciting kind of baseball,'' Petrila  
said. ``In the United States, people swing for the fences. Here 
there are a lot of bunts and stealing. It is a more strategic kind 
of playing, like Ty Cobb in in the 1940s.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After getting last-minute federal approval March 19 to take his  
team to Cuba, Angelos sent word to area schools and recreation 
leagues that he would provide a plane for 100 youths and up to 50 
chaperones. By Sunday, 50 youths had been signed up by parents who 
could afford the $750 per person. 
</P>
<P>
	Organizers saved the rest of the seats for students who would  
have trouble affording the fee. Angelos pledged $12,500 and other 
donors chipped in about $5,000. 
</P>
<P>
	While the American youngsters praised their Cuban counterparts,  
the Cubans had kind words for their new friends as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just feel great to be able to play for the first time  
against the Americans,'' said 11-year-old catcher Jorge Luis Coury, 
who wore his baseball cap backwards. ``They're pretty good.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
