<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former Ill. Detectives Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Two former Cicero detectives were arrested Friday  
on federal racketeering conspiracy charges for allegedly accepting 
thousands of dollars to fix police investigations. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Biziarek, 52, and Darlene Sobczak, 42, were picked up a  
day after a federal grand jury returned a five-count indictment 
charging them with a series of shakedowns. Both defendants pleaded 
innocent and were released on bond. 
</P>
<P>
	The charges carry sentences as long as 30 years in prison and  
fines up to $1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``Federal law enforcement has zero tolerance for police officers  
who betray their oath and prey upon citizens whom they are sworn to 
protect, whether victims or those accused of crimes,'' U.S. 
Attorney Scott Lassar said. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal agents have long been investigating allegations of  
official corruption in Cicero, a gritty blue-collar community of 
factories and semi-trailer parks just west of Chicago. At one time 
it was the heart of Al Capone's bootlegging empire. 
</P>
<P>
	The indictment alleges Biziarek and Sobczak solicited and  
accepted extortion payments totaling at least $13,800 from nine 
people to fix Cicero police investigations. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal agents said they believe the two former officers gained  
as much as $80,000 through corrupt activities. 
</P>
<P>
	Biziarek left the force in 1997; Sobczak in 1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
