<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cubs Closer Rod Beck Pitches Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MESA, Ariz. (AP) -- Rod Beck was up, down and out of the ballpark  
in his first trip back to the mound. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chicago Cubs closer, who's been sidelined with a protruding  
disc in his lower back, pitched Friday for the first time since 
March 5. He came in at the top of the sixth inning and promptly 
gave up a homer to Steve Finley. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was a little wild,'' Beck said. ``I hadn't been out there in  
(three) weeks, and it's hard to just go out and paint the corners. 
Although I expected to. But expectations are always greater.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Beck, who converted 51 of 58 save opportunities last season to  
become only the fifth reliever in the majors to reach 50 saves, 
pitched one inning. He gave up two runs -- all earned -- and three 
hits. 
</P>
<P>
	He also hit Travis Lee in the shoulder, a toss that led to a  
bench-clearing brawl in the bottom of the sixth. The Diamondbacks 
went on to win 17-10. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was just trying to put the fastball inside. I wasn't trying  
to hit him,'' Beck said. ``I've got no reason to hit anybody in 
spring training.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Beck said he also was a little wild in a simulated game and  
bullpen workouts earlier this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not a wild pitcher,'' he said. ``So that will come.''  
</P>
<P>
	There were no problems with the back, and Beck said he'll be  
fine for opening day. His biggest concern now is getting enough 
work. He'll rest Saturday and pitch again Sunday, going every other 
day for the rest of spring training. 
</P>
<P>
	He'll pitch two innings in one game, and the rest will be  
one-inning outings. Bumping one of those up to two would be great, 
Beck said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're running out of time,'' he said, ``and I've got to get in  
what I can get in.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
