<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Mixed in Quiet Trading / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Treasury securities were little changed Friday  
as investors assessed the escalating tensions in the Balkans and 
several huge corporate bond sales. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 1/16  
point, or 63 cents per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves 
in the opposite direction, rose to 5.59 percent from 5.58 percent 
late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	But shorter-maturity Treasuries edged up Friday as uncertainties  
surrounding the third day of NATO air strikes on Yugoslavia 
encouraged some investors to seek the safety of U.S. government 
bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	Bonds also received support as gold fell below $280 a troy  
ounce, a sign that inflation remains tame. 
</P>
<P>
	Hurting Treasury prices was several big corporate-backed bond  
sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Citigroup, the giant financial services company, led corporate  
sales Friday with $1.5 billion of global bonds. ImperialTobacco 
Group Plc, which manufactures cigarettes under brand names such as 
Embassy, Regal, and Lambert &AMP; Butler, sold $600 million of 10-year 
notes. 
</P>
<P>
	Some $16 billion of corporate bonds were sold this week,  
including AT&AMP;T Corp.'s record $8 billion sale. That's the highest 
weekly total since early January. More than $3 billion in new 
corporate bonds is expected next week. 
</P>
<P>
	Investment banks often sell Treasuries when they underwrite  
corporate debt to protect against losses in case interest rates 
rise before the sales are completed. They usually buy the 
government securities back later. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
rose 1/16, while intermediate Treasury securities rose between 3/32 
and 1/8 point from Thursday, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial 
information service. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lehman Brothers Daily Treasury Bond Index, reflecting price  
movements on bonds with maturities of a year or longer, rose 0.21 
point to 1,282.90. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.50 percent, while  
the discount was unchanged from Thursday at 4.39 percent. Six-month 
yields were 4.52 percent, as the discount fell 0.02 percentage 
point to 4.36 percent. One-year yields were 4.70 percent, while the 
discount fell 0.03 percentage point to 4.48 percent from late 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, fell to 4.50 percent from 5.13 percent Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 1/16 to 124 23/32. The average yield to 
maturity was rose to 5.20 percent from 5.19 percent on Thursday. 




</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
