<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 15:54:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lewinsky Juror Ends Public Comments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After breaking her silence, the forewoman of  
the federal grand jury that investigated the Monica Lewinsky affair 
abruptly announced today she won't speak any more about the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Freda Alexander made the announcement through her lawyers, who  
said she made her comments Thursday to several news outlets without 
their knowledge. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal grand jury process is designed by law to be  
conducted in secret, and grand jurors rarely ever talk about their 
activities. 
</P>
<P>
	There are indications that U.S. District Judge Norma Holloway  
Johnson, who oversaw the Lewinsky grand jury, might be upset over 
Ms. Alexander's comments. 
</P>
<P>
	Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr met privately with the judge  
about the matter Friday, according to a source familiar with the 
meeting who would not be identified by name. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Alexander told The Associated Press on Thursday that she  
believed President Clinton behaved badly in his personal life, and 
she would have voted to indict him for perjury if prosecutors had 
asked her to. 
</P>
<P>
	She also expressed sympathy with Clinton and believed his  
personal failings should not have become public or led to his 
impeachment. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was personal and of a civil nature,'' Ms. Alexander said.  
``He didn't do anything that I can see that took away my liberty or 
was a crime against the state.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Alexander's lawyers, Douglas B. Huron and Richard A. Salzman  
said in a written statement, ``On March 25, 1999, several press and 
TV representatives contacted Freda Alexander. Initially she 
responded to questions about her recently ended grand jury service 
without consulting counsel. 
</P>
<P>
	``Later that evening Ms. Alexander spoke to counsel about media  
inquiries. With her approval, we are authorized to say that, on our 
advice, she will not be responding to further media inquiries.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
