<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hawks' Gray Arrested for DUI, Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Atlanta Hawks reserve guard Ed Gray was charged  
with drug possession and driving under the influence after a state 
trooper stopped him for minor traffic violations. 
</P>
<P>
	The trooper stopped Gray's 1991 BMW about 8 p.m. Thursday near  
downtown Atlanta after noticing that the car's windows were tinted 
darker than state law allows and that his California tags had 
expired, spokesman Gordy Wright of the Georgia Department of Public 
Safety said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the trooper found less than an ounce of marijuana and an  
open container of alcohol in the car. 
</P>
<P>
	Gray, who was released on bond after spending the night in jail,  
declined to comment prior to the Hawks' game against the Chicago 
Bulls. ``I'm fine,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The arrest was the latest in a series of problems that have  
plagued the 6-foot-3 guard since he was drafted in the first round 
by the Hawks in 1997. Last season, Gray was fined $57,000 for 
various transgressions, the most serious being the equivalent of a 
four-game suspension when he failed to show up to be treated for a 
broken foot. 
</P>
<P>
	He started this season as a backup to Steve Smith, but he lost  
that role to Tyrone Corbin because of miserable shooting. Prior to 
Friday's game, Gray had played in only four of the previous 12 
games and was shooting 26.8 percent from the field, averaging 4.5 
points per game. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to drug possession and DUI, Gray was charged with  
driving with an open container and driving on a suspended and 
revoked license, Wright said. Blood-alcohol tests are pending on 
the DUI charge. 
</P>
<P>
	Hawks general manager Pete Babcock said the team can't take any  
action against Gray unless he is convicted. A hearing was scheduled 
for April 27. 
</P>
<P>
	``We take these issues extremely seriously,'' Babcock said. ``We  
met with our team this morning and told them we'll support anybody 
who is in our family 100 percent with legal help, counseling, 
whatever's necessary. 
</P>
<P>
	``But if in fact any of our guys are found guilty of a  
misdemeanor or felony, we would take the harshest measure allowed 
by collective bargaining.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The new NBA collective bargaining agreement includes marijuana  
as a banned substance. A player convicted of possession would be 
required to undergo counseling, while harsher penalties such as 
fines and suspensions are allowed for subsequent convictions, 
league spokeswoman Teri Washington said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gray, who played at California, took part in 30 games during his  
rookie season before breaking his foot. He averaged 7.6 points per 
game. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
