<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Penguins Told To Stay in Pittsburgh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- A federal judge has ordered the Pittsburgh  
Penguins to remain at the Civic Arena through 2007 and barred team 
officials from any talks about moving to other cities. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Bernard Markovitz issued a permanent  
injunction prohibiting Penguins co-owner Roger Marino -- or any new 
owners who come out of bankruptcy proceedings -- from trying to take 
the team to any other city. 
</P>
<P>
	The injunction prohibits team officials from even discussing a  
possible sale to non-Pittsburgh owners. 
</P>
<P>
	In a 26-page opinion and order issued Thursday, the judge also  
questioned whether Marino ever intended to honor a commitment the 
team made, which called for the Penguins to stay in the arena 
through 2007 in exchange for nearly $13 million in public 
improvements. 
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins filed for protection from creditors in U.S.  
Bankruptcy Court just as the NHL season began in October, citing 
debt of as much as $124 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Penguins star Mario Lemieux submitted a plan this month  
to buy the team and rescue it from bankruptcy. Markovitz is 
expected to rule sometime next month on whether the plan paints an 
honest picture of the team's financial position. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling Thursday stems from a temporary injunction Markovitz  
issued in November. The Public Auditorium Authority, a city-county 
agency that owns the arena, and SMG, a private firm that operates 
the facility, requested the order. 
</P>
<P>
	Marino and the Penguins asked that it be lifted. Marino's  
attorneys have said the financially troubled team would be more 
valuable if it were allowed to move, bringing more money to 
creditors following a sale. Markovitz said the team's value in the 
city was more important. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Penguins are as much a part of the warp and woof of this  
community as are its other professional sports teams, museums, 
parks, theaters and ethnic neighborhoods,'' the judge wrote in his 
ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	``As important as (the creditors') interests are, they may have  
to give way when the interest of the community at large so 
dictates. In this case, it so dictates.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The team has said it wanted to lift the injunction and end its  
commitment to the arena in order to gain leverage in negotiating a 
lease with SMG. 
</P>
<P>
	Penguins officials say they cannot operate profitably under the  
lease, which forces them to give up between $6 million and $7 
million annually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
