<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gasoline futures prices soared Friday on the New York Mercantile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Gasoline futures prices soared Friday on the New York Mercantile  
amid expectations that a fire at a California refinery will divert 
supplies away from the Northeast. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude, heating oil and natural gas futures also jumped. On other  
commodity markets, gold slumped, while wheat rose sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	Gasoline futures rose to the highest level since October after  
Chevron Corp. reported an explosion and fire had shut down a large 
gas-making unit. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not clear how long the unit near San Francisco would be  
shut down. But market participants were worried a spate of recent 
production problems in the West might cause producers to divert gas 
to that region to secure better profits. 
</P>
<P>
	The Northeast would suffer most under that scenario since it  
relies on gasoline shipped by pipeline from the Gulf Coast to meet 
consumers' daily driving needs. 
</P>
<P>
	The market has grown more sensitive to supply concerns following  
a decision by major producing nations to further slash output in a 
bid to boost prices. Mexico recently defaulted on several contracts 
to U.S. customers in a bid to achieve its goal. 
</P>
<P>
	Further supporting gas prices are inventory figures released  
this week indicating that demand is at record levels even before 
the peak driving season begins. The American Petroleum Institute 
also revised downward by 1 million barrels its estimate of weekly 
gasoline production. 
</P>
<P>
	The contract for May delivery of light, sweet crude rose 50  
cents to $16.17 a barrel; April heating oil rose 1.29 cents to 
42.74 cents a gallon; April unleaded gasoline rose 2.22 cents to 
50.63 cents a gallon; April natural gas rose 0.02 cent to $1.855 
for each 1,000 cubic feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold futures slumped on the New York Mercantile Exchange after  
Canada's prime minister called on the International Monetary Fund 
to sell part of its reserves to help poor countries pay their 
debts. 
</P>
<P>
	Jean Chretien joined a growing number of wealthier nations  
calling for IMF gold sales. Chretien, whose country is the world's 
fourth-largest producer, suggested that as much as 10 million 
ounces should be put on the market. 
</P>
<P>
	That could seriously depress gold prices, and market  
participants said the proposal was significant because it likely 
would hurt Canada's mining industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold futures prices have been languishing below $300 an ounce  
for months, depressed by low inflation in the United States and 
other industrial countries, as well as central bank decisions to 
sell their holdings. 
</P>
<P>
	April gold fell $3.40 to $279.70 an ounce.  
</P>
<P>
	Wheat rose sharply on the Chicago Board of Trade as investors  
began positioning ahead of a key government report next week. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Agriculture Department early Wednesday is set to reveal  
farmer planting intentions for the spring crop, which will provide 
the first concrete estimate of whether producers intend to plant 
more soybeans over corn and wheat. 
</P>
<P>
	Market participants are expecting spring wheat acreage to suffer  
most as farmers turn toward crops that have a better chance of 
selling overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat also found continued support from market talk that the  
Clinton administration is considering a one-time exemption to bans 
on exports to Iran and other countries. 
</P>
<P>
	July wheat rose 6 cents to $2.98 3/4 a bushel.  


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 14:35:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> In Brazil, Panic Turns to Euphoria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- In just two months, economic panic  
has given way to euphoria in Brazil as a flurry of good news has 
people believing the worst is over. 
</P>
<P>
	Stock markets are surging, the currency is stronger, inflation  
is lessening and investors are slowly returning. The crisis may not 
be over, but there's a growing sense that Latin America's largest 
economy is recovering. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe we've seen the worst in Brazil,'' James A. Harmon,  
president and chairman of the U.S. Export-Import Bank, told a group 
of international bankers in Miami Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Merrill Lynch agrees. The U.S. investment bank picked Brazil as  
its favorite Latin American equity market for the second quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a dramatic change from a month ago. Brazil's currency, the  
real, was in free fall, investors scurried to pull their money from 
banks, and President Fernando Henrique Cardoso went on national 
television to plead for calm. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the low point of a crisis that began with an abrupt  
devalution of the real on Jan. 13. In three weeks, the currency 
plunged 46 percent, and the government seemed powerless to stop it. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, the government's challenge is to keep the new-found  
ebullience in check and convince Brazilians that the battle for 
economic stability isn't over yet. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, Finance Minister Pedro Malan warned against the  
premature optimism pervading markets and predicted the turbulence 
will persist for months. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, it's hard to resist so many positive signs.  
</P>
<P>
	The real, worth only about 48 cents at the end of February, was  
up to 56 cents on Friday. That's still well below the 82 cents the 
real cost at the end of 1998, but a significant improvement 
nonetheless. 
</P>
<P>
	After losing $1.82 billion last year, Brazilian stock markets  
are enjoying a new bull run. The Bovespa index of the Sao Paulo 
Stock Exchange, Latin America's largest, surged 15 percent in the 
first week of March alone. 
</P>
<P>
	Inflation, which was about 2 percent last year but threatened to  
roar back with the devaluation, is way below initial predictions. 
Consumer prices in Sao Paulo rose just 0.8 percent in the past four 
weeks, down from 1.4 percent in January. 
</P>
<P>
	The optimism grew when Brazil signed a new agreement with the  
International Monetary Fund, which underpins a $41.5 billion rescue 
plan. The country hopes to receive $8.6 billion of that money by 
early April. 
</P>
<P>
	Cardoso has shown his strength in Congress, winning approval for  
a controversial tax on bank transactions that is expected to 
generate $8.5 billion, a year. The tax is a key to Brazil's 
commitment to reducing its budget deficit. 
</P>
<P>
	Arminio Fraga, president of Brazil's Central Bank, said foreign  
perception of Brazil has ``improved a lot and will continue 
improving as we move ahead'' with austerity reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	Fraga himself has been part of the turnaround. A former  
associate of U.S. billionaire financier George Soros, the 
market-savvy Fraga was essential in persuading foreign bankers to 
maintain credit lines to Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet big hurdles remain. Wholesale prices are rising and could  
feed inflation. Unions also are demanding large cost-of-living 
raises, and labor unrest promises to heat up. 
</P>
<P>
	An expected surge in exports hasn't happened, and the $11  
billion trade surplus Brazil promised the IMF looks unlikely. 
</P>
<P>
	The government also seems to have no solution for its huge  
domestic debt, which soared with the real's devaluation and grows 
daily, with interest rates running as high as 42 percent. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 11:25:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Harmon Industries Buys Calif. Firm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BLUE SPRINGS, Mo. (AP) -- Harmon Industries Inc., a supplier of  
train control and communications products is acquiring Golden Gate 
Switchgear Co. Inc. of Napa, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Terms of the deal were not disclosed.  
</P>
<P>
	Golden Gate Switchgear manufactures AC and DC switchgear for  
electrified rail and commerical applications. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 15:51:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dems Challenge GOP on Bank Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Democratic leaders are challenging Senate  
Republicans to compromise on legislation to lift barriers between 
banks, securities firms and insurance companies, casting the 
dispute as a major test of bipartisanship in the new Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., Treasury Secretary  
Robert Rubin and Sen. Paul Sarbanes, D-Md., insisted Friday that 
community lending requirements for banks must be included or 
President Clinton will veto the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want financial modernization enacted this year. This should  
not be a partisan issue,'' Daschle told reporters. He said 
lawmakers must choose ``either a partisan brinksmanship or a 
bipartisan accomplishment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin attended to emphasize the administration's opposition to a  
Republican bill in the Senate while supporting the dismantling of 
Depression-era prohibitions against combining banks, insurers and 
brokerages. 
</P>
<P>
	Legislation proposed by both parties would create huge financial  
``supermarkets,'' offering consumers checking accounts, mutual 
funds, insurance policies and much more. Consumer advocates have 
expressed concern that the measures, by allowing banks, brokerage 
firms and insurers to merge and get more deeply into each other's 
businesses, could bring a dangerous concentration of economic power 
in fewer hands. 
</P>
<P>
	Backers of the legislation, including Wall Street, banks and  
insurers, insist it is needed to keep the U.S. financial industry 
competitive in a fast-changing global economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Daschle and Sarbanes, the Senate Banking Committee's senior  
Democrat, formally proposed a bill as an alternative to a GOP 
measure that cleared the committee in a party-line vote early this 
month. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the Republican bill, pushed by Banking Committee Chairman  
Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, banks would not have to get a 
satisfactory community-lending rating from the government to 
conduct new financial activities. The bill also would exempt small 
banks with less than $100 million in assets from the community 
lending laws, which require banks and thrifts to lend to the poor 
and minorities in their neighborhoods. 
</P>
<P>
	The Democrats' bill, as well as a bipartisan measure approved  
recently by the House Banking Committee, 51-8, include the 
requirement for a community-lending rating and have no exemption 
for small banks. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1977 lending laws have played a valuable role by ``expanding  
access to credit for all communities in our country,'' Sarbanes 
said, adding that they have helped many African Americans and other 
minorities to become home owners. 
</P>
<P>
	Gramm has maintained that the government shouldn't dictate to  
banks what people or companies they can do business with -- a view 
that led him to block financial overhaul legislation last fall. The 
blocking maneuver by Gramm and Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., came 
after the legislation squeaked through the House by one vote, 
214-213. 
</P>
<P>
	Christi Harlan, a spokeswoman for Gramm, said Friday ``he's not  
willing to compromise on the issue of expanding'' the reach of the 
community lending law. Gramm is not pushing for its repeal, 
however, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Harlan noted that Gramm plans to meet soon after Congress'  
two-week Easter recess with Daschle, Sarbanes and Senate Majority 
Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., to discuss the legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a test,'' Daschle said. ``The Republicans in the House  
have already met that test.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 05:46:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baltimore Students Depart for Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAVANA (AP) -- Within hours after landing on Cuban soil, about  
100 American students hit the ball field, teaming against Cuban 
kids their own age as a kind of warmup to Sunday's exhibition 
between the Baltimore Orioles and a Cuban national team. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's great out here,'' said Clarence Collier, 11. ``The kids  
who play baseball here are really challenging.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The students from the Baltimore-Washington area arrived in  
Havana on Thursday on a plane chartered by Baltimore Orioles owner 
Peter Angelos. With the exception of more than 400 foreign 
correspondents, they will be among the few foreigners to watch the 
exhibition match in person. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be great. I have loved baseball longer than I  
can remember,'' said Jimmy Petrila, 12, of Washington D.C., whose 
parents paid for his trip. ``And the Orioles are definitely my 
favorite team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As for the Cubans, only those who receive invitations will be  
able to attend, the government confirmed on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though it had not been announced yet by Cuba's  
government-controlled media, the news was spreading Thursday 
throughout government workplaces, schools, parks, and along 
Havana's famous seawall, the Malecon. 
</P>
<P>
	``There will be no sale of tickets at the stadium,'' said  
Reinaldo Calviac, director of the International Press Center. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said invitations probably would go to organizations  
such as schools and sports clubs. 
</P>
<P>
	In a city as baseball-mad as Havana, such invitations will be  
highly coveted. 
</P>
<P>
	The rustic Latinoamericano stadium built in 1946, where Sunday's  
game will be played, holds 50,000 fans. 
</P>
<P>
	It will be the first time in 40 years that a major league team  
has played in Cuba. Big leaguers used to come to the island 
regularly before the 1959 revolution that brought Fidel Castro to 
power. 
</P>
<P>
	Because it is only an exhibition game, Cuban officials are  
downplaying its importance. 
</P>
<P>
	``The most important game, the most interesting games right now  
in Cuba are our playoff games,'' Juan Gomez, coach of the hometown 
favorites, the Industriales, said Wednesday night before his team 
beat Isla de Juventud to earn a spot in the final. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the Sunday match between the Orioles and the Cubans is a  
big deal for the American kids. 
</P>
<P>
	``For our four days here we are going to see some of the most  
exciting things that baseball has to offer,'' Jim Mauro, president 
of the Northwest Washington Little League, said Thursday as the 
kids played on a sandlot near the Plaza of the Revolution. 
</P>
<P>
	Soon, they were already getting a sense of what Sunday's game  
might be like. 
</P>
<P>
	``The kids here play a more exciting kind of baseball,'' Petrila  
said. ``In the United States, people swing for the fences. Here 
there are a lot of bunts and stealing. It is a more strategic kind 
of playing, like Ty Cobb in in the 1940s.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After getting last-minute federal approval March 19 to take his  
team to Cuba, Angelos sent word to area schools and recreation 
leagues that he would provide a plane for 100 youths and up to 50 
chaperones. By Sunday, 50 youths had been signed up by parents who 
could afford the $750 per person. 
</P>
<P>
	Organizers saved the rest of the seats for students who would  
have trouble affording the fee. Angelos pledged $12,500 and other 
donors chipped in about $5,000. 
</P>
<P>
	While the American youngsters praised their Cuban counterparts,  
the Cubans had kind words for their new friends as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just feel great to be able to play for the first time  
against the Americans,'' said 11-year-old catcher Jorge Luis Coury, 
who wore his baseball cap backwards. ``They're pretty good.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 10:52:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  NATO Launches First Daylight Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO aircraft and missiles blasted  
targets in Yugoslavia for a second night, directing much of their 
fire on Kosovo, where fighting raged between Serbs and ethnic 
Albanians. Today, NATO forces launched their first daylight attack 
on Yugoslavia, state and independent media said. 
</P>
<P>
	Air raid sirens wailed at midafternoon in Belgrade and several  
other cities, and targets were hit in three suburbs of the capital, 
according to the official Tanjug news agency and independent Studio 
B television. People in the city center said they did not 
immediately see evidence of the strikes. 
</P>
<P>
	Western officials called the previous two nights of attacks a  
successful start to forcing President Slobodan Milosevic to agree 
to a peace deal. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's not going to be one knockout blow, but day after day,  
if he does not stop his genocidal attacks on the Kosovo people, we 
will take larger and larger lumps out of his military force,'' 
British Defense Secretary George Robertson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslavia's army maintained its defiant tone, claiming it  
inflicted ``substantial damage'' against an ``overpoweringly 
stronger enemy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first round of airstrikes Wednesday killed at least 11  
people and injured dozens, Serbian officials said. A Yugoslav army 
division said one person was killed and three were wounded in 
airstrikes Thursday night near the Montenegrin town of Rozaje. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslav forces continued their offensive on the ground Thursday  
against ethnic Albanians. International monitors and relief 
officials forced to leave Kosovo because of the bombing said they 
feared Serb forces were burning villages and killing ethnic 
Albanians or forcing them to flee. 
</P>
<P>
	Ethnic Albanian sources reported persistent gunfire overnight in  
Pristina, the Kosovo capital, and an ethnic Albanian human rights 
group said a political figure and a union leader were killed in the 
northern town of Kosovska Mitrovica. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.N. refugee agency said Kosovo refugees who crossed into  
Albania claim that 20 men were shot to death by Serb forces 
evacuating the village of Goden in southwest Kosovo on Thursday. It 
said it was unable to verify the account. 
</P>
<P>
	``With only a handful of independent observers left on the  
ground, we are extremely worried about the plight of Kosovo's 
civilian population, which has already been through a terrible 
ordeal,'' U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees Sadako Ogata said in 
Geneva. 
</P>
<P>
	William Walker, the U.S. head of the 1,400-member monitoring  
mission that left Kosovo this week, also said the situation was 
deteriorating. The Organization for Security and Cooperation in 
Europe decided today to reduce Walker's mission created last year 
to monitor a failed peace agreement down to 250 people. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia failed today to muster enough support to pass a  
resolution in the U.N. Security Council demanding NATO stop bombing 
Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO officials said today that allied aircraft had flown 400  
sorties against Yugoslavia in the first two days of air operations 
and had struck 50 targets, all air defense and related facilities. 
</P>
<P>
	Bomb damage assessments are still being assembled, said Air  
Commodore David Wilby, briefing reporters at NATO headquarters. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're making steady headway just as we had anticipated,'' NATO  
commander Gen. Wesley Clark said on NBC's ``Today'' show. ``We've 
done severe damage to a number of targets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NATO officials have said all planes returned safely.  
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton appealed directly to the Serbian people today  
for support, saying Milosevic has imperiled their future and forced 
their ``sons to keep fighting a senseless conflict that you did not 
ask for and that he could have prevented.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There was no hint from Milosevic that he would back down over  
Kosovo, the southern province of Serbia. He cut off diplomatic 
relations with the United States, France, Germany and Britain, 
while Serbian authorities ordered journalists from NATO nations out 
of the country. Scores did so, but some were trying to return today 
after conciliatory statements from Yugoslav officials. 
</P>
<P>
	A Yugoslav army statement said the Thursday night bombing  
targeted military barracks, military airports, air defense systems, 
communications centers and command posts. It lacked specifics on 
any damage caused and claimed Yugoslav forces retaliated 
effectively. 
</P>
<P>
	``In an unfair airborne battle, acting against an overpoweringly  
stronger enemy, according to reports available, substantial damage 
was inflicted on the enemy,'' the statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilby denied that NATO had attacked Yugoslav military barracks.  
</P>
<P>
	``At the moment ... our only target is the integrated air  
defense system and facilities associated with that,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The strikes Thursday hit inside Kosovo around Pristina, Kosovska  
Mitrovica and the southwestern town of Prizren, media in Yugoslavia 
said. Serbian TV said three missiles hit a police station on a 
military base, injuring one policeman and leaving two others 
missing. 
</P>
<P>
	A Belgrade city official said there was ``heavy activity'' by  
warplanes attacking targets outside the Yugoslav capital, Belgrade. 
The official Tanjug news agency said an airport in the central 
Serbian city of Nis had been hit. 
</P>
<P>
	In Montenegro, Yugoslavia's other republic, there were reports  
of explosions at army compounds and barracks, as well as at an 
airport and radar facilities. 
</P>
<P>
	A NATO missile hit Djakovica, near the Kosovo-Albanian border,  
missing an army compound, Tanjug reported. ``The material damage is 
substantial, and there are casualties,'' it said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tanjug reported that ethnic Albanian rebels had attacked Serb  
police in Djakovica, wounding one. 
</P>
<P>
	Pleurat Sejeu, spokesman for the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army in  
London, told BBC World television that Yugoslav MiGs were being 
used against ethnic Albanians, who make up 90 percent of Kosovo's 
population. 
</P>
<P>
	Sejeu said Serbs had rounded up thousands of displaced ethnic  
Albanian civilians in the central Drenica region and were marching 
them toward Pristina. ``Nobody knows what will happen'' to them, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 200 Kosovo Albanians crossed into Albania on Thursday,  
saying Serb security forces had swept into the village of Goden, 
detaining men, setting the village on fire, and marching women and 
children across the border. 
</P>
<P>
	Selim Ferraj, 37, one of the few males with the group from  
Goden, said he feared the other men were dead. ``I am only alive 
because I knew the Serb commander before,'' said Ferraj, who 
escaped with his wife and five children. 
</P>
<P>
	The conflict has claimed more than 2,000 lives in the past year.  
UNHCR estimates that more than 450,000 people have been forced from 
their homes. 
</P>
<P>
	Romanian Prime Minister Radu Vasile said today that Romania  
plans to accept up to 4,000 refugees from Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	A day after appearing to waver on the NATO strikes, Italian  
Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema said today that Italy will stand 
firm with alliance -- but also push to resume talks. 
</P>
<P>
	French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin and British Prime Minister  
Tony Blair reiterated their support, and Secretary of State 
Madeleine Albright denied that NATO solidarity was at risk. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know there is the will to continue,'' she said on ``Today.''  
``It's my sense that the coalition is very strong and united.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As part of a freeze on all relations with NATO, Russia today  
told NATO's top diplomatic official and its senior military 
representative in Moscow to leave the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslav officials have said they were willing to resume peace  
talks. But they reject an agreement the ethnic Albanians signed 
last month in France, saying it was forced on them by the West. 
</P>
<P>
	Western leaders say Milosevic has bluffed before and they demand  
that he either sign the agreement and halt violence in Kosovo or 
face further attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 10:52:33 </DATE_TIME>
