<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fidelity to Frequent Callers: Stop! </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Fidelity Investments has told 30,000 frequent  
callers to quit reaching out and touching its telephone 
representatives. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, 5,000 customers who call often for fund balances,  
stock quotes or other information got letters from Fidelity telling 
them to use its Web site or automated phone system instead. 
</P>
<P>
	Those who continue making calls will be routed to special  
representatives who won't give them answers, but will direct them 
to the routine information. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Fidelity sent letters to another 25,000 customers -- a  
total of only half of one percent of its 6 million retail 
customers. Fidelity, the world's largest mutual fund company, has a 
total of 15 million customers. 
</P>
<P>
	Some frequent callers were miffed.  
</P>
<P>
	``Offensive and insulting,'' Michael Fischler, a professor at  
Plymouth State College in New Hampshire, told The Wall Street 
Journal. 
</P>
<P>
	``The message is really clear: Don't bother us. You're annoying  
us. Get in line, or we don't want your business,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	At least one Fidelity watcher applauded the move.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's very smart,'' said David O'Leary, president of  
N.H.-based Alpha Equity Research, said today. ``The more they can 
drive their customers to the Internet, the more they reduce their 
costs, and the more they limit their regulatory exposure because of 
people making mistakes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The people who call often -- sometimes every hour -- are just  
lazy, retired or have nothing else to do, said O'Leary. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are people who are just behind the curve in terms of  
using technology,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Many customers simply need instruction on how to use Fidelity's  
automated telephone system or Web site, said Anne Crowley, Fidelity 
spokeswoman. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most people, once they've been shown it, said, 'This was  
great,''' Crowley said, noting Fidelity spends at least $500 
million every year updating its technology. 
</P>
<P>
	Customers who received the letter will still be able to talk to  
a phone representative to ask more complicated questions about 
their accounts, said Crowley. 
</P>
<P>
	She wouldn't say how frequently a customer had to call to make  
the cutoff list, but she said the company was careful to screen out 
customers who needed extra help for more complex transactions. 
</P>
<P>
	Few have complained.  
</P>
<P>
	``We've only heard from 34 customers who registered  
complaints,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Fidelity receives 680,000 telephone calls a day, 77 percent of  
which are handled by automated systems, said Crowley. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you had a phone representative answer that 77 percent of  
calls, people would be waiting on hold forever, or it would be 
prohibitively costly and raise the customers' costs,'' Crowley 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	A phone call fielded by a human being costs $13; an automated  
phone call costs only $1. 
</P>
<P>
	The average Fidelity mutual fund customer calls 4 or 5 times a  
year, she said. The average brokerage customer calls 15 times a 
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 06:07:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Will Refinery Blasts Raise Gas Cost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Gas prices surged in California following  
last month's deadly explosion at a Tosco refinery, and analysts say 
Thursday's fire at a Chevron plant may well send them higher. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're going to go up a lot,'' said Michael Mayer, a  
securities analyst who follows Chevron Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	No one was injured in the explosion Thursday afternoon at the  
Chevron plant in Richmond, which sent a huge pillar of black smoke 
across the Bay area. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at the Chevron plant said the refinery would remain  
open, while the unit where the fiery explosion occurred was shut 
down indefinitely. 
</P>
<P>
	The refinery can produce up to 240,000 gallons of crude oil  
daily, said Chevron spokeswoman Dawn Soper. She would not say how 
the unit's closure would impact production there. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this point I couldn't speculate on anything regarding  
pricing,'' Soper said. With refineries in El Segundo and elsewhere, 
``we don't expect what happened today to have a significant affect 
on our customers including those at the pump.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But production already is crippled in the state, with at least  
three other refineries operating at less than 100 percent capacity, 
said Jay McKeeman, executive vice president of the California 
Independent Oil Marketers Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Various refinery shutdowns in California mean about 250,000 to  
300,000 gallons a day are cut out of the state's normal daily 
supply of 2 million gallons, according to Chevron spokesman Jack 
Coffey. Tosco's Avon plant alone usually produces 160,000 gallons a 
day. 
</P>
<P>
	``The problem is one in a continuing series of problems,''  
McKeeman said. ``California is a huge petroleum consumer entity, 
(buying) 13 billion gallons of gasoline a year. It needs a lot of 
refining capacity a year to meet that demand. Anytime there's a 
glitch in the system you get a problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Feb. 23, the day of the blast at the Tosco Avon refinery that  
killed four workers and left another man critically injured, prices 
shot up 16 cents -- to $1.18 a gallon on the West Coast -- before 
sliding back down to about $1.02 per gallon. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices for regular gasoline were about $1.30 a gallon or more in  
the San Francisco Bay area this week, compared to about $1.12 on 
the West Coast overall, according to the U.S. Energy Department. 
</P>
<P>
	California motorists face unique concerns when buying gas  
because laws require it to be specially formulated and most of what 
they purchase is produced in the state. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can't immediately get access to other supplies of fuel,''  
McKeeman said. ``It's going to cost more; there's delays in getting 
conforming fuel in the state.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just how much supply could be affected is an open question,  
McKeeman said. The refineries experiencing various problems -- which 
also include an Arco facility in the Los Angeles area and an Exxon 
site in Benicia -- account for as much as half of the state's fuel 
production. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it's true that close to half of the refining capacity in  
the state is at risk, yeah, there's a very definite problem of 
supply shortages,'' McKeeman said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 10:34:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Boys Charged Over Distress Calls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FAIRFIELD, Conn. (AP) -- Two 12-year-old boys have been charged  
with making false distress-at-sea calls from their school bus in a 
prank that set off a urgent search of Long Island Sound by the 
Coast Guard. 
</P>
<P>
	The boys made four calls over two days this week, using a  
hand-held VHF radio. They reported their boat had crashed into 
rocks and was taking on water near Bridgeport Harbor. 
</P>
<P>
	The Coast Guard dispatched two 41-foot boats, which spent  
several hours searching for the boys. A helicopter was set to take 
off when the boys reported that they were safely ashore. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is dangerous business,'' said John D. Strauser, Coast  
Guard chief warrant officer. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to respond. Even when we think there is a possibility  
they're not being truthful, we're going to respond the same as the 
fire department and police department.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Strauser said the prank cost taxpayers about $16,000.  
</P>
<P>
	The boys' names were not released because they are juveniles.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 16:44:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Von Ert Wins U.S. Snowboard Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LUDLOW, Vt. (AP) -- Olympic snowboard teammates Sondra Van Ert of  
Ketchum, Idaho, took control on the second run Friday to overtake 
Rosey Fletcher of Anchorage, Alaska, and win the giant slalom for 
her ninth U.S. championship. 
</P>
<P>
	Fletcher and the semi-ageless Van Ert, who turned 35 on March 9,  
flip-flopped their results from Thursday's slalom, which was won 
handily by Fletcher. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Ert, who won three World Cup races this winter and a bronze  
medal in giant slalom in the world snowboard championships, had a 
winning time of 2 minutes, 42.30 seconds. Fletcher was silver 
medalist in 2:42.48 and Lisa Kosglow of Boise, Idaho, was third in 
2:42.94. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hey, I get to play for another year,'' Van Ert giggled as she  
discussed possibly continuing until the 2002 Olympics in Salt Lake 
City. She graduated from the University of Utah after retiring from 
World Cup skiing in the mid-1980s. She became hooked on 
snowboarding while recuperating from knee surgery and watching kids 
having fun riding 'boards in Sun Valley, near her home. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was third in the first run, but I was two seconds back of  
Rosey,'' Van Ert said, ``so I had nothing to lose on my second run. 
I tried to ride aggressively.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fletcher was disappointed in letting another title slip away but  
she brightened as she noted her younger sister, Beth, finished 
ninth and Friday was her last race of the season. ``I haven't been 
home since Christmas,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the men's event, Canadians Mark Fawcett and Jasey Jay  
Anderson finished 1-2 with Peter Thorndike of Meredith, N.H., in 
third place. Fawcett dominated the race, posting the fastest time 
on each run to finish in 2:29.41. 
</P>
<P>
	Although racers and coaches heaped praise on course crews for  
keeping the run together despite the softening conditions, the 
mushy snow created big gaps in time among the riders. 
</P>
<P>
	``True, but it would've been worse if these guys hadn't done  
such a good job preparing the course,'' Fawcett said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
