<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Rises Broadly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar rose broadly Friday as investors  
sought a safe haven while the U.S.-led NATO bombing in Yugoslavia 
continued. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0769, down from $1.0826. During the  
trading day, the euro fell to $1.0715, its lowest level since the 
launch of the new currency in January. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading, the dollar was quoted at 120.26 Japanese yen,  
up from 118.13. 
</P>
<P>
	``The (foreign exchange) market feels the longer the conflict in  
Kosovo involving NATO, this is a negative for euroland,'' said 
Jeffrey Yu, a senior foreign exchange dealer at Sanwa Bank, 
referring to the 11 nations using the new currency. ``It's a sell 
Europe and buy something else (market). For the time being it's buy 
the dollar, buy North America.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.4806 Swiss francs, up from  
1.4716, and 1.5142 Canadian dollars, up from 1.5078. The British 
pound was quoted at $1.6218, down from $1.6234. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Monday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8162 German 
marks, up from 1.8067; 6.0901 French francs, up from 6.0606; and 
1,798.56 Italian lire, up from 1,788.91. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
