<DOCNO> APW19990326.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 14:55:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton Appeals to Serbian People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton appealed directly to the  
Serb people Friday for support in NATO's struggle against Yugoslav 
President Slobodan Milosevic. ``He has jeopardized Kosovo's future 
and brought you more war,'' Clinton said in a satellite-beamed 
message he labeled ``the plain truth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With Yugoslav authorities tightly controlling the media in  
Belgrade, administration officials said the purpose of Clinton's 
broadcast, and a similar one by Secretary of State Madeleine 
Albright in the local Serbo-Croatian language, was to explain to 
the Serb people why NATO bombers had attacked their country. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no such thing as a free press and opposing views in  
Serbia now,'' White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said. 
</P>
<P>
	But by sounding the theme that Milosevic was to blame for the  
bloodshed, Clinton and Albright appeared to be trying to unsettle 
Milosevic's rule and turn his people against him. 
</P>
<P>
	``He could have kept Kosovo and Serbia and given you peace,''  
Clinton said. ``Right now, he's forcing your sons to keep fighting 
a senseless conflict that you did not ask for and that he could 
have prevented.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Striking at the Serbs' national pride, Clinton told those able  
to receive his videotaped broadcast that ``President Milosevic has 
spoken often of Serbia's standing in the world, but by his every 
action he has diminished your country's standing, exposed you to 
violence and instability, and isolated you from the rest of 
Europe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was unclear how many people heard Clinton's message, which  
was carried by Radio Free Europe, Voice of America and World Net, 
the television enterprise run by the U.S. Information Agency, as 
well as over the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	White House spokesman Joe Lockhart conceded that Milosevic was  
unlikely to allow state television to broadcast Clinton's message. 
``But we do believe through a variety of sources, including the 
Internet, that the message will get through,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	State Department spokesman James P. Rubin, meanwhile, said the  
administration was ``extremely alarmed'' about reports of 
atrocities against ethnic Albanian civilians in Kosovo and was 
``putting a great deal of resources and efforts into checking these 
out as quickly as we can and as thoroughly as we can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Any evidence will be turned over to an international war crimes  
tribunal, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright, who learned Serbo-Croatian as a child when her father  
served as a Czech diplomat in Belgrade, told the Serbs: ``Americans 
do not hate Serbs. Like me, they remember when we were allies 
against fascism. Like you, Americans want to live in peace with 
their neighbors and the wider world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She said the United States and its allies ``could not sit idly  
by while security forces were used to commit atrocities against 
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With NATO warplanes raking Serb targets with bombs and cruise  
missiles, ethnic Serb demonstrators charged the U.S. Embassy in 
neighboring Macedonia on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ambassador Christopher Hill and other Americans were not  
injured. But on Friday, the State Department authorized the 
departure from Skopje of nonessential personnel and dependents. 
</P>
<P>
	The State Department has warned Milosevic not to expand the  
conflict in Kosovo to Macedonia, a former Yugoslav republic. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials confirmed that the Serbs' sweep through the  
villages of Kosovo was continuing. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know that there is intensified fighting. It remains  
localized ... but there is fighting,'' Lockhart said. ``This is not 
surprising to us. This is something that started before the allied 
operation began.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gen. Wesley Clark, NATO's supreme military commander, said a  
third day of airstrikes would be focused on further reducing 
Yugoslavia's formidable air defenses. 
</P>
<P>
	Allied fighter planes on Friday shot down two Yugoslav jets over  
Bosnia. Rubin said the Yugoslavs were ``moving against'' troops 
maintaining peace accords in the country where Serbs, Croats and 
Muslims had fought a war for more than three years. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright said on NBC that the 19-nation NATO alliance was united  
in supporting the assault. This conflicted with reports that Italy 
wanted to reopen negotiations and that Greece was skeptical of the 
operation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 17:33:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Redskins Sign Linebacker Strickland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Washington Redskins signed linebacker Fred  
Strickland to a two-year, $1 million contract, the team announced 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Strickland, an unrestricted free agent, will also receive a  
$100,000 signing bonus. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-2, 251-pound Strickland started 15 games for Dallas  
last season and was third on the team with 117 tackles. 
</P>
<P>
	He played his first five seasons with the Los Angeles Rams, then  
played with Minnesota and Green Bay before going to Dallas in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
