<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fouls Worry Ga. Coach Against Duke </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Everywhere Georgia coach Andy Landers  
looks, he sees people in striped shirts. Every sound he hears 
resembles a whistle. 
</P>
<P>
	On the eve of his team's game against Duke in the national  
semifinals, Landers was dealing Thursday with a serious referee 
obsession. Like most coaches, he was concerned about his team's 
penchant for getting into foul trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you get up on people and play aggressive, as we do, we  
have to be careful there,'' Landers said. ``We fouled the person at 
McDonalds this morning that was serving us Coke.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Landers' team has struggled with foul trouble at times this  
season. The Lady Bulldogs have averaged 20.4 fouls per game, as 
opposed to 18.9 by their opponents. And Georgia has had players 
foul out 24 times -- including eight times by freshman center Tawana 
McDonald. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very important for our basketball team to stay out of  
foul trouble,'' he said. ``When you dribble-drive the way Duke 
does, when you have the inside people that Duke has, there's the 
potential to have fouls.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Duke coach Gail Goestenkors also thinks fouls will be a key to  
the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think both teams are probably going to try to get the ball  
inside early on and try to get somebody in foul trouble,'' she 
said. ``We are both very, very aggressive on the defensive end of 
the floor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A bigger concern for Goestenkors is whether her team can stop  
Kelly and Coco Miller. The identical twins, who average a combined 
37 points a game in the Georgia backcourt, present a double 
challenge for Duke in tonight's first semifinal game at the Women's 
Final Four. 
</P>
<P>
	``Watching the twins is an incredible experience,'' Goestenkors  
said. ``It's an exciting brand of basketball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kelly averaged 18.6 points a game this season for the Lady  
Bulldogs, and Coco averaged 18.4. They swapped the team lead for 
scoring six times this season, with Kelly overtaking her sister by 
scoring a career-high 33 points in Georgia's 89-71 win over Iowa 
State in the Mideast Regional final. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think our personalities are very similar,'' Kelly said.  
``And we've played together for so long I think that helps a lot on 
the court. We love to play together. We are really close. I think 
it definitely has strengthened the bond.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 5-foot-10 sophomore sisters started playing basketball as 4  
year olds in Rochester, Minn. They are considered the best twins in 
women's basketball since Pam and Paula McGee played at Southern 
California in the 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	Landers has coached three sets of twins, and tries to downplay  
the novelty of coaching such similar players. When asked for 
humorous anecdotes about the twins, such as cases of mistaken 
identity, he is at a loss. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to burst your bubble. I can't tell you a lot of  
funny stories because we've worked hard at treating them as 
individuals,'' he said. ``While they look alike, they're not alike. 
Do they have a lot of common bonds? Yes. But I hope everybody on 
our team does.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coco is a slightly better outside shooter. Kelly has more  
rebounds, steals and assists. 
</P>
<P>
	``The way that they move is very different,'' Landers said.  
``You can just look across the floor and know who it is, who is 
running or dribbling or shooting.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
