<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- A man wanted for questioning in  
the slaying of a Brazilian man at the Waldorf Astoria in New York 
turned himself in to police Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Marcio Scherer, 27, was the last person seen with Joao Saboia  
before the 56-year-old was found dead on March 13. Police 
questioned Scherer for an hour, in the presence of his two lawyers, 
federal police spokeswomen Jocelia Pisoni said by telephone from 
Porto Alegre 700 miles southwest of Rio de Janeiro. 
</P>
<P>
	A local judge ordered Scherer jailed until the investigation is  
completed, Pisoni said. 
</P>
<P>
	New York police had wanted to talk to Scherer, who left the  
United States shortly after the murder, but have so far declined to 
call him a suspect. 
</P>
<P>
	Saboia had stopped in New York on his way to Atlantic City,  
where he was well known for his high-priced gambling. He often 
carried a lot of cash, and police told his family that about 
$50,000 was missing from his room, his nephew said. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	GUADALAJARA (AP) -- Religious leaders said Friday they were  
delighted at reports the Vatican will canonize a Mexican nun who 
founded a religious order. 
</P>
<P>
	The Vatican said Friday it had officially attributed a miracle  
to Sister Maria de Jesus Sacramentado Venegas, which clears her 
path to sainthood, Vatican Radio reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Venegas, founder of the Daughters of the Sacred Heart of Jesus,  
was born in the western state of Jalisco in 1868 and died in the 
state capital, Guadalajara, in 1959. She was known locally as Madre 
Naty. 
</P>
<P>
	``The news is a great honor to religious people in Jalisco, and  
to its Catholic Church,'' said Jose Trinidad Gonzalez, assistant 
bishop of Guadalajara. Venegas would become Mexico's second saint, 
after 19th-century Franciscan monk Saint Felipe de Jesus. 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzalez said thousands of Mexicans will lead a pilgrimage to  
the Vatican on May 21, 2000, the day scheduled for the canonization 
ceremony. 
</P>
<P>
	He said other Mexicans chosen for sainthood could include Juan  
Diego, an Indian thought to have been visited by the Virgin Mary, 
as well as father Jose Maria del Yermo and Bishop Cristobal 
Magayanes. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Vendors left their sidewalk stands and took  
to the streets Friday to protest the arrest of a powerful leader of 
a vendors' organization on suspicion of leading a turf battle 
earlier this week with a rival group. 
</P>
<P>
	About one hundred vendors blocked a street outside the Mexico  
City prosecutor's office, demanding Silvia Rico's release. She will 
be either charged or released within two days. 
</P>
<P>
	Rico was arrested after she was implicated in a pitched battle  
between two rival groups of vendors outside the city's main square 
in which three people suffered gunshot wounds earlier this week. 
</P>
<P>
	The vendors have engaged in frequent clashes with police over  
the last two years. The administration of leftist Mayor Cuauhtemoc 
Cardenas has vowed to clear some streets of stands, which were long 
tolerated because of the political clout of the vendors' groups and 
bribes they paid. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- A merger of Mexico's top two financial groups  
would have difficulty winning regulatory approval, the country's 
top antitrust watchdog said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Rumors have swirled in Mexico during recent days that a merger  
between Bancomer and Banamex-Accival was in the works, despite 
repeated denials by company officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Fernando Sanchez Ugarte, head of the Federal Competition  
Commission, said neither financial group has submitted a formal 
request for a merger, but that considering their market positions, 
the antitrust agency would carefully evaluate such a proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe that under current market conditions, it would be  
very difficult for the commission to approve a merger of this 
kind,'' Sanchez Ugarte told foreign correspondents. 
</P>
<P>
	If the two banks were to merge, the resulting entity would  
control about half the Mexican market. 
</P>
<P>
	In a Thursday interview, central bank Gov. Guillermo Ortiz told  
the Financial Times that he ``had informal notice'' that the 
institutions have the intention of starting preliminary merger 
talks. 
</P>
