<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Safety of Diabetes Drug Reviewed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BETHESDA, Md. (AP) -- The controversial drug Rezulin is credited  
with helping thousands battle diabetes, but it also can cause 
sudden and lethal liver failure. 
</P>
<P>
	A scientific panel has decided in frustration that just how  
risky Rezulin really is remains a mystery, but it advised imposing 
new restrictions on the drug in hopes that only diabetics who need 
Rezulin most will chance using it. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not to be used, ever, as a first-line drug for  
diabetes,'' Dr. Jules Hirsch of Rockefeller University said as 
fellow advisers to the Food and Drug Administration pushed for new 
curbs on Rezulin. 
</P>
<P>
	Rezulin, known chemically as troglitazone, was widely cheered  
when it hit the market in 1997, because it is the only drug sold 
that resensitizes the body to insulin, the underlying problem of 
Type II or adult-onset diabetes. 
</P>
<P>
	Many doctors contend it is invaluable for certain patients, and  
750,000 Americans now use it. 
</P>
<P>
	But because the drug can damage patients' livers, the FDA on  
Friday gathered its advisory panel for a highly unusual public 
reassessment of Rezulin's safety. 
</P>
<P>
	The FDA said 43 patients have suffered acute liver failure after  
taking Rezulin for several months and the drug probably caused 38 
of the cases. Twenty-eight died, seven survived only with liver 
transplants and five recovered without transplants. The FDA has not 
determined what happened to the other three. 
</P>
<P>
	An FDA epidemiologist, Dr. David Graham, contended that the 43  
cases may represent only 10 percent of all Rezulin patients with 
liver failure, because the government seldom learns of all drug 
side effects. Thus, Graham argued that Rezulin may have caused up 
to 400 cases of liver failure instead of just the 38 he can prove. 
</P>
<P>
	The risk increases the longer diabetics use the drug, Graham  
said. He created a model that estimated that risk at one in 1,800 
people who use Rezulin for six months. 
</P>
<P>
	And despite repeated FDA warnings that patients' livers should  
be tested monthly for early damage signs, so they can stop the drug 
in hopes their livers will heal, one study suggests less than half 
of doctors do so. In addition, testing didn't help a handful of 
patients whose fatal liver damage occurred just weeks after they 
passed a liver test. 
</P>
<P>
	Manufacturer Parke-Davis, a division of Warner-Lambert Inc.,  
vehemently denied that Rezulin's risk is so high. It contends that 
about one in 45,000 Rezulin users will develop liver failure. 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of people have used Rezulin for six months to a year,  
the company said. So, it said, if the risk were as high as the FDA 
contends, an epidemic of liver failure would have resulted. 
</P>
<P>
	``Where is the epidemic?'' asked Dr. Gerald Faich, a Parke-Davis  
consultant. 
</P>
<P>
	FDA's Graham conceded he knows of no patient who died after  
taking Rezulin for a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten diabetes specialists begged the FDA's advisers not to ban  
Rezulin. 
</P>
<P>
	``No drug is 100 percent safe,'' said Dr. Steven Edelman of the  
Veterans Affairs Medical Center in San Diego, noting that 
uncontrolled diabetes causes blindness, kidney damage, heart 
disease and stroke. ``But diabetes is a serious disease'' that 
kills 400 Americans a day, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The FDA advisers were frustrated that no one can prove which  
risk estimate is accurate. So they recommended restrictions on the 
drug until doctors get a better grasp of the risk. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel decided that Rezulin should never be used as a lone  
therapy, as it now is sold, but only in combination with older 
treatments, and it should only be prescribed for patients who 
cannot adequately control their disease with other, less risky 
therapies. 
</P>
<P>
	It is ``abysmal'' that so few doctors conduct proper liver  
tests, the FDA panel said. It insisted that Parke-Davis explicitly 
warn patients about the liver risks so they'll know to demand tests 
for their own safety. 
</P>
<P>
	The FDA isn't bound by its advisers' decisions, but usually  
follows them. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
