<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., China Negotiate Trade Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. and Chinese negotiators are intensifying  
efforts to achieve a breakthrough in trade relations despite 
tensions over human rights and allegations of nuclear espionage by 
China. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials said Friday that negotiators have made  
significant progress toward opening China's huge market for 
American manufacturers, farmers and financial firms, something the 
administration says is critical to narrow a trade gap with China 
that hit a record $57 billion last year. 
</P>
<P>
	In return for China agreeing to open its markets, the United  
States would lift its objections to China's membership in the World 
Trade Organization, an economic prize the Asian nation has been 
seeking for 13 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Negotiations between the United States and China over WTO  
membership have intensified in recent weeks even as anger over 
China's human rights record and alleged nuclear espionage have 
risen in Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Both sides are struggling to complete a deal that could be used  
as the centerpiece for a Washington visit next month by Chinese 
Premier Zhu Rongji. The White House announced Friday that Zhu will 
hold high-level talks with President Clinton on April 8 as part of 
a nine-day visit that will include stops in five other American 
cities. 
</P>
<P>
	Zhu is eager to obtain WTO membership for China, and U.S.  
officials say China's market-opening offers have improved 
considerably since Zhu became personally involved in the 
negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States is seeking to break down sizable barriers to  
the sale of American exports of everything from wheat to cars to 
compact discs. The Clinton administration also wants permission for 
American banks, investment houses and insurance companies to expand 
their Chinese operations. 
</P>
<P>
	``China has made more progress in the last month than it had in  
the last three years,'' said one American trade official involved 
in the talks. 
</P>
<P>
	But this official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said a  
lot of ground still must be covered to achieve a deal acceptable to 
the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	A high-level team in Beijing, led by U.S. Assistant Trade  
Representative Bob Cassidy, is expected to continue negotiations 
over the weekend. Commerce Secretary William Daley will arrive 
there Monday, leading a trade mission that includes top U.S. 
business executives. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky is thought likely  
to join the talks either in Beijing or when they move back to 
Washington as officials try to close a deal in the days before 
Zhu's arrival. 
</P>
<P>
	But trade experts said they still believe a WTO deal this year  
would be a long shot, given the current deterioration in 
U.S.-Chinese relations, including recent allegations that Beijing 
stole U.S. nuclear secrets in the 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said  
Friday that the U.S. delegation to the U.N. Human Rights 
Commission's annual session in Geneva will introduce a resolution 
next month accusing China of wholesale violations of the human 
rights of its people. ``China's human rights record has 
deteriorated sharply,'' Rubin said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There has been real progress in the negotiations in a number  
of areas,'' said Greg Mastel, a trade expert at the Economic 
Strategy Institute in Washington. ``But the environment is so bad 
right now that it will be a tremendous uphill political struggle to 
sell even a good agreement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The WTO sets the rules for global trade. China first sought  
membership in 1986 in the WTO's predecessor organization, the 
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade. Negotiations for China's 
membership were nearly complete in 1989 when talks were put on hold 
following China's crackdown on the democracy movement. 
</P>
<P>
	To gain WTO membership, China must satisfy the United States and  
other economic powers that it will play by global trade rules by 
opening up its economy. Without U.S. approval, China's membership 
cannot go forward. 
</P>
<P>
	The new Chinese offers include proposals to cut high tariffs and  
other barriers restricting the sale of U.S.-manufactured goods and 
agriculture products such as wheat and citrus, to allow greater 
foreign ownership in such areas as telecommunications companies and 
to remove tight restrictions on operations by American banks. 
</P>
<P>
	WTO membership for China would mean protection against  
unilateral trade sanctions imposed by the United States or other 
WTO members as well as the prestige of being at the table when the 
next round of global trade talks begins this coming November in 
Seattle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
