<HEADLINE> Marsalis May Work With NY Orchestra </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Philharmonic's musical director is  
one step closer to his goal of working with jazz great Wynton 
Marsalis on an original composition. 
</P>
<P>
	Kurt Masur first spoke to Marsalis about a collaboration five  
years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``I heard something he composed for his band and what he did  
with improvisation and thought he was someone who might be 
refreshing to work with the Philharmonic. I wanted him to have a 
composition for himself and for us together,'' he said this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``He refused the first time. After two and a half years he  
called me back and said, `Maybe I can do it now.''' 
</P>
<P>
	The Philharmonic is collaborating with the Lincoln Center Jazz  
Orchestra, directed by Marsalis, for ``Uptown Blues: Ellington at 
100.'' The concert will be televised on PBS on April 7. 
</P>
<P>
	Next December, the premiere of Marsalis' ``All Rise'' will be  
played by the Philharmonic, Lincoln Center Jazz Orchestra and 
Morgan State University Choir. 
</P>
</TEXT>
