<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 13:35:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dubai Win Would Boost Silver Charm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DUBAI, United Arab Emirates (AP) -- Silver Charm can get closer  
to Cigar by winning the $5 million Dubai World Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	A second straight victory in the 1 1/4-mile race Sunday night at  
Nad al-Sheba Racecourse would be worth $3 million and boost him 
into No. 2 on the career earnings list with $9,803,066. Cigar is 
No. 1 with $9,999,815, with Skip Away second at $9,616,368 
</P>
<P>
	``Silver Charm is looking real good,'' trainer Bob Baffert said.  
``I expect him to run a good race and I expect him to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert, however, will not attend the race. While owners Bob and  
Beverly Lewis remain behind, Baffert was to fly by Concorde to the 
United States for Kentucky Derby hopeful Straight Man's start in a 
Kentucky Derby prep Saturday at Turfway Park in Kentucky. Straight 
Man also is owned by the Lewises. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver Charm, the 1997 Kentucky Derby winner, is one of three  
U.S. horses in the World Cup. The other two are Victory Gallop, 
winner of the 1998 Belmont Stakes, and Malek, a Chilean-bred who 
was fourth in this race last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver Charm was the 2-1 favorite by British bookmaker William  
Hill. Betting is illegal in Dubai. 
</P>
<P>
	Four of the eight starters are owned by members of Dubai's  
ruling Al Maktoum family. The other is British-owned and trained 
Running Stag, whose last four starts were in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The Maktoum horses, making their debuts in the race on the dirt,  
are English Derby winner High-Rise, Daylami, Central Park and 
Almutawakel. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver Charm, who will again be ridden by Gary Stevens, won his  
1999 debut, but has finished third in both his last two starts, 
including the Santa Anita Handicap March 6. Stevens takes the blame 
for that performance, saying he worked the big gray horse too fast 
the week of the race. 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert has a shot at becoming the first trainer to win three  
straight Kentucky Derbies. He won with Silver Charm, then with Real 
Quiet last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Straight Man is one three colts that are possible starters for  
Baffert in the May 1 Derby. Prime Timber is considered his top 
candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only horse I'm worried about is Worldly Manner,'' Baffert  
said. ``If he wins the Kentucky Derby, I think I might set up shop 
in Dubai.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Worldly Manner is a Godolphin prospect for the Derby, which  
would be his first start this year. He will prepare for the Derby 
in some trial races at Nad al-Sheba. 
</P>
<P>
	Dubai Crown Prince Sheik Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum said  
Friday that his family's decision to race in Kentucky would not 
lower racing standards in Britain, where Godolphin's horses have 
been a fixture at top races. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kentucky venture raised concerns about the sheik's long-term  
commitment to British racing. But Sheik Mohammed, who threatened to 
withdraw from English racing a couple years ago unless the purses 
improve, said England feels like a second home. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not quitting the races in Europe. I want to improve  
racing and don't want to see Great Britain lagging behind in 
racing,'' Sheik Mohammed said. The way to improve it, he said, is 
to ``do something about the prize money.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
