<DOCNO> APW19990326.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 14:50:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dems Challenge GOP on Bank Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Democratic leaders are challenging Senate  
Republicans to compromise on legislation to lift barriers between 
banks, securities firms and insurance companies, casting the 
dispute as a major test of bipartisanship in the new Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., Treasury Secretary  
Robert Rubin and Sen. Paul Sarbanes, D-Md., insisted Friday that 
community lending requirements for banks must be included or 
President Clinton will veto the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want financial modernization enacted this year. This should  
not be a partisan issue,'' Daschle told reporters. He said 
lawmakers must choose ``either a partisan brinksmanship or a 
bipartisan accomplishment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin attended to emphasize the administration's opposition to a  
Republican bill in the Senate while supporting the dismantling of 
Depression-era prohibitions against combining banks, insurers and 
brokerages. 
</P>
<P>
	Legislation proposed by both parties would create huge financial  
``supermarkets,'' offering consumers checking accounts, mutual 
funds, insurance policies and much more. Consumer advocates have 
expressed concern that the measures, by allowing banks, brokerage 
firms and insurers to merge and get more deeply into each other's 
businesses, could bring a dangerous concentration of economic power 
in fewer hands. 
</P>
<P>
	Backers of the legislation, including Wall Street, banks and  
insurers, insist it is needed to keep the U.S. financial industry 
competitive in a fast-changing global economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Daschle and Sarbanes, the Senate Banking Committee's senior  
Democrat, formally proposed a bill as an alternative to a GOP 
measure that cleared the committee in a party-line vote early this 
month. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the Republican bill, pushed by Banking Committee Chairman  
Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, banks would not have to get a 
satisfactory community-lending rating from the government to 
conduct new financial activities. The bill also would exempt small 
banks with less than $100 million in assets from the community 
lending laws, which require banks and thrifts to lend to the poor 
and minorities in their neighborhoods. 
</P>
<P>
	The Democrats' bill, as well as a bipartisan measure approved  
recently by the House Banking Committee, 51-8, include the 
requirement for a community-lending rating and have no exemption 
for small banks. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1977 lending laws have played a valuable role by ``expanding  
access to credit for all communities in our country,'' Sarbanes 
said, adding that they have helped many African Americans and other 
minorities to become home owners. 
</P>
<P>
	Gramm has maintained that the government shouldn't dictate to  
banks what people or companies they can do business with -- a view 
that led him to block financial overhaul legislation last fall. The 
blocking maneuver by Gramm and Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., came 
after the legislation squeaked through the House by one vote, 
214-213. 
</P>
<P>
	Christi Harlan, a spokeswoman for Gramm, said Friday ``he's not  
willing to compromise on the issue of expanding'' the reach of the 
community lending law. Gramm is not pushing for its repeal, 
however, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Harlan noted that Gramm plans to meet soon after Congress'  
two-week Easter recess with Daschle, Sarbanes and Senate Majority 
Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., to discuss the legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a test,'' Daschle said. ``The Republicans in the House  
have already met that test.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
