<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NASCAR Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT WORTH (AP) -- Bobby Labonte is driving despite pain, but he  
insists it's not because he's a tough guy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ask my wife,'' Labonte said with a grin. ``I'm not very tough.  
I'm definitely not one of those tough Texans people talk about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite his protestations, the 34-year-old Winston Cup star gave  
more evidence Friday that he is indeed tough as nails. He took part 
in both practice sessions and then qualified second to pole-winner 
Kenny Irwin in time trials for Sunday's Primestar 500 at Texas 
Motor Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	Labonte, who fractured the tip of his right shoulderblade in a  
crash last Friday during a practice session for the Busch Series 
race, drove the first 45 laps in the Winston Cup race in Darlington 
last Sunday before giving way to relief driver Matt Kenseth. 
</P>
<P>
	Team owner Joe Gibbs, former coach of the Washington Redskins,  
knows something about toughness. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can tell you that it takes real mental toughness to work  
your way through the kind of pain that you have from that type of 
injury,'' Gibbs said. 
</P>
<P>
	Labonte spent four days this week working with trainers from the  
Carolina Panthers, rehabilitating the shoulder. He also had a 
special cast built to alleviate some of the pounding he takes in 
the team's Pontiac. 
</P>
<P>
	``The thing is I can lean back in the seat and it feels pretty  
good,'' Labonte said. ``The biggest problem I had last week was 
shifting, but once you get on the track, that's not a big deal. The 
biggest problem I have now is extending the arm to get it in 
reverse. But, hopefully, we don't need to do that very often.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kenseth will stand by again on Sunday, although Labonte said he  
would like to stay in the car to the end. 
</P>
<P>
	``You came to work this morning because you wanted to and I came  
to work this morning because I wanted to. I like what I do.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *CRASH CRUSH:* Despite major changes to the Texas track, the  
1 1/2-mile oval has seen a demolition derby so far for the Busch 
Series, which will race Saturday in the Coca-Cola 300. 
</P>
<P>
	After seven crashes in practice on Thursday, there were five  
more incidents on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Tony Raines was transported by ambulance to a Fort Worth  
hospital for examination and observation after sustaining a 
concussion in a crash on Friday in turn two on the 1 1/2-mile oval. He 
was later released. 
</P>
<P>
	There was also a one-car smashup by Brad Loney, who was treated  
at the track for a bruised rib and elbow, and another involving 
defending series champion Dale Earnhardt Jr. and Kenseth, who was 
last year's runnerup and is the current leader in the standings. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was coming around turn four when a car slowed down to enter  
the pits,'' said Kenseth, who is coming off a victory last Saturday 
in Darlington. ``Dale swerved to the right to avoid the car and ran 
into me. Our car should be fine for the race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earnhardt said, ``The car in front of me just slowed down and I  
tried to miss him. Then I hit the other car. My car is going to be 
fine. We'll be back out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not so his older brother, Kerry, who crashed on Thursday and was  
replaced in the car on Friday by Stanton Barrett. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for the ChannelLock Chevrolet said the driver change  
``is a decision by the owner, and it is not the result of an 
injury.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other Busch Series drivers involved in crashes on Friday were  
Joe Buford, who came away with a bruised knee, and Mark Green, who 
was not injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Winston Cup drivers, who began practice on Friday, were  
considerably easier on equipment. The only accident of the day for 
the senior circuit came when Ken Bouchard hit the wall during his 
qualifying attempt. 
</P>
<P>
	Bouchard had to be cut out of the car and was flown by  
helicopter to a Dallas Hospital, where he was reported awake and 
alert after suffering a concussion. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *TRACK SUCCESS:* Jeff Gordon has a chance in Sunday's race to  
cut the number of tracks where he has yet to win to just two. 
</P>
<P>
	If it's anything like the first two Winston Cup races at Texas  
Motor Speedway, it won't be easy for the two-time defending series 
champion. 
</P>
<P>
	Gordon has finished 30th and 31st on the 1 1/2-mile Texas oval.  
</P>
<P>
	``This has been a tough place for us, and we've had some bad  
luck, too,'' Gordon said. ``But, with the changes in the track, I 
don't see why we can't have a good weekend.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He was referring to the offseason reconfiguring and repaving of  
the track, which was widened in several places and had the 
transitions from the turns to the speedways made smoother. 
</P>
<P>
	Gordon has won at 17 of the 20 tracks where NASCAR's top series  
has run since he began his Winston Cup career in 1993. Besides 
Texas, the only other places where he has not visited victory 
circle are Las Vegas and Phoenix. 
</P>
<P>
	He'll start ninth in Sunday's race.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *MILESTONE:* Michael Waltrip, who got his first ride in 1985,  
will make his 400th career start on Sunday. The younger brother of 
three-time series champion Darrell Waltrip remains winless in 
Winston Cup competition. 


</P>
</TEXT>
