<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 05:46:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> It's Duke and the Forgotten Three </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- Signs and billboards all over  
Florida proclaim the arrival of the Final Four. 
</P>
<P>
	What we really have here is Duke &AMP; the Forgotten Three.  
</P>
<P>
	Yes, Mike Krzyzewski and the Blue Devils can make their case as  
one of the best college teams ever by winning their third national 
championship this decade. But let's not forget, the Dukies have 
company. Michigan State, Connecticut and Ohio State get a chance, 
too. 
</P>
<P>
	The Spartans (33-4) play Duke (36-1) in the national semifinals  
on Saturday, and should not be taken lightly. Mateen Cleaves, 
toughness personified, has never met a pressure shot he didn't want 
to take. Like Magic Johnson 20 years ago, Cleaves needs to win. 
</P>
<P>
	For UConn (32-2), a national title is all Jim Calhoun needs to  
consummate his splendid run as coach of the Huskies. Standing in 
the way is Ohio State, which used a little infusion of BC to help 
it forget all about last year's 8-22 season. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Jim O'Brien's best move since going to Boston College and  
playing for Bob Cousy was bringing sensational guard Scoonie Penn 
with him when he left. 
</P>
<P>
	Three of the Final Four teams have been here before, and  
Krzyzewski is making his eighth appearance. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once you get there, all bets are off,'' said Calhoun, whose  
teams lost in the regional final in 1990, '95 and '98. ``Now, very 
simply, you've got to make that one more stretch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some might say that another way to spell Duke is U-N-L-V.  
Krzyzewski has consciously avoided comparisons with -- or even the 
mention of -- the heavily favored 1991 UNLV team that his Blue 
Devils upset in the national semifinal before claiming Coach K's 
first championship. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never talked to them about the '91 Vegas team,''  
Krzyzewski said. ``Don't believe everything you read in the papers, 
OK?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Likewise, Krzyzewski wants to save the talk about Duke's place  
in history for later; Monday night, about midnight or so, at the 
earliest. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's for somebody else to decide,'' he said. ``It would be  
really dumb of me to even be thinking of those things right now, 
because we're going to have to play a hell of a game to beat 
Michigan State.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What of Duke's 31-game winning streak, the devastating 3-point  
shooting of Trajan Langdon and the inside presence of Elton Brand? 
Well, Michigan State has won 22 in a row, losing by just six points 
(73-67) to Duke in December in the Great Eight. It was one of only 
two times the Blue Devils won by fewer than 10 points. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think they're a much different team than they were the first  
time,'' Spartans coach Tom Izzo said. ``I don't mean with personnel 
or anything. Elton Brand didn't play well against us the first 
time, I don't know if it was us or them. 
</P>
<P>
	``Shane Battier has raised his game a couple of levels and Corey  
Maggette is raising his level a lot,'' he added. ``I think we're a 
different team and I think we're a lot better than we were then.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Calhoun and O'Brien bring quite a history into their semifinal  
matchup on Saturday. When O'Brien was at Boston College, his teams 
lost 20 of 23 to Calhoun's Huskies during an 11-year span. The 
UConn jinx, as persistent as a New England Nor'easter, ended with 
18 straight losses before O'Brien left Boston College to take over 
the Buckeyes' sinking program in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Ohio State (27-8) emerged from the wreckage of the Randy Ayers  
era under the leadership of Penn, the BC transfer who sat out last 
season. His matchup with UConn point guard Khalid El-Amin should be 
sensational. 
</P>
<P>
	Not coincidentally, UConn is 61-6 since El-Amin joined the team.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's uncanny how similar the point guards are,'' O'Brien said.  
``In their case, Richard Hamilton is the leading scorer, but Khalid 
is the leader. It's the same thing with us. ... Scoonie is the guy 
who makes us go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All the way to the Final Four, where guys named Scoonie, Mateen  
and Khalid will try to prove that Duke isn't the only name in town. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 14:55:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tyson Records Become Issue Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- Mike Tyson's psychological records became an  
issue again Friday when Nevada boxing commissioners argued for a 
new law that would keep almost all information about fighters and 
promoters given to the commission confidential. 
</P>
<P>
	Commissioners contended they needed the bill to keep the  
personal lives of boxers private and so Las Vegas can retain its 
place as the host of most major fights. 
</P>
<P>
	A press representative, however, called the bill a ``knee-jerk  
reaction'' to the release of Tyson's psychological records and said 
the public that buys tickets or makes bets on fights has a right to 
know about a boxer's mental and physical state. 
</P>
<P>
	``Can anyone say with certainty that the public dissemination of  
Mike Tyson's psychological reports caused any substantial harm to 
Mike Tyson?'' asked Kent Lauer, director of the Nevada State Press 
Association. ``I don't think so. In fact, I think the public 
confidence in the commission's decision on Tyson's license was 
bolstered by the release of those reports.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The action in Nevada came on the same day a Maryland judge  
praised the ``remarkable'' progress made by the former heavyweight 
champion, but rejected his request for a reduced sentence. Tyson 
must still serve 60 days in Maryland for violating probation for a 
1992 rape conviction in Indiana. 
</P>
<P>
	In the end, a Nevada Assembly committee decided to delete  
sweeping language keeping most records confidential. But it 
authorized an amendment to keep medical information not relevant to 
an application to box confidential. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee also approved legislation allowing the commission  
to grant a boxing license with restrictions. That also became an 
issue with Tyson when the commission wanted to grant him a license 
to box again -- with certain conditions -- but couldn't add the 
conditions because Nevada law didn't allow it. 
</P>
<P>
	Three of the five Nevada athletic commissioners appeared before  
the committee in Carson City to argue that records given the 
commission should not be made public without a court order. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to psychological records, the bill supported by the  
commissioners would have restricted access to medical and criminal 
records. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is in no way an effort to keep information from the  
public,'' commissioner Lorenzo Fertitta said. ``I believe it is 
good public policy to have this information open to the public. But 
there are certain circumstances where it affects our ability to 
regulate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other than the release of Tyson's psychological records prior to  
his relicensing hearing in October, commissioners cited no other 
case in which there was a problem over the release of a boxer's 
information. 
</P>
<P>
	But commissioner Glenn Carano said that by assuring boxers that  
any information given the commission when it is licensing a fighter 
be kept private it will help the state get more big fights. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are the boxing capital of the world. The Nevada Athletic  
Commission is very highly regarded,'' Carano said. ``It is, 
however, a very competitive industry. We need the confidence of 
everybody we do business with -- that includes the boxers and 
promoters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lauer, however, said that the present system has been in place  
for years and that Nevada has had no problems before. 
</P>
<P>
	``This information has been open for a long time now, and I  
didn't hear the athletic commission testify to any abuses of this 
open information,'' Lauer said. ``All of a sudden because of this 
Mike Tyson episode they want to make everything confidential.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson was ordered last September to undergo five days of  
psychological testing by a team of doctors at Massachusetts General 
Hospital before boxing regulators would agree to hear his request 
for a license to replace the one taken from him for biting Evander 
Holyfield's ears. 
</P>
<P>
	He went to court to try and keep the records closed, but a judge  
ruled that Nevada law made them public documents and they were 
released. 
</P>
<P>
	``How can you say that embarrassed Mike Tyson?'' Lauer asked.  
``It didn't. Mike Tyson does a good enough job of embarrassing 
himself in other ways.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 12:41:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Saint Louis Hires Romar As Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Lorenzo Romar, who turned around a struggling  
program at Pepperdine and was an assistant for 1995 national 
champion UCLA, today was hired as Saint Louis' basketball coach. 
</P>
<P>
	Romar replaces Charlie Spoonhour, who retired March 5 after  
seven years at Saint Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	```This is a coach's dream,'' Romar said.  
</P>
<P>
	The Los Angeles Times reported that Romar will earn about  
$400,000 annually, including shoe and television-radio deals. The 
newspaper said Romar made about $125,000 at Pepperdine. 
</P>
<P>
	Romar was 19-13 at Pepperdine this season, and 42-44 overall.  
The Wave earned a spot in the National Invitation Tournament, 
losing to Colorado in the first round. 
</P>
<P>
	Pepperdine was 10-18 the season before Romar's arrival and 6-21  
in his first season. But the Wave improved to 17-10 the next 
season. This year's team finished second in the West Coast 
Conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Romar's strength is in recruiting. As an assistant to Jim  
Harrick at UCLA for four years, he helped bring in Toby Bailey, 
Jelani McCoy and Charles O'Bannon, key players on the national 
championship team. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is a proven recruiter and his communications skills with  
his student-athletes are highly regarded,'' Saint Louis athletic 
director Doug Wollard said. 
</P>
<P>
	Romar played at Washington, then played in the NBA with Golden  
State (1980-83) and Milwaukee (1983-84). He finished his pro career 
averaging about six points and six assists per game. 
</P>
<P>
	Romar then played for Athletes in Action from 1985-92, serving  
as co-coach from 1989 through 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 10:35:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  French Tunnel Death Toll Hits 30 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHAMONIX, France (AP) -- Exhausted firefighters battled searing  
heat and poisonous smoke today in a tunnel under Western Europe's 
highest peak, searching through charred tractor-trailer trucks for 
victims of a blaze that killed at least 30 people. 
</P>
<P>
	The seven-mile tunnel under Mont Blanc, a major route connecting  
Italy and France, turned into an inferno two days ago, when the 
blaze broke out in a truck carrying flour and margarine. 
</P>
<P>
	Firefighters sprayed the area with coolant today, trying to  
bring down temperatures that at one point reached more than 1,800 
degrees in the tunnel, said Lt. Stephane Marcelin of the Chamonix 
fire department. 
</P>
<P>
	The extreme heat and smoke had such a deadly effect, said  
another fire official, Jean-Guy Laurent, that only two or three 
victims were able to find refuge in heat-resistant bunkers in the 
tunnel. The rest were found at the wheels of the cars. 
</P>
<P>
	Marie-Claude Bazile, a spokeswoman for the regional government  
of Haute-Savoie region on the French end of the tunnel, said 30 
people were confirmed killed, with nine bodies identified. 
</P>
<P>
	``There could be more, unfortunately,'' Bazile told The  
Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first fatal fire in the tunnel, which was the longest  
in the world when President Charles de Gaulle opened it in 1965. 
The Alpine tunnel is used daily by about 4,000 trucks. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking from his hospital bed, Chamonix fire chief Christian  
Comte said he'd spent five hours in the tunnel Wednesday, looking 
for his men. 
</P>
<P>
	``The smoke was very dense and the temperatures were soaring,  
but I knew that I had to go help them,'' he said from the 
Sallanches Hospital, where he was recovering from smoke inhalation. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking to the AP in Paris by telephone, Comte said he'd worked  
his way along the wall of the tunnel until he came to a group of 
six firefighters -- all lying on the ground with their jackets over 
their heads, motionless. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought they were all dead,'' he said. He helped them all  
leave, but one later died. 
</P>
<P>
	A fresh contingent of 52 firefighters and 17 vehicles began  
battling the blaze early today, said Haute-Savoie's governor, 
Pierre Breuil. French, Swiss and Italian firefighters were working 
from the Italian end of the tunnel because the wind was blowing 
fumes and smoke toward the French side. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said the temperature had been lowered to 158 degrees  
at a critical point in the tunnel. 
</P>
<P>
	Italian firefighters Thursday evening managed to reach the area  
where the blaze began, discovering five bodies in scorched cars, 
adding to the four bodies found the day before. They also passed 20 
destroyed tractor-trailer trucks and up to 11 cars. 
</P>
<P>
	The fire raised questions about the emergency systems in the  
tunnel, which is equipped with ventilation equipment and 20 bunkers 
designed to resist heat and toxic fumes, each of which can hold 
dozens of people. 
</P>
<P>
	Drivers in the two-lane tunnel can pull out every 1,000 feet in  
case of breakdowns or if they need to turn around. In addition, 
tunnel officials can send messages to drivers through an emergency 
broadcast system. 
</P>
<P>
	A truck driver who passed the burning truck claimed tunnel  
personnel did not take the situation seriously. 
</P>
<P>
	At the French end, according to Jean-Luc Lacave, the tunnel was  
still open, and at the Italian end, where he exited and reported 
the fire, there was little reaction from officials, who said they 
were aware of the blaze. 
</P>
<P>
	``They didn't take the fire seriously and they waited much too  
long,'' he told RTL radio. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not clear whether any of the emergency systems had  
suffered a breakdown when the Belgian truck caught fire, officials 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Michel Charlet, the mayor of Chamonix, the town closest to  
the French side, said the accident ``could not have been avoided.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``For a long time now, it has been said that the Mont Blanc  
tunnel is no longer adaptable to the traffic'' of thousands of 
heavy trucks per day, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	During the night, firefighters discovered that 100 yards of the  
tunnel's ceiling had collapsed, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Victims of the fire included two Italian employees of the tunnel  
operator, one firefighter and a couple from Lyon. The identities of 
the other victims were not immediately available. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-seven others suffered mostly minor injuries from inhaling  
toxic smoke. 
</P>
<P>
	French Transport Minister Jean-Claude Gayssot said the tunnel  
would remain closed for several weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
