<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Garciaparra Homers on First Pitch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. (AP) -- Nomar Garciaparra needed just one  
pitch to prove his batting stroke was in great shape. Now he hopes 
to show his elbow is just as healthy. 
</P>
<P>
	He hit the first pitch he saw Friday over the left-field fence  
in his first game since March 18. Then, on his third at-bat, he let 
one pitch go by before hitting another homer, also off Rick 
Helling. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes you close your eyes, it works,'' said Garciaparra,  
the designated hitter in Boston's 10-3 win over the Texas Rangers. 
</P>
<P>
	He hopes to return to shortstop Saturday, when the Red Sox visit  
the Tampa Bay Devil Rays. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll see what he feels like, but he's going on the trip,''  
manager Jimy Williams said. ``He'll play in some capacity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Garciaparra, the 1997 AL Rookie of the Year, last played  
shortstop on March 11 when he felt pain in his elbow after making a 
relay throw. He sat our three games, was DH the next four and 
missed three more before heading last Sunday for the West Coast 
where he was examined by two doctors. 
</P>
<P>
	The diagnosis was encouraging. He had tendinitis but no  
structural damage in his throwing elbow. 
</P>
<P>
	``He knows his arm,'' Williams said. ``He knows how he feels. He  
knows how he's supposed to feel, how he wants to feel. Will he be 
at that particular point at the outset? Probably not. But from the 
reports that he's OK, at least we're going in the right 
direction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Garciaparra said the injury never affected his hitting. That was  
obvious Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of people tell me I shouldn't hit the first pitch,'' he  
joked. ``I feel bad for those people. I felt like I ignored them 
and I'm sorry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Just to see Nomie get back to being right on track is really  
nice,'' said Pedro Martinez, who struck out 10 and allowed just one 
run in six innings, getting the win. 
</P>
<P>
	In 10 exhibition games, Garciaparra is 10-for-33, a .303 batting  
average. He has four homers, nine RBIs and 24 total bases. 
</P>
<P>
	He also had a game Friday that bore similarities to the one Mo  
Vaughn had for Boston last spring after also spending a Monday and 
Tuesday out of town before returning on a Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Vaughn, now with the Anaheim Angels, missed two days for his  
trial on a drunk driving charge (he was acquitted), returned to the 
lineup on a Thursday and hit three homers, including a grand slam, 
in a 12-9 win over Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	Garciaparra scoffed at the comparison.  
</P>
<P>
	``You get lucky,'' he said. ``I don't think about that. It's  
spring training.'' 
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:*Lou Merloni, who had the inside track on Boston's utility  
infielder job, was to return to Massachusetts to have his sprained 
left wrist examined this weekend by team physician Arthur Pappas. 
Merloni was hurt sliding into third base Thursday night against 
Philadelphia. ... Catchers Mandy Romero and Joe Depastino were 
returned to Boston's minor-league camp. ... Left fielder Jon 
Nunnally, acquired in a trade with Cincinnati on Thursday, went 
1-for-3 and threw out Tom Goodwin trying to score from second base 
in the fourth inning. ... The Red Sox' four homers gave them 31 for 
spring training. They gave up none Friday and have allowed an 
AL-low 14. 
</P>
</TEXT>
