<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 15:14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Shoots Down Two Yugo MiGs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO jets shot down two Yugoslav MiG  
fighters in Bosnia, thwarting an attempted attack on NATO-led 
peacekeeping forces, alliance and U.S. officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The confrontation outside Yugoslav territory was a dangerous  
broadening of the showdown between the Western alliance and 
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic over Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	The air-to-air combat came as Yugoslav media reported that NATO  
forces launched their first daylight attack on Yugoslavia. Air raid 
sirens wailed at midafternoon in Belgrade and several other cities, 
and targets were hit in three suburbs of the capital, the official 
Tanjug news agency and independent Studio B television reported. 
</P>
<P>
	People in the capital's center, however, said they did not  
immediately see evidence of the strikes. 
</P>
<P>
	In the fighting in Bosnian skies, NATO jets flying defensive  
missions ``encountered'' the Yugoslav MiGs and shot them down about 
five miles inside Bosnia, said Maj. David Scanlon. 
</P>
<P>
	Peacekeepers were searching for the pilots, NATO spokesman Jamie  
Shea said. Initial NATO reports said the men were captured. 
</P>
<P>
	Witnesses and local news reports said wreckage was scattered in  
three places along a narrow strip of Bosnia's Serb republic. The 
land separates the Muslim-Croat federation from the border of 
Serbia, the dominant Yugoslav republic. 
</P>
<P>
	But Yugoslav Foreign Minister Zivadin Jovanovic, speaking to  
Britain's Channel 4 TV News, denied that the planes went down. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whatever they say, it is not true,'' Jovanovic said, referring  
to NATO. 
</P>
<P>
	In bombing attacks Thursday night, NATO aircraft and missiles  
blasted targets in Yugoslavia, directing much of their fire on 
Kosovo, where fighting raged between Serbs and ethnic Albanians. 
</P>
<P>
	Western officials called the bombing, which began Wednesday, a  
successful start to forcing President Slobodan Milosevic to agree 
to a peace deal. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's not going to be one knockout blow, but day after day,  
if he does not stop his genocidal attacks on the Kosovo people, we 
will take larger and larger lumps out of his military force,'' 
British Defense Secretary George Robertson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslavia's army maintained its defiant tone, claiming it  
inflicted ``substantial damage'' against an ``overpoweringly 
stronger enemy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslavia's U.N. envoy said today that ``hundreds of  
civilians'' have been killed in NATO airstrikes which hit a 
cemetery for Nazi victims, two refugee camps and two youth hostels. 
</P>
<P>
	The claims made by Vladislav Jovanovic in a speech to the U.N.  
Security Council could not be independently confirmed. Yugoslav 
authorities in Belgrade have reported at least a dozen dead and 
dozens wounded. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslav forces continued their offensive on the ground against  
ethnic Albanians. International monitors and relief officials 
forced to leave Kosovo because of the bombing said they feared Serb 
forces were burning villages and killing ethnic Albanians or 
forcing them to flee. 
</P>
<P>
	Ethnic Albanian sources reported persistent gunfire overnight in  
Pristina, the Kosovo capital, and an ethnic Albanian human rights 
group said a political figure and a union leader were killed in the 
northern town of Kosovska Mitrovica. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.N. refugee agency said Kosovo refugees who crossed into  
Albania claimed that 20 men were shot to death by Serb forces 
evacuating the village of Goden in southwest Kosovo on Thursday. 
The account could not be independently verified. 
</P>
<P>
	``With only a handful of independent observers left on the  
ground, we are extremely worried about the plight of Kosovo's 
civilian population, which has already been through a terrible 
ordeal,'' U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees Sadako Ogata said in 
Geneva. 
</P>
<P>
	William Walker, the U.S. head of the 1,400-member monitoring  
mission that left Kosovo this week, also said the situation was 
deteriorating. The Organization for Security and Cooperation in 
Europe decided today to reduce Walker's mission created last year 
to monitor a failed peace agreement down to 250 people. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia failed today to muster enough support to pass a  
resolution in the U.N. Security Council demanding NATO stop bombing 
Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO officials said today that allied aircraft had flown 400  
sorties against Yugoslavia in the first two days of air operations 
and had struck 50 targets, all air defense and related facilities. 
</P>
<P>
	Bomb damage assessments were still being made, said Air  
Commodore David Wilby, briefing reporters at NATO headquarters. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're making steady headway just as we had anticipated,'' NATO  
commander Gen. Wesley Clark said on NBC's ``Today'' show. ``We've 
done severe damage to a number of targets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton appealed directly to the Serbian people today  
for support, saying Milosevic has imperiled their future and forced 
their ``sons to keep fighting a senseless conflict that you did not 
ask for and that he could have prevented.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There was no hint from Milosevic that he would back down over  
Kosovo, the southern province of Serbia. He cut off diplomatic 
relations with the United States, France, Germany and Britain, 
while Serbian authorities ordered journalists from NATO nations out 
of the country. Scores did so, but some were trying to return today 
after conciliatory statements from Yugoslav officials. 
</P>
<P>
	A Yugoslav army statement said the Thursday night bombing  
targeted military barracks, military airports, air defense systems, 
communications centers and command posts. It lacked specifics on 
any damage caused and claimed Yugoslav forces retaliated 
effectively. 
</P>
<P>
	``In an unfair airborne battle, acting against an overpoweringly  
stronger enemy, according to reports available, substantial damage 
was inflicted on the enemy,'' the statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilby denied that NATO had attacked Yugoslav military barracks.  
</P>
<P>
	``At the moment ... our only target is the integrated air  
defense system and facilities associated with that,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The strikes Thursday hit inside Kosovo around Pristina, Kosovska  
Mitrovica and the southwestern town of Prizren, media in Yugoslavia 
said. Serbian TV said three missiles hit a police station on a 
military base, injuring one policeman and leaving two others 
missing. 
</P>
<P>
	In Montenegro, Yugoslavia's other republic, there were reports  
of explosions at army compounds and barracks, as well as at an 
airport and radar facilities. 
</P>
<P>
	Tanjug reported that ethnic Albanian rebels had attacked Serb  
police in Djakovica, wounding one. 
</P>
<P>
	Pleurat Sejeu, spokesman for the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army in  
London, told BBC World television that Yugoslav MiGs were being 
used against ethnic Albanians, who make up 90 percent of Kosovo's 
population. 
</P>
<P>
	Sejeu said Serbs had rounded up thousands of displaced ethnic  
Albanian civilians in the central Drenica region and were marching 
them toward Pristina. ``Nobody knows what will happen'' to them, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	About 200 Kosovo Albanians crossed into Albania on Thursday,  
saying Serb security forces had swept into the village of Goden, 
detaining men, setting the village on fire, and marching women and 
children across the border. 
</P>
<P>
	Selim Ferraj, 37, one of the few males with the group from  
Goden, said he feared the other men were dead. ``I am only alive 
because I knew the Serb commander before,'' said Ferraj, who 
escaped with his wife and five children. 
</P>
<P>
	Romanian Prime Minister Radu Vasile said today that Romania  
plans to accept up to 4,000 refugees from Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	A day after appearing to waver on the NATO strikes, Italian  
Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema said today that Italy will stand 
firm with alliance -- but also push to resume talks. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of a freeze on all relations with NATO, Russia today  
told NATO's top diplomatic official and its senior military 
representative in Moscow to leave the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
