<DOCNO> APW19990326.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 05:25:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Panel Passes Satellite Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Most satellite TV customers, for the first  
time, could watch their local broadcast stations on their satellite 
systems under a bill passed Thursday by the House Commerce 
Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill, approved without dissent, is meant to resolve a  
dispute between satellite companies and broadcasters over the 
conditions under which viewers who get their TV from satellite can 
watch broadcast programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Satellite TV companies are not supposed to beam local TV  
stations to customers who use either pizza-sized dishes or big 
``backyard'' dishes, although one company, EchoStar, does in a few 
markets. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill makes clear that satellite providers legally may carry  
local signals. Eventually, companies would have to carry all local 
stations in a given market by 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is supposed to be merged with a similar measure from  
the House Judiciary Committee. The merged bill could go to the 
House for a vote next month. The Senate also may vote on a 
satellite TV bill next month. 
</P>
<P>
	The bills aim to help make satellite companies stronger  
competitors to cable TV providers, which carry local TV signals. 
That, in turn, should serve as a check on cable rates, which will 
be deregulated next week. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill also would direct the Federal Communications Commission  
to look into whether there is a better way of determining which 
satellite TV customers are eligible to receive broadcast network 
programs from ``distant'' network affiliates. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal law lets satellite companies provide customers with  
``distant'' network signals -- which come from other broadcast areas 
-- only if those customers cannot receive their local stations using 
rooftop antennas. 
</P>
<P>
	But the satellite and broadcasting industries have been at odds  
for years over how to interpret the arcane legal test that 
determines when a satellite customer cannot get a local signal and 
thus is eligible to receive network programming by satellite. 
</P>
<P>
	The major TV networks and DirecTV, the nation's largest  
satellite TV company, recently agreed to delay a deadline for 
cutting off ineligible satellite customers from network signals. 
Given that, the committee's bill does not include a provision 
addressing this matter as a previously approved version of the bill 
had. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, that agreement deal does not stop as many as 500,000  
customers who own big backyard satellite dishes from being cut off 
from network programs on April 30. 
</P>
<P>
	If the industries do not voluntarily avert this cutoff, Rep.  
Billy Tauzin, R-La., will insert a provision into the bill that 
will, spokesman Ken Johnson said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
