<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Begins More Airstrikes  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- For a third night, American-led NATO forces  
have launched airstrikes against Yugoslavia. Serb military sites 
were the targets of air-launched cruise missiles and U.S. stealth 
fighter jets, the Pentagon said. NATO was hitting numerous targets 
in the Yugoslav capital Belgrade's suburbs in what appeared to be 
the strongest attack so far. It began with cruise missile fired by 
B-52 bombers. F-117 stealth fighter jets equipped with laser-guided 
munitions also took part. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Shoots Down Two Yugo MiGs  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In the first spillover of NATO's air war with  
Yugoslavia beyond its borders, two U.S. Air Force F-15 fighters 
shot down two Yugoslav MiG-29 jets in Bosnia today, officials said. 
Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said it was not immediately clear 
why the Russian-built MiGs had crossed into Bosnian airspace, but 
he said it was possible they had intended to attack NATO 
peacekeeping troops in Bosnia. The shootdowns brought to five the 
number of Yugoslav MiG-29s destroyed since NATO's air campaign 
began on Wednesday. 

</P>
<P>
	Anti-NATO Protests Target Embassies  
</P>
<P>
	ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- Protesters opposed to NATO attacks on  
Yugoslavia directed their anger at American sites around Europe 
today, drenching olive branches in red dye and calling President 
Clinton a ``fascist.'' Up to 10,000 people in Bulgaria gathered in 
the nation's capital of Sofia to protest the NATO airstrikes. In 
Greece, a NATO member, 15,000 protesters marched to the U.S. 
Embassy. The U.S. and British embassies in Moscow were also the 
scene of demonstrations. And riot police blocked demonstrators 
trying to reach the American Embassy in Skopje, Macedonia. 

</P>
<P>
	Kevorkian Convicted of Murder  
</P>
<P>
	PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) -- Dr. Jack Kevorkian was convicted of  
second-degree murder today for giving an ailing man a lethal 
injection and putting it all on videotape. Kevorkian, 70, could get 
a life term at sentencing April 14 for the death of 52-year-old 
Thomas Youk, who suffered from Lou Gehrig's disease. The jury 
rejected his defense that some acts ``by sheer common sense are not 
crimes.'' Kevorkian also was convicted of delivery of a controlled 
substance, which carries up to seven years. 

</P>
<P>
	Pastor Found Guilty in Gay Marriage  
</P>
<P>
	DOWNERS GROVE, Ill. (AP) -- A Methodist minister who officiated  
at the ``marriage'' of two gay men was convicted in a church trial 
today of disobedience in the first test of the denomination's ban 
on same-sex ceremonies and could be defrocked. The jury of 13 
pastors decided 10-3 that the Rev. Gregory Dell disobeyed church 
law when he presided over the ``holy union'' of the Chicago men 
last September. Immediately after the verdict, the penalty phase of 
the trial began. 

</P>
<P>
	Safety of Diabetes Drug Reviewed  
</P>
<P>
	BETHESDA, Md. (AP) -- Unable to determine exactly how risky a  
controversial diabetes drug is, scientists advised the government 
today to restrict how doctors prescribe Rezulin, in hopes that only 
diabetics who need it most will risk deadly liver damage. ``This is 
not to be used ever as a first-line drug for diabetes,'' said Dr. 
Jules Hirsch of Rockefeller University. He stressed that patients 
should try Rezulin only after finding that other, less-risky 
therapies don't work. 

</P>
<P>
	Russia Won't Cooperate on Y2K Bug  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In another show of protest over the fighting in  
Kosovo, Russia's Defense Ministry said today it will stop 
cooperating with the United States on the Y2K computer problem. In 
Washington, Sen. Robert F. Bennett, chairman of the Senate Special 
Committee on the Year 2000 Technology Problem, urged Russia to 
reconsider. Western defense officials have been working with Russia 
on upgrading its computers for fear that the cash-starved country 
has not done enough to tackle the millennium bug. Some fear that 
faulty computers could trigger false alarms on Russia's nuclear 
early warning systems. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Falls 14.15 to 9,822.24  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices drifted lower today in sluggish  
trading as investors adjusted their holdings before the end of the 
quarter and kept an eye on NATO air strikes in Kosovo. The Dow 
industrials closed down 14.15 at 9,822.24. Declines on the NYSE 
beat advances 1,609-1,358. The Nasdaq finished at 2,419.17, down 
15.63. 

</P>
<P>
	Ozaki Leads in Players Golf  
</P>
<P>
	PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Golfer Joe Ozaki shot a 4-under  
68 today for a two-round 137 to take the lead at The Players 
Championship. Hometown hero David Duval missed a 4-foot birdie putt 
on the 18th, but still managed to piece together a 3-under 69 for 
138. Bruce Lietzke had a 68 and was two strokes behind, followed by 
Davis Love III (70) and a pair of two-time U.S. Open champions -- 
Ernie Els (67) and Curtis Strange (69). 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by JEROME MINERVA  
</P>
</TEXT>
