<HEADLINE> Jones, Johnson Win in SAfrica Track </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) -- World champions Marion Jones and  
Michael Johnson were impressive winners Friday at the Engen Grand 
Prix Summer Series. 
</P>
<P>
	A strong headwind slowed the times, but both sprinters were  
impressive. Jones started brilliantly in the 100 meters, and never 
was threatened, clocking 11.06 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was in shape to run fast,'' Jones said. ``My body felt in  
10.8 shape.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson also got out well, then eased up to win the 200 at  
20.41. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm feeling particularly good,'' Johnson said. ``The time is  
not significant in this wind, but I will be ready this year -- 
looking to win the world championship in Seville, Spain, over 200 
meters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the men's 100, Namibian Frank Fredericks, the 1993 world 200  
champion, won in 10.38. ``My goal is gold in Seville,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Olympic champion in the men's 400 hurdles, Derrick Adkins,  
started fast in a tough field, but clipped the seventh hurdle. He 
limped home in seventh, beaten by South African Llewellyn Herbert 
(49.01). 
</P>
<P>
	Other winners included triple jump world record-holder Jonathan  
Edwards of Britain, who leaped 56 feet, 9 1/4 inches, and Jerome 
Young, in the 400 at 45.31. 
</P>
</TEXT>
