<DOCNO> APW19990326.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 05:46:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Buckeyes Routine Same in Final Four </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- Scoonie Penn insists Ohio State is  
not superstitious. Don't believe him. 
</P>
<P>
	The Buckeyes' Final Four will be no different from the weeks  
leading up to it. No routine will be broken and no quirky detail 
forgotten for fear something bad might happen. 
</P>
<P>
	At team meetings, the players will sit in the same configuration  
of seats, always four across the front with the rest in the back. 
Penn will lead the Buckeyes on the floor for practice and in 
Saturday night's national semifinal with Connecticut and will 
always take the first shot in warmups. 
</P>
<P>
	The team trainer will tape ankles in the same order -- always  
ending with a tap on the bottom of each foot -- and the Buckeyes 
will unwind before the game by listening to their lucky boom box. 
</P>
<P>
	Nope, Penn protested, nothing odd about that.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's just been our routine the whole season. Now people are  
looking for the answer to why we're winning,'' he said. ``They ask 
if we're doing anything the same and we start talking, yes, we're 
doing the same things we've been doing all season. And they become 
superstitions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But what would happen if you weren't first on the floor?  
</P>
<P>
	``Nothing,'' Penn said. ``But I'm not going to test it.''  
</P>
<P>
	Coach Jim O'Brien can only shake his head and, like the rest of  
his players, follow Penn's lead. 
</P>
<P>
	``I find it interesting,'' he said. ``I'm not going to get in  
the way of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Buckeyes' craving for routine might have been a product of  
the team's choice of Final Four lodging. While the other three 
teams are staying in resort hotels, Ohio State is hidden in a 
remote, gated community that is patrolled by guards. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked why it switched from the Hilton to private condominiums  
surrounded by 6-foot fence, O'Brien said, ``Because it's too, too 
busy in there, too crazy. It has nothing to do with being 
paranoid.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Forward Jason Singleton said there is logic behind the team's  
superstitious nature. 
</P>
<P>
	``Scoonie took his boom box to Puerto Rico and we won that  
tournament,'' Singleton said. ``He didn't take it to the Big Ten 
tournament and we lost. So we put two and two together and we 
figure we've got to take it to all our NCAA tournament games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There is almost no end to the team's superstitions. Ken Johnson  
is always the last player out of the locker room. Tri-captains 
Penn, Singleton and Neshaun Coleman are the first players in the 
three-man weave drill in practice. Trainer Mike Bordner has worn 
the same suit for each NCAA game, with the small pins given to each 
participant arranged in ascending order on his lapel. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Brien said many of the team's peculiarities stem from Penn's  
desire for order. 
</P>
<P>
	``He likes direction, he likes organization,'' O'Brien said.  
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in the year, to break up the monotony of another  
repetitious series of drills, O'Brien decided to shake things up. 
</P>
<P>
	``In my infinite wisdom I decided, why don't we just have  
shooting games instead and make it a little bit light?'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	A few practices later, O'Brien asked the team what it wanted to  
do in practice. 
</P>
<P>
	``Scoonie said, `No shooting games! Let's do our routine and do  
it the same way we always do,''' O'Brien said. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the team's superstitious nature that allowed O'Brien to  
keep his hair. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the tournament began, everyone on the team agreed to  
shave his head if the Buckeyes made it to the Final Four. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Brien showed up Sunday after the win over St. John's in the  
South Regional title game and asked who was going to lose his hair 
first. Not wanting to break up its routine, the team agreed they 
wouldn't go through with it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said, `Great. That's terrific,' because I really did not  
want to have to shave my head,'' O'Brien said with a laugh. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 16:14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Joe Torre Returns to Legends Field </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- A smiling and tan Joe Torre returned to  
Legends Field on Friday, meeting with his players and coaches for 
the first time since prostate cancer surgery at Barnes-Jewish 
Hospital in St. Louis on March 18. 
</P>
<P>
	Torre talked with his players about five minutes during a  
closed-door meeting. He also met with his coaching staff in the 
manager's office for 45 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought it was important for them to see that I'm feeling  
fine and that it's just a matter of time,'' the New York Yankees 
manager said. ``I asked them if there were any questions, I'd be 
around.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Torre will continue recuperating from the surgery in Florida  
until heading to New York around the time of home opener April 9 
against Detroit. Torre also plans on coming to the ballpark either 
daily or two of every three days during the remaining week of 
spring training. 
</P>
<P>
	``By that time, the 8th or 9th, I may be visible but I'm not  
going to be directing the team,'' Torre said. ``Don Zimmer has done 
enough of that during his career -- a lot longer than I have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Zimmer is the team's interim manager until Torre returns.  
</P>
<P>
	``That's the first time I've felt natural ... seeing him sitting  
behind his desk,'' Zimmer said. ``He's going to get stronger every 
day. Up to this point, he's made a great recovery.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. William Catalona, who performed the surgery, said it's  
normally 6-to-12 weeks before patients go back to work. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to come back and suddenly be washed out and have  
to take a few days off,'' Torre said. ``We'll go according to how I 
feel and how I maintain my strength.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Torre planned on visiting his team early next week, but moved up  
his visit after consulting with his doctor. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been progressing every day, and I talked to my doctor  
yesterday and he said, `Why don't you go tomorrow?' '' Torre said. 
``After he said that, that's all I needed to hear. There's not much 
you can do. I walk and eat. He just thought I needed a little 
stimulation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Torre's visit caught his players off guard.  
</P>
<P>
	``It was great. I was surprised to see him,'' Yankees second  
baseman Chuck Knoblauch said. 
</P>
<P>
	Even more surprising was Torre's condition.  
</P>
<P>
	``He looked like he was ready to manage right now,'' pitcher  
David Cone said. ``Obviously he needs time. It's remarkable the guy 
look great. He's well on the road to recovery.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As expected, Torre feels weak later in the day. That's why he  
doesn't want to rush his return. 
</P>
<P>
	``This sure puts things in the proper perspective,'' Torre said.  
``You try and do that, but you get so involved that winning is the 
most important thing in the world. I sense it will be again once I 
get back into uniform.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Torre took part in Thursday's organizational meeting and will  
take part in sessions as the team prepares to make roster cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	Pathology reports indicate Torre's cancer was limited to the  
prostate gland and did not spread. Torre will undergo tests within 
the next month, at his own request, to see if any additional 
treatment is needed. 
</P>
<P>
	Torre called his experience away from spring training ``weird.''  
</P>
<P>
	``I've always wondered what people did during the day in spring  
training and now I've found out,'' Torre said. ``Sit out, get some 
sun and play scrabble.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
