<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cops Let Suspected Dealer Flee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- In a sort of drug-bust-in-reverse, police  
accidentally let a suspected dealer get away with $17,000 in 
cocaine they supplied. 
</P>
<P>
	After a two-month search, U.S. marshals arrested the suspect  
last week. But the cocaine is still missing. 
</P>
<P>
	The incident occurred Jan. 15, when an undercover officer posing  
as a dealer met with a man in a restaurant parking lot and sold him 
a kilo, or 2.2 pounds, of the drug. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty officers were watching, waiting to move in when the  
undercover officer signaled for an arrest. But the officers had 
trouble with their radios, and no one was able to see the exchange 
well, an unidentified source told the Seattle Post-Intelligencer. 
</P>
<P>
	The suspect -- who got a good deal, paying less than street value  
-- left in a car. 
</P>
<P>
	Two backup officers from Bellevue pursued the man but cut off  
the chase for safety reasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Timothy Meadows, 45, was finally arrested at a restaurant. He  
told police he threw away the cocaine on Interstate 405. Detectives 
and drug-sniffing dogs scoured the area but never found it. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reality is that we do this kind of thing 99 percent of the  
time successfully. I wish it would be successful 100 percent of the 
time. But it's not an exact science,'' Assistant Chief Clark 
Kimerer said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
