<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Examples of Cable TV Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Examples of companies' plans for cable TV rates this year:  
</P>
<P>
	--Time Warner, which runs the nation's largest cable TV company  
with 12.6 million customers, announced price increases this year of 
no more than 4.9 percent, said spokesman Mike Luftman. 
</P>
<P>
	The average customer's bill, consisting of expanded basic,  
set-top box and remote rental and a couple of premium channels, is 
expected to go up less than 4 percent, Luftman said, adding that no 
price changes will occur because of deregulation. 
</P>
<P>
	--AT&AMP;T-owned Tele-Communications Inc., which runs the  
second-largest chain of cable TV systems, said its customers can 
expect some price adjustments after deregulation, said spokeswoman 
Lela Cocoros. She couldn't give any specifics for increases this 
year but said the company wants to minimize them. 
</P>
<P>
	--Comcast, the third-ranked cable company, has said it would  
raise rates 5 percent this year, and says its takeover of another 
cable provider, MediaOne, will not change those plans. 
</P>
<P>
	--Cablevision Systems Corp., the nation's sixth-largest cable TV  
company, announced price increases this year averaging about 5 
percent, said spokesman Charlie Schueler. 
</P>
<P>
	But some customers could get rate reductions. Customers on New  
York's Long Island who buy a bundled package of telephone and cable 
services and spend more than $50 a month on just their phone 
service will get their cable TV service discounted, he said. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
