<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wheat Rises Sharply / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Wheat and corn furtures rose Friday on the  
Chicago Board of Trade amid expectations that next week's report on 
spring planting plans will show farmers turning toward more 
profitable crops. Soybeans retreated. 
</P>
<P>
	The report Wednesday from the Agriculture Department will  
provide the first concrete estimate of whether farmers intend to 
plant more soybeans over corn and wheat. 
</P>
<P>
	Market participants are expecting spring wheat acreage to suffer  
most as farmers turn toward crops that have a better chance of 
selling overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat also found continued support from talk that the Clinton  
administration is considering a one-time exemption to the ban on 
exports to Iran and other countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures moved higher in step with wheat, while soybeans  
were pressured by expectations for a large American crop that will 
have to compete for sales with bumper South American crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery rose 6 cents to $2.98 3/4 a bushel; May  
corn rose 2 1/2 cents to $2.32 1/4 a bushel; May oats rose 2 3/4 cents to 
$1.22 3/4 a bushel; May soybeans fell 2 1/4 cents to $4.96 3/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Meat and livestock futures were mostly higher on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	April live cattle rose 0.67 cent to 66.62 cents a pound; April  
feeder cattle rose 0.50 cent to 71.55 cents a pound; April lean 
hogs fell 0.15 cent to 43.95 cents a pound; May pork bellies rose 
0.98 cent to 57.20 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
