<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Will Refinery Blasts Raise Gas Cost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Gas prices surged in California following  
last month's deadly explosion at a Tosco refinery, and analysts say 
Thursday's fire at a Chevron plant may well send them higher. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're going to go up a lot,'' said Michael Mayer, a  
securities analyst who follows Chevron Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	No one was injured in the explosion Thursday afternoon at the  
Chevron plant in Richmond, which sent a huge pillar of black smoke 
across the Bay area. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at the Chevron plant said the refinery would remain  
open, while the unit where the fiery explosion occurred was shut 
down indefinitely. 
</P>
<P>
	The refinery can produce up to 240,000 gallons of crude oil  
daily, said Chevron spokeswoman Dawn Soper. She would not say how 
the unit's closure would impact production there. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this point I couldn't speculate on anything regarding  
pricing,'' Soper said. With refineries in El Segundo and elsewhere, 
``we don't expect what happened today to have a significant affect 
on our customers including those at the pump.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But production already is crippled in the state, with at least  
three other refineries operating at less than 100 percent capacity, 
said Jay McKeeman, executive vice president of the California 
Independent Oil Marketers Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Various refinery shutdowns in California mean about 250,000 to  
300,000 gallons a day are cut out of the state's normal daily 
supply of 2 million gallons, according to Chevron spokesman Jack 
Coffey. Tosco's Avon plant alone usually produces 160,000 gallons a 
day. 
</P>
<P>
	``The problem is one in a continuing series of problems,''  
McKeeman said. ``California is a huge petroleum consumer entity, 
(buying) 13 billion gallons of gasoline a year. It needs a lot of 
refining capacity a year to meet that demand. Anytime there's a 
glitch in the system you get a problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Feb. 23, the day of the blast at the Tosco Avon refinery that  
killed four workers and left another man critically injured, prices 
shot up 16 cents -- to $1.18 a gallon on the West Coast -- before 
sliding back down to about $1.02 per gallon. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices for regular gasoline were about $1.30 a gallon or more in  
the San Francisco Bay area this week, compared to about $1.12 on 
the West Coast overall, according to the U.S. Energy Department. 
</P>
<P>
	California motorists face unique concerns when buying gas  
because laws require it to be specially formulated and most of what 
they purchase is produced in the state. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can't immediately get access to other supplies of fuel,''  
McKeeman said. ``It's going to cost more; there's delays in getting 
conforming fuel in the state.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just how much supply could be affected is an open question,  
McKeeman said. The refineries experiencing various problems -- which 
also include an Arco facility in the Los Angeles area and an Exxon 
site in Benicia -- account for as much as half of the state's fuel 
production. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it's true that close to half of the refining capacity in  
the state is at risk, yeah, there's a very definite problem of 
supply shortages,'' McKeeman said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 20:32:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Okla. Prosecutors To Charge Nichols </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- Terry Nichols, serving a life sentence  
after his federal conviction as a conspirator in the Oklahoma City 
bombing, will be charged with murder in state court next week, the 
district attorney said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Oklahoma County District Attorney Bob Macy said 160 counts of  
first-degree murder will be filed against Nichols as early as 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, a federal jury in Denver found Nichols, 43, guilty of  
conspiring to bomb the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building and of 
eight counts of involuntary manslaughter in the deaths of federal 
law officers killed in the blast. 
</P>
<P>
	The state charges represent the other victims of the April 19,  
1995, bombing, which killed a total of 168 people. 
</P>
<P>
	Co-defendant Timothy McVeigh was convicted of first-degree  
murder, conspiracy and weapons-related charges. McVeigh was 
sentenced to death. 
</P>
<P>
	Macy said his office likely won't file state charges against  
McVeigh unless it looks as though he will escape the death penalty. 
His sentence has been upheld by the U.S. Supreme Court. 
</P>
<P>
	Macy said he wanted to meet with victims of the bombing before  
formally filing charges against Nichols. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
