<DOCNO> APW19990326.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 13:05:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ligtenberg May Be Out for Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KISSIMMEE, Fla. (AP) -- Kerry Ligtenberg said Friday he will  
likely have season-ending surgery on his ailing right elbow, 
leaving a gaping hole in the Atlanta Braves' bullpen. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm trying to remain positive, but I just don't think it's  
going to heal by itself,'' Ligtenberg said before Friday's 
exhibition game against Montreal. ``There's no sense in putting it 
off. If I get it done now, I can be back for the opener next 
season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ligtenberg was diagnosed with a partial tear of the medial  
collateral ligament in his right elbow March 10, two days after 
allowing five runs in the ninth inning of a spring game against 
Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	The right-hander was asked not to throw for at least three weeks  
and then be reexamined. But he said trainer Dave Pursley ``pushed 
on it yesterday where the ligament is, and it's pretty tender. 
</P>
<P>
	``He told me if it were him, he would get the surgery done. So,  
I'm leaning toward that,'' Ligtenberg said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Braves orthopedic surgeon Dr. Joe Chandler will be at  
training camp Sunday. ``Hopefully he'll let me throw some and we'll 
see.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ligtenberg had a breakthrough year in 1998, taking over the  
closer's role after Mark Wohlers experienced control problems and 
was sent to the minors. The former independent league player, once 
traded for a bag of baseballs, wound up with 30 saves in 34 
chances. 
</P>
<P>
	Wohlers struggled to find the strike zone last season after  
injuring his side last May. He was 0-1 with a 10.18 ERA with 
Atlanta, walking 33 in 20.1 innings. At Triple A Richmond, he was 
worse, going 0-3 with a 20.43 ERA, walking 36 in 12.1 innings. 
</P>
<P>
	Wohlers, in seven appearances this spring, has allowed eight  
hits, five runs, walked six and struck out eight in seven innings 
and lowered his ERA to 7.71. He pitched two scoreless innings 
Thursday night for his best outing of the spring. 
</P>
<P>
	John Rocker, who was 1-3 in 47 games last year for Atlanta with  
a 2.13 ERA in 38 innings, will likely begin the season as the 
closer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
