<DOCNO> APW19990326.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 10:05:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Safety of Diabetes Drug Reviewed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BETHESDA, Md. (AP) -- Federal officials said today they have  
linked 38 cases of acute liver failure to the diabetes drug Rezulin 
and believe the risk of liver problems grows over time as patients 
take the drug. 
</P>
<P>
	In all, Food and Drug Administration officials have discovered  
43 cases of acute liver failure among Rezulin patients, 38 of which 
were probably caused by the medicine, the officials told a panel of 
scientific advisers weighing the drug's safety. 
</P>
<P>
	Of those 43 people, seven had a liver transplant and survived,  
five survived without a transplant and 28 died. Officials did not 
know the outcome of the other three cases. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, several doctors told the FDA scientific  
advisers that Rezulin helps many of their toughest diabetes 
patients, and the benefits outweigh the risk. 
</P>
<P>
	``No drug is 100 percent safe,'' said Dr. Steven Edelman of the  
Veterans Affairs Medical Center in San Diego. ``But diabetes is a 
serious disease.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Only an estimated 45 percent of Rezulin patients are getting the  
proper liver testing to detect problems in time to treat them, 
under the best-case scenario, said Dr. David Graham, an FDA 
epidemiologist. Thus, it's impossible to say if a better job of 
liver testing would save a significant number. 
</P>
<P>
	Very few Rezulin patients have used the drug for more than  
several months, but Graham argued that the longer patients do use 
it, the greater the risk of liver damage. Using the data that 
exist, Graham created a model to estimate that among people who use 
Rezulin for six months, as many as one in 1,800 could have liver 
failure. 
</P>
<P>
	The FDA believes it has received reports of only about 10  
percent of the liver damage that may have occurred among Rezulin 
users, because there is no law requiring doctors to report patient 
side effects. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no question that individual patients have benefited''  
from Rezulin, Graham said. But ``the longer you stay on 
troglitazone (Rezulin), the greater the risk of developing acute 
liver failure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 16-month debate over the safety of the novel drug, taken by  
750,000 Americans, has sharply divided diabetes specialists. 
</P>
<P>
	Of all the medications sold for type 2 or so-called adult onset  
diabetes, Rezulin is the only one that targets the disease's 
underlying cause. It has helped patients for whom other therapies 
failed and thus are at higher risk of serious complications. 
</P>
<P>
	But other specialists have stopped prescribing Rezulin because  
it can attack some patients' livers. On Monday, Britain ruled that 
Rezulin was too dangerous to sell in that country. 
</P>
<P>
	The Food and Drug Administration long has warned patients of the  
liver risk, and urges they get repeated, rigorous liver tests to 
catch early signs of damage. For many such patients, stopping 
Rezulin can reverse liver damage, FDA drug chief Dr. Janet Woodcock 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	But the FDA called the highly unusual safety meeting today  
because of the alarming finding that some patients who took all 
those precautions still died -- from severe liver toxicity that 
arose just weeks after they had passed a liver test. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel of scientific advisers is itself under intense  
scrutiny because some of the scientists have conducted research 
financed at least indirectly by Rezulin's manufacturer, 
Warner-Lambert Inc. The same panel enthusiastically backed 
Rezulin's initial approval in December 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	One opponent of the drug, consumer advocate Dr. Sidney Wolfe of  
Public Citizen, contends that ill-informed doctors are using 
Rezulin in ways that worsen the risk. How? By prescribing Rezulin 
to patients who are supposed to try less risky therapies first, and 
by not properly conducting liver tests. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are lots of people who are dead from this drug, and in  
most cases I think they're people who could have responded to 
something else,'' Wolfe says. 
</P>
<P>
	The FDA has spent months investigating more than 100 reports of  
problems among Rezulin users to sift out which patients' liver 
toxicity Rezulin actually could have caused -- and which diabetics 
may have become ill or died for totally unrelated reasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Warner-Lambert plans to ask FDA's advisers to allow more  
diabetics to use Rezulin, by letting the drug be combined with 
older diabetes therapies. 
</P>
<P>
	Even Rezulin's harshest critics don't expect the advisory group  
to take the drastic step of recommending that Rezulin be banned. 
But it has many options, from taking no action to recommending much 
stricter safety steps that could hinder how often doctors prescribe 
Rezulin. 
</P>
<P>
	The FDA typically follows its advisers' recommendations.  
</P>
<P>
	Regardless of the outcome of today's hearing, experts expect  
Rezulin sales could soon drop off dramatically because two new 
drugs that promise Rezulin's benefit without the liver risk are 
awaiting FDA approval. 
</P>
<P>
	About 15 million people have adult-onset diabetes. Their bodies'  
natural insulin gradually loses its ability to convert blood sugar 
into energy. Insulin and other medicines can help control many 
patients' blood sugar, but an estimated 1 million diabetics need 
additional help. Uncontrolled diabetes leads to kidney damage, 
blindness, heart disease and other complications. 
</P>
<P>
	Rezulin, known chemically as troglitazone, was widely hailed as  
the first drug to attack this underlying diabetes trigger by 
somehow resensitizing the body to insulin. Many patients need fewer 
daily insulin injections; some have even been able to quit insulin. 
</P>
<P>
	But the FDA has been issuing escalating warnings about the liver  
side effects since November 1997. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
