<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Phoenix 200 Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- The ghost of Tony Stewart lives on in the Indy  
Racing League. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart, who now drives for former Washington Redskins coach Joe  
Gibbs on NASCAR's Winston Cup circuit, got the attention of the 
popular stock-car owner by winning the IRL driving championship in 
1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Greg Ray, his replacement with Team Menard, found Stewart's old  
car to his liking on Friday, when he had the fastest lap during 
practice for the MCI WorldCom 200 at Phoenix International Raceway, 
averaging 173.653 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	``The car is not super special, but the conditions (wind) are  
bad enough that we are better than everyone,'' said Ray, who got 
the attention of Wisconsin lumberyard magnate John Menard by 
qualifying second with another team in last year's Indianapolis 
500. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if anything today means anything for tomorrow,''  
Ray said about qualifying for the second race of the IRL season. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott Sharp was second in practice with a 173.027 mph lap,  
followed by Scott Goodyear, John Hollansworth and Sam Schmidt, who 
did his 171.388 mph lap in the afternoon session. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *LOONEY TUNES AT THE TRACK:* Warner Bros. Studio Stores will  
sponsor Team Truscelli Racing's entry in 10 Indy Racing League 
races this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the arrangement announced Friday, the IRL practice day for  
Sunday's MCI WorldCom 200 at Phoenix International Raceway, the 
car, tractor-trailer and crew of driver Robert Moreno will carry 
the company's logo and featured Looney Tunes cartoon characters. 
</P>
<P>
	Appropriately, the introductory cartoon figure in Phoenix is  
Speedy Gonzalez. 
</P>
<P>
	Moreno, a Brazilian who took up residence in Monaco while  
driving in Formula One, is in his first year in the IRL. The 
40-year-old veteran last raced in eight CART events in 1997, then 
spent last season out of world-class racing. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *OLD NO. 99:* Brazilian Raul Boesel got a $10,000 check Friday,  
the first handed out under the Firestone First at '99 Award 
program. 
</P>
<P>
	Boesel was in Phoenix to practice for the 200-mile Indy Racing  
League race Sunday, but he earned the money during the Indy 200 
near Orlando, Fla., on Jan. 24. 
</P>
<P>
	The McCormack Motorsports ace led 19 laps at the Walt Disney  
World Speedway, but the 99th was not among them. He was running 
fifth behind Scott Sharp and three other cars equipped with 
Goodyear rubber. Boesel finished fifth in a race won by Eddie 
Cheever Jr. 
</P>
<P>
	The award will be presented following every IRL race this season  
as part of a promotional partnership between Firestone Racing and 
Tony George's Indianapolis Motor Speedway Corp. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *BRINGING JUNIOR ALONG:* Mark Dismore will have more problems  
than usual controlling his nerves Sunday before the MCI WorldCom 
200 at Phoenix International Raceway. 
</P>
<P>
	Dismore, who had the fastest time during winter testing in  
Phoenix, has to juggle his feelings about work and family while 
preparing to drive in the 200-mile event. 
</P>
<P>
	That's because his son, also named Mark, will be making his  
driving debut in a Formula 2000 support race earlier Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if I'll watch,'' Dismore said. ``I think I'll sit  
in the motor home and have my wife tell me what happened. But he 
should be able to do this. It's an educational deal; it's a 
school.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dismore, who usually takes second billing to Kelley Racing  
teammate Scott Sharp, had a 175.627 mph lap during testing four 
weeks ago. But he could only coax a 170.916 mph tour of the 
one-mile oval out of his car on Friday, the eighth-fastest practice 
time. 


</P>
</TEXT>
