<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 02:23:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gates: Push Technology on Employers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Bill Gates, the technology guru and head of  
Microsoft Corp., returned to the nation's capital to encourage 
college students to coax their future employers into adopting 
digital tools to improve business. 
</P>
<P>
	Gates, promoting his new book in a speech at Georgetown  
University, predicted that the next major high-tech advances will 
involve wireless networks, tablet-sized computers, speech 
recognition programs and software to let people collaborate on 
electronic documents. 
</P>
<P>
	Gates, wearing a Georgetown sweatshirt, recounted to students  
some ways that Microsoft helps employees work more efficiently, 
such as making sales figures available online and abolishing most 
paper documents. 
</P>
<P>
	Gates described telling his staff to bring to him binders filled  
with copies of every paper form the company used, from purchase 
approvals to benefits requests. 
</P>
<P>
	``I did something only a CEO really can do -- I said get rid of  
them,'' said Gates, who ordered the forms be made available 
electronically. ``In fact, the only ones we have left are the ones 
we have to fill out and send to the government.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He cited figures showing 153 million people worldwide --  
including 87 million in the United States and Canada -- use the 
Internet at least for e-mail. But he predicted a full decade may 
pass before most people get online. 
</P>
<P>
	``People tend to be evangelistic about the Web,'' Gates said.  
``This kind of evangelism, that's pretty much what's pulling people 
in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Use of high-tech tools by businesses is more common than by  
consumers. Gates said students already comfortable with technology 
should encourage their future employers to adopt digital tools to 
enhance their companies. 
</P>
<P>
	``Students lead the way,'' Gates said. ``It's really students  
who are driving this into business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gates also said:  
</P>
<P>
	--Technology may replace some jobs but those workers should be  
retrained. ``There is infinite demand for jobs out there. It's not 
like we're going to run out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--To serve customers better, companies ``should be able to call  
up every interaction with a customer in just a few seconds ... any 
phone call, any news, any insight that somebody in the company has 
about what that customer is thinking and what they might need.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But asked later about privacy concerns, Gates said, ``These are  
important political questions, and the rules need to be laid 
down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thursday's visit to Washington was the first by Gates since last  
summer, when he appeared with other software executives to talk 
about new laws the industry wanted from Congress. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
