<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO: Yugoslavia Defense Silent  
</P>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- Western officials said today that  
Yugoslavia's air defense system, which had caused concern before 
the NATO air attacks, have hardly been used. Air Commodore David 
Wilby of the British Royal Air Force said only one launch of a 
surface-to-air missile has been spotted and it wasn't successful. 
Wilby also confirmed that on the first night of the NATO air 
strikes, three Yugoslav MiG aircraft were shot down -- one over 
Kosovo, the other two over central Serbia. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Protests Continue in Macedonia  
</P>
<P>
	SKOPJE, Macedonia (AP) -- Riot squads pushed back demonstrators  
at the American Embassy today, a day after the mission was attacked 
with gasoline bombs and rocks. Police surrounded the compound, 
where U.S. troops strung up concertina wire and set up defensive 
positions. Sources said officials were considering banning all 
anti-NATO demonstrations. Macedonians have been showing increasing 
displeasure at the more than 10,000 NATO troops sent here to 
implement a peace agreement on Kosovo. Macedonian nationalists and 
members of the Serb minority in the former Yugoslav republic are 
sympathetic to Yugoslavia. 

</P>
<P>
	Russia Avoids Kosovo Confrontation  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- President Boris Yeltsin gathered his ministers  
today to discuss the Kosovo crisis, but Russia has refrained from 
directly confronting the West to help its ally Yugoslavia. Some 
Russian leaders have hinted that Russia could provide Yugoslavia 
with weapons, flouting an arms embargo. But the military's Chief of 
General Staff Gen. Anatoly Kvashnin said Russia could help 
Yugoslavia without using force. A military source told the Interfax 
news agency that Russia could provide Moscow's satellite 
intelligence. 

</P>
<P>
	First Lady Decries Abuse of Women  
</P>
<P>
	TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) -- First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton lashed  
out today at Islamic extremists in neighboring Algeria. ``We must 
speak up for the women and people of Algeria, who are victims of 
the war that is civil in name only,'' she said. In seven years of 
violence by Islamic radicals in Algeria, thousands of women have 
been raped, forced into slavery and killed in the name of religion, 
Mrs. Clinton said. She also decried violence against women in 
Afghanistan, where, she said, women and girls are being 
``brutalized by the Taliban once again.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Kevorkian Withdraws As Own Lawyer  
</P>
<P>
	PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) -- Dr. Jack Kevorkian said today he would  
stop acting as his own lawyer, and jurors resumed deliberating 
murder charges in the injection death of a Lou Gehrig's disease 
patient. Further legal matters in the trial apparently would be 
handled by attorney David Gorosh, who had been acting as 
Kevorkian's legal adviser. The jury resumed deliberations this 
morning after five hours of discussion yesterday ended without a 
verdict for the retired pathologist accused of killing 52-year-old 
Thomas Youk. 

</P>
<P>
	Body May Be Linked to Yosemite Case  
</P>
<P>
	FRESNO, Calif. (AP) -- A body has been found outside Yosemite  
National Park and the FBI was trying to determine if it was one of 
three female tourists who disappeared six weeks ago. A law 
enforcement source said yesterday the victim was female. The body 
was found just outside the park, where Carole Sund, 42, her 
daughter Julie, and Silvina Pelloso were last seen. Nearby is 
Sierra Village, where the burned bodies of two victims were found 
in the trunk of their rental car. One was identified as Mrs. 
Sund's. 

</P>
<P>
	P.R. Firm Tries Formal Fridays  
</P>
<P>
	EDISON, N.J. (AP) -- A public relations firm has taken Casual  
Fridays to the other extreme -- its employees wear tuxedos and 
evening gowns for Formal Fridays. Alison Pollak, director of media 
at the Pollak Agency, came up with the idea. Tired of having to 
dress up for client meetings while others wore jeans, she suggested 
that all 10 employees try dressing to the hilt one Friday. That one 
Friday led to another, and another. Some clients have started 
joining in, and the firm even landed an account from someone who 
read about Formal Fridays. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Slips 59.38 in Early Trading  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices have opened down. Just before 10  
a.m. EST, the Dow Jones industrial average was down 59.38 points at 
9,777.01 points. Losers on the New York Stock Exchange outnumbered 
gainers 1,012-607. The Nasdaq was down 18.59 at 2,416.21. 

</P>
<P>
	Women's Final Four Games Tonight  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Louisiana Tech faces Purdue in the Final  
Four of the women's NCAA tournament tonight. It's a rematch of last 
year's Midwest Regional final, which Tech won 72-65. Purdue beat 
Tech 71-65 in December in West Lafayette, Ind., and brings a 
30-game winning streak into the Final Four. Duke and Georgia will 
play in the other semifinal. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SUZANNE ROWLAND  
</P>
</TEXT>
