<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 15:05:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. To Accuse China on Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The human rights situation in China has  
``deteriorated sharply,'' the State Department said today, and the 
United States will seek a resolution to censure China at a meeting 
of the U.N. agency that monitors rights issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the past three months, Chinese authorities ``have initiated  
a crackdown against organized political opposition, dozens of 
political activists have been detained for peaceful political 
activities, and three leaders of the China Democracy Party have 
been given harsh sentences in closed trials that clearly violated 
due process,'' spokesman James P. Rubin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Chinese Embassy spokesman Yu Shuning said his government firmly  
opposes the U.S. action, which he described as interference in 
China's domestic affairs. He said the proper forum for a discussion 
of such issues is the U.S.-China human rights dialogue, which 
resumed in January after a three-year hiatus. 
</P>
<P>
	Yu said the United States has tried to censure China seven times  
at U.N. Human Rights Commission meetings in Geneva, and each time 
the effort failed. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they try again this year, they will fail again,'' he said.  
``We request the U.S. government to reconsider and change this 
wrong decision.'' This year's commission meeting opened Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. action further aggravates a relationship already  
burdened by disagreements over trade, Taiwan and U.S. plans to 
develop a missile defense system. Among other irritants are 
allegations of Chinese spying at the weapons development site at 
Los Alamos, N.M. 
</P>
<P>
	On the positive side, the White House announced that Chinese  
Premier Zhu Rongji will come to the United States April 6-14 on an 
official visit. The announcement had been widely expected. The 
administration hopes to use that visit to reach final agreement on 
China's quest for membership in the World Trade Organization. 
</P>
<P>
	An administration official, asking not to be identified, said  
China will attempt to block the U.S. effort in the rights 
commission by introducing a ``no-action'' resolution that, if 
approved, would forbid the panel from considering the U.S. 
proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the official, Chinese ``no-action'' resolutions  
have succeeded twice previously. On a third occasion, the vote 
ended in a tie, meaning that the U.S. resolution was placed on the 
agenda. The proposal nonetheless ended in defeat. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton decided against seeking a China resolution at  
the 1998 commission meeting, citing progress in the rights 
situation in China. It was the first time since China's crackdown 
on pro-democracy activists at Tiananmen Square in 1989 that the 
United States did not seek a China resolution. The House and the 
Senate took strong exception to the decision in lopsided votes a 
year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	This year's decision drew strong expressions of support from  
House Relations Committee chairman Benjamin Gilman, R-N.Y., and 
Rep. Nancy Pelosi, long an outspoken critic of China's rights 
performance. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin recalled that the latest annual State Department report on  
human rights conditions worldwide, issued last month, noted that 
Chinese authorities ``tightened regulations on publishers and 
newspapers, increased monitoring of the Internet, continued to 
restrict religious practice and intensified controls over Tibet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``These developments are a source of deep concern to the United  
States. They constitute a reversal of the comparatively more 
tolerant attitude toward political expression and association which 
Chinese authorities had begun to exhibit,'' Rubin said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said China has accepted international human rights  
obligations by signing the international covenant on civil and 
political rights. 
</P>
<P>
	``In its dialogues with the United States, the European Union  
and others,'' Rubin said, ``China has stated its intention to 
fulfill its obligation under these conventions and other 
instruments of international human rights law.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
