<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Paralyzed Racing Driver Finishes 2nd </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ALAMITOS, Calif. (AP) -- O.J. Waddell's shoulders were a  
little sore, his adrenaline running a little high, after coming in 
second in a $25,000 harness racing event at Los Alamitos Race 
Course. 
</P>
<P>
	A second place finish was good enough, said Waddell, who is  
paralyzed from the waist down and must be strapped into the sulky. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel kind of winded from the excitement,'' he said after the  
race, adding, ``I feel a little bit sore on my shoulders from the 
horse pulling but other than that I feel great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Waddell, driving Hutt Girl, finished 3 3/4 lengths behind  
Canterbury Tower in the mile race for fillies and mares. 
</P>
<P>
	The 38-year-old Waddell was at a party 18 years ago when a fight  
broke out. He wasn't involved in the scuffle but was shot in the 
back and left paralyzed. 
</P>
<P>
	For the race, his legs were strapped into the sulky, which  
prompted some concern from other drivers who say an accident on the 
track could put other drivers and horses in jeopardy. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I showed today that I do belong,'' Waddell said.  
``That was one of the most important things I wanted to do 
tonight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Waddell began training horses after his accident, learning the  
trade from this father. That work exposed him to harness racing. 
</P>
<P>
	Waddell was scheduled to race today, driving Laagin in an  
elimination heat in the $200,000 Arnold Pacing Series. 
</P>
</TEXT>
