<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 17:33:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grandchildren Remember DiMaggio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOLLYWOOD, Fla. (AP) -- Joe DiMaggio's four great-grandchildren  
accepted lilies from patients at the children's hospital bearing 
the Yankee Clipper's name on Friday, then told a memorial service 
about the man they knew simply as ``Big Joe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Most of us remember him as a hero, as a baseball legend,''  
Vanassa Hamra said as she took turns reading their eulogy with her 
sister Valerie and cousins Kendahl and Mitchell Stein. 
</P>
<P>
	Kendahl Stein, 11, followed by saying: ``We also looked up to  
him, but not as a legend. We looked up to him as our 
great-grandfather.'' She later said one of their favorite memories 
is of DiMaggio feeding turkey to their cats at Thanksgiving. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 300 people, including Florida Gov. Jeb Bush and a  
handful of former players, crammed into the small auditorium at Joe 
DiMaggio Children's Hospital to remember the Hall of Famer. 
DiMaggio died March 8 after a lengthy bout with lung cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Fellow Yankee Hall of Famers Phil Rizzuto and Reggie Jackson  
also offered eulogies. Also in attendance were former Yankees Clyde 
King, Phil Linz, Tom Tresh and Stan Bahnsen. 
</P>
<P>
	Dom DiMaggio, Joe's brother, sat in the back of the audience and  
did not participate. 
</P>
<P>
	``He had a great sense of pride,'' said Jackson, who got to know  
DiMaggio while winning two World Series with the Yankees in the 
late 1970s. ``He made any date special. He made the time that you'd 
spend with him unique.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rizzuto, who said DiMaggio took him under his wing when he came  
up in 1941, had the audience chuckling when he said he used to love 
watching the Yankee Clipper shave. 
</P>
<P>
	``He shaved with such distinction. It was beautiful to watch.  
Now it might be a little flaky to say that,'' Rizzuto said as 
laughter rang through the auditorium. ``But he was perfect in 
everything he did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A portrait of a smiling DiMaggio in a blue sport coat and blue  
print tie stood in front of the lectern, with five lily displays 
fronting the stage. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he was here right now, he would say, `Gosh, folks, this  
wasn't necessary,''' Linz said following the service. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, the auditorium was illuminated by candlelight as the  
hospital's young patients offered their thanks to the man who 
dropped by to read them stories and boost their spirits. 
</P>
<P>
	Clutching a lily in one hand and a hospital worker in the other,  
dozens of children lined up down the center aisle to present the 
flowers to the great-grandchildren. The flowers then were placed in 
a vase beside DiMaggio's portrait. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was a great humanitarian with a very special place in his  
heart for children,'' said Frank Sacco, the hospital's chief 
executive officer, noting that DiMaggio's only demand in return for 
lending his name to the facility was that no child be turned away 
because of a lack of funds. 
</P>
<P>
	``He did it with the same stature, grace and dignity as he did  
in baseball a half-century earlier,'' Sacco said. ``He did 
everything we asked of him, yet he remained humble.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another memorial service for DiMaggio will be held April 23 at  
St. Patrick's Cathedral in New York. Cardinal John O'Connor is 
expected to officiate at that service. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Yankees Roger Maris and Billy Martin also received  
similar tributes at St. Patrick's following their deaths. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
