<DOCNO> APW19990326.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 01:12:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Krzyzewski Has Final 4 Experience </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- It's natural to assume Duke has  
Final Four experience and won't be fazed by all the hoopla. After 
all, coach Mike Krzyzewski has been to eight of them since 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	But no player on this powerful Duke team has ever been to the  
Final Four. Same goes for Michigan State, Ohio State and 
Connecticut. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any nervousness that we may feel, we know the team we're  
playing against is also experiencing it,'' Duke's Shane Battier 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blue Devils (36-1) arrived at the Don CeSar resort on St.  
Petersburg Beach on Thursday afternoon, ready to take on the 
Spartans in the national semifinals Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``We took it as a regular road trip,'' said Battier, who emerged  
from the team bus with a camcorder while slapping a handful of fans 
high-fives. ``But as soon as we landed it was a pretty electric 
feeling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Krzyzewski received the largest hand from about 75 fans, and  
players milled around the hotel lobby signing basketballs and caps. 
</P>
<P>
	The bus ride along Interstate 275 took Duke past Tropicana  
Field, the site of this year's Final Four and the scene of a 
17-point collapse last season against Kentucky in the South 
Regional final. 
</P>
<P>
	``We drove right past it,'' Battier said. ``I got out my  
camcorder and on first feature film I say, `This was the spot we 
didn't take care of business last year but the good Lord has put us 
in a position this year where we can redeem ourselves.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Krzyzewski laughed when told Duke's hotel has housed many famous  
guests, including former Presidents Ford, Carter and Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know it's a great, great place,'' Krzyzewski said. ``I'm  
sure when I come back sometime with my wife I'll try to figure out 
who was here before me, but right now I'm trying to figure out how 
to stop Mateen Cleaves on a fastbreak more so than who stayed in 
room 602.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the best NCAA tournament record among active coaches,  
Krzyzewski has plenty of insights for his team about the Final Four 
and the experiences surrounding one of the nation's biggest 
sporting events. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think until you get into this for about a day, when  
you are around all the stuff, you really get a true feeling of 
it,'' Krzyzewski said of the hoopla. ``Then, when you come out on 
the floor Saturday, that's one of the best days in sport.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Duke has received enormous hype all season, being billed as one  
of the all-time great teams. That should help them cope with a 
hectic weekend filled with media scrutiny. 
</P>
<P>
	``I tell them just before we go into something what they going  
to experience for the next 12 to 24 hours,'' Krzyzewski said of his 
players. ``You tell them the truth and they usually handle it the 
right way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For Battier, who grew up in Michigan, being in Florida is fun  
enough. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't see too much sand growing up, so it's pretty cool to  
come and see girls in bikinis and see the sand,'' Battier said. 
</P>
<P>
	Could that be a distraction?  
</P>
<P>
	``One of the things this team has learned to deal with is  
putting distractions behind us and focusing on basketball,'' 
Battier said. ``We'll see the sun (Thursday) but after that we're 
going to be in the hotel watching film, and eating and sleeping 
basketball.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
