<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 14:05:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Speaker Hastert Chats Online </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Speaker Dennis Hastert misses being able  
to spend time around young people now that his new post keeps him 
away from home a lot more. So Friday, the former high-school 
government teacher and coach connected with local students via the 
Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Kids from the Illinois Republican's own alma mater, Oswego High  
School, even came back from their just-started spring break for the 
chance to have a live online chat with such a powerful alumnus. 
</P>
<P>
	``To talk with someone at that high a level of government on a  
Friday morning -- life is good!'' said Oswego Principal Ross 
Truemper. About a dozen seniors in advanced government class 
participated from the school about 60 miles west of Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	The discussion -- prompted by mostly prearranged questions --  
covered some of the hottest topics facing Washington these days: 
Kosovo, tax cuts, Congress' post-impeachment relationship with 
President Clinton, arts funding, and Hastert's predecessor, former 
Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga. 
</P>
<P>
	The seven schools, all in Hastert's district of Chicago suburbs  
and far-flung farmland, posed their questions in turn. At times, 
the hourlong discussion got ahead of itself as the next school sent 
a query before Hastert had finished his answer to the last one. And 
one out-of-turn school found itself chastened by another with a 
``point of order'' complaint. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked by DeKalb High School about the Kosovo situation, Hastert  
said he supports American servicemen involved in the NATO mission 
but wishes Clinton had explained how it would end, saying, ``Nobody 
knows for sure if this will be successful or when it will end.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also acknowledged that the $15 billion in tax cuts promised  
in just-passed Republican-written budgets may not materialize. ``If 
there are funds left over, they may be distributed through tax 
cuts,'' Hastert wrote West Chicago Community High School. 
</P>
<P>
	Hastert dodged a question from Dixon High School -- located in  
the Illinois prairie town where Ronald Reagan grew up -- on whether 
he thinks parents of children in private schools should get tax 
credits. Instead, he expressed support for public schools and for 
sending federal education dollars to states and local districts so 
they can decide how to spend them. 
</P>
<P>
	The speaker pledged to work with Clinton to ``get things done.''  
</P>
<P>
	Hastert defended the combative tenor of Gingrich's reign, while  
promising a shift under his watch. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even though those years were partisan, we accomplished a great  
deal for the American people,'' he said. ``I have great respect for 
Newt but I will run the House differently.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before the session began, Hastert said he is still struggling to  
get comfortable with the Web, but he allowed that he has two 
favorite Web sites: that of country singer Johnny Cash and, for the 
former championship-winning high school wrestling coach in him, one 
with wrestling scores and updates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
