<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Telecom Firm Lures Major Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- J. Patrick Barrett has made millions. He's  
courted by governors and senators. 
</P>
<P>
	Frank Zaccanelli moved from Syracuse to Texas 20 years ago with  
$300 in his pocket. Today, he helps oversee the Perot financial 
empire as one of Ross Jr.'s top lieutenants. He owns part of the 
NBA's Dallas Mavericks. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither man is easily impressed. Nor are they enticed by small  
opportunities. 
</P>
<P>
	But Telergy Inc., a 3-year-old, privately held  
telecommunications company, has managed to persuade both men to 
back its plan to become a giant in the industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``I saw great potential here, but even I admit I've been mildly  
surprised,'' said Barrett, a past chairman of the Avis car rental 
company and former New York State Republican Party head who now 
serves as Telergy's president. 
</P>
<P>
	``Internet access, data transfer, videocommunications, intranet  
service, cable television, are all merging into one service ... and 
someday it will all be delivered through Telergy's network,'' said 
Zaccanelli, who is on the company's board of directors. 
</P>
<P>
	Telergy is one of a new generation of fast-growing  
telecommunications companies looking to profit from the increasing 
need for network capacity, or bandwidth, said Paul Robinson, a vice 
president at Eastern Management Group, a New Jersey-based 
telecommunications consulting firm. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies sell space, or transmission capacity, on  
fiber-optic networks to other phone carriers. Telergy also resells 
local and long-distance service to about 3,500 business customers. 
</P>
<P>
	It is a high-risk business because of the cost of building the  
networks. Only the strongest, best-managed companies will survive, 
Robinson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Telergy founder Brian Kelly said it would still be a while  
before Telergy actually makes money. Since 1995, it has spent $200 
million building a fiber-optic network stretching from Montreal to 
New York City, the busiest communications corridor in the country. 
Eventually, the network will include the Cleveland and Washington, 
D.C. areas. 
</P>
<P>
	By the time it is finished, Telergy's network will have cost at  
least $500 million. 
</P>
<P>
	But the company is off to a good start, having struck  
multimillion dollar service deals with Bell Canada and Bell 
Atlantic Corp. It has also brokered novel right-of-way deals with 
three major utilities that give it access to 10 million homes and 
businesses in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Telergy's roots can be traced back to a part-time job. Kelly and  
his brothers, twin Kevin, and younger sibling, William, started a 
truck-washing business after the twins graduated from LeMoyne 
College in Syracuse. 
</P>
<P>
	To make ends meet, Brian began selling telephone equipment  
part-time. That experience led him to launch another small business 
selling disposable telephones to hospitals for patient use. That 
venture gave the Kellys a better idea, and in 1991 they started 
Telecommunications Management Systems to manage phone service for 
hospital patients. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, TMS serves more than 50 hospitals throughout the  
Northeast. 
</P>
<P>
	In the course of doing business, TMS obtained a certificate to  
resell long-distance to commercial customers. The Kellys envisioned 
something grander and formed KCI Communications. 
</P>
<P>
	Brian Kelly decided quickly that to be a major player in the  
telecommunications business, he had to get his own high-capacity 
fiber optic network going. So he approached Niagara Mohawk and made 
a deal to use the utility's right-of-way across upstate New York as 
the backbone of the system. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, New York's utilities were gearing up for  
deregulation and eyeing new ventures, with an especially keen eye 
on telecommunications. Thus, Telergy was born, and it soon had 
similar deals with New York State Gas &AMP; Electric and Consolidated 
Edison. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Telergy's utility deals put it in a good position in  
New York, its plan is not unique, said Milton Mueller, a 
telecommunications expert at Syracuse University. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the past three years, utilities across the nation have  
begun selling or developing their rights of way to build local 
telecommunications networks, Mueller said. MFS Network 
Technologies, a subsidiary of MCI WorldCom, is building a fiber 
network along 542 miles of New York State Thruway right-of-way, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Telergy's network-building strategy appears to be working,  
Mueller said, and with help from Barrett and Zaccanelli, Brian 
Kelly's vision may become a reality. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
