<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First Union Helps Minority Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE (AP) -- First Union is putting $5 million into a fund  
that invests in minority-owned businesses, joining a partnership of 
major corporations started by Earl Graves, the founder of Black 
Enterprise magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	The fund, Black Enterprise/Greenwich Street Corporate Growth  
Partners, recently received $86 million in commitments from other 
companies such as J.P. Morgan, Citigroup, IBM, Bell Atlantic and 
DaimlerChrysler. 
</P>
<P>
	Graves once served as chairman and chief executive of Pepsi-Cola  
of Washington, D.C., the nation's largest minority-owned Pepsi 
bottler. He is also a board member at numerous companies, including 
Aetna Life and Casualty Co.; AMR Corp., the parent of American 
Airlines; DaimlerChrysler Corp.; and Federated Department Stores. 
</P>
<P>
	His magazine, which now has a circulation of 300,000, was  
started with a $150,000 loan backed by the Small Business 
Administration. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
