<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 20:32:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> F-16 Crash Forces Flight Suspension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GLENDALE, Ariz. (AP) -- The Air Force suspended all F-16 fighter  
flights at Luke Air Force Base -- its largest training area for the 
jets -- after one of the planes crashed in the desert Friday. It was 
the fifth such accident at Luke since October. 
</P>
<P>
	Student pilot Capt. Michael G. Rider, 27, ejected safely before  
the single-seat jet slammed into the desert about 22 miles 
southwest of the training base near Phoenix. 
</P>
<P>
	Approximately 200 F-16s -- worth about $20 million apiece -- will  
be inspected before they are cleared to fly again, Gen. John Barry 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rider had been airborne for 20 minutes when he developed engine  
problems and turned back toward Luke. Witnesses said the plane was 
on fire. 
</P>
<P>
	``I saw a big ball of fire going across, then it hit the  
ground,'' said Willie Falcido, a maintenance worker who saw the 
crash from the roof of a school. 
</P>
<P>
	The last three F-16 crashes were also engine-related.  
</P>
<P>
	Pilots fly more than 100,000 sorties a year out of Luke.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
