<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 14:25:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reds' Williamson Pitching Well </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEARWATER, Fla. (AP) -- As Scott Williamson began warming up for  
the bottom of the ninth inning, a handful of Cincinnati Reds fans 
seated behind home plate squinted to try to read the name on the 
back of the uniform. 
</P>
<P>
	Who?  
</P>
<P>
	The first time Williamson threw a fastball, the fans turned  
towards each other in amazement. 
</P>
<P>
	``Did you see that?'' one said.  
</P>
<P>
	Another started glancing down his program to find the reliever's  
name. 
</P>
<P>
	``Number 66, number 66,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	About that time, Williamson threw another fastball that made a  
loud pop when it found the catcher's mitt. 
</P>
<P>
	``You couldn't even see that ball!'' a fan exclaimed.  
</P>
<P>
	That scene at a game in Fort Myers this week has played out at  
other spring training ballparks as well. Williamson, a nonroster 
pitcher with an offensive lineman's number, has been making himself 
known, fastball by fastball. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure when they look at the No. 66, they know I'm an  
invitee. Hopefully that number will change, will get a little bit 
lower -- 65, or something like that,'' Williamson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Barring a change in plans, Williamson will be getting a much  
lower number on a major league uniform in 10 days. 
</P>
<P>
	Williamson, 23, has been one of the biggest surprises of the  
Reds' training camp. He's the last player listed in the media guide 
-- alphabetical, with nonroster players at the rear -- and was 
basically brought to camp for the experience. 
</P>
<P>
	He pitched so well that he survived one cut after another. When  
setup man Stan Belinda went on the disabled list this week with 
tendinitis, there was an opening for Williamson to make the roster 
instead of returning to Triple-A Indianapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not etched in stone, but right now with the injuries,  
he's got a hell of a chance,'' manager Jack McKeon said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Williamson's numbers practically demand it. The right-hander has  
given up only one run in 13 2-3 innings for a 0.66 ERA. He allowed 
only an infield single during 1 1-3 innings of a 12-8 victory 
Friday over Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	A year ago, the right-hander couldn't imagine being in this  
position. 
</P>
<P>
	Williamson was a ninth-round draft pick in June 1997 out of  
Oklahoma State. He lasted so long in the draft because he never had 
an ERA lower than 4.31 in three seasons at Tulane and Oklahoma 
State. 
</P>
<P>
	Things fell into place in the Pioneer League, where he put up a  
1.78 ERA in his first professional season. He divided last season 
between Double-A and Triple-A, going 4-5 as a starter. 
</P>
<P>
	His progress was slowed last year by various injuries -- a line  
drive that grazed his forehead, a strained tendon in a finger, a 
stiff shoulder. Near the end of the season, the Reds made some 
changes in his delivery that increased his fastball from the low 
90s to 97 mph. They also suggested he try relieving. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never relieved before -- a couple of times in high school,  
but that was to get a couple of guys out in the seventh inning.'' 
he said. ``Whatever management says, you do. If it helps me get to 
the big leagues faster, then I'd rather be a reliever.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
