<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Speaker Hastert Chats Online </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Speaker Dennis Hastert has two favorite  
places to visit on the Web: country singer Johnny Cash's site and, 
for the former championship-winning wrestling coach, a site with 
wrestling scores and updates. 
</P>
<P>
	Hastert, who said he is still struggling to get comfortable with  
the Web, got a little practice Friday as he chatted online with 
students in his district who lobbed questions about some of Capitol 
Hill's hottest issues. 
</P>
<P>
	The opportunity to connect with young people now that his new  
job keeps him away from home more was a welcome one for the former 
high school government teacher. 
</P>
<P>
	The feeling was mutual. Students from the Illinois Republican's  
alma mater, Oswego High School, came back from their spring break 
for the chance to hear from a powerful alumnus. Six other schools 
participated, all from Hastert's district of Chicago suburbs and 
far-flung farmland. 
</P>
<P>
	The discussion covered such topics as Kosovo, tax cuts,  
Congress' post-impeachment relationship with President Clinton, 
arts funding, and Hastert's predecessor, former Speaker Newt 
Gingrich, R-Ga. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about Kosovo, Hastert said he supports American servicemen  
involved in the NATO mission but wishes Clinton had explained how 
it would end. 
</P>
<P>
	He also acknowledged that the $15 billion in tax cuts promised  
in just-passed Republican budgets may not materialize. 
</P>
<P>
	Hastert dodged a question on whether parents of children in  
private schools should get tax credits, but he expressed support 
for public schools and for sending federal education dollars to 
states and local districts so they can decide how to spend them. 
</P>
<P>
	The speaker pledged to work with Clinton to ``get things done.''  
</P>
<P>
	Hastert also defended the combative tenor of Gingrich's reign,  
while promising a shift under his watch. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even though those years were partisan, we accomplished a great  
deal for the American people,'' he said. ``I have great respect for 
Newt, but I will run the House differently.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
