<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Guerrero Riding Infiniti in Phoenix </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- If an Infiniti-powered car winds up in victory  
lane at an Indy Racing League event this year, Roberto Guerrero 
probably will be behind the wheel. 
</P>
<P>
	He has the crew, the experience and, apparently, the engine to  
do it. 
</P>
<P>
	``The improvement the engine has made since '97 is incredible,''  
the 39-year-old Colombia native said Friday ``The engine is to a 
point that, with the right breaks, it can win a race. It's going to 
be hard, because when you only have four cars out of 28 with the 
engine, it obviously makes the odds a little bit harder, but I 
think it's ready.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That wasn't the case two years ago. By the time the series hit  
Phoenix International Raceway for the second race of the season, 
teams using the new Infinitis were already thinking about switching 
to Oldsmobile's dependable Aurora. 
</P>
<P>
	Guerrero drove one of the two Infiniti-equipped cars still  
running at the end of the 200-mile event. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not familiar with their program at that point in time, but  
clearly as an outsider looking in they've jumped leaps and bounds 
from that point to this,'' Cobb Racing crew chief Phil Spano said. 
</P>
<P>
	Robbie Buhl is the only other driver at Phoenix with an  
Infiniti-equipped G Force. Rookies Jaques Lazier and Scott 
Harrington have Infinitis in their Dallara chassis. 
</P>
<P>
	Harrington Motorsports crew chief Steve Dunlap said Nissan  
improved its backup support while taking the bugs out of the 
powerplant. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had good luck with our private tests and mileaged the  
engine out without any difficulty, and when we got down to the 
block it was in great shape,'' Dunlap said. 
</P>
<P>
	Horsepower and durability aside, Guerrero has reason to feel  
confident in Phoenix, the site of this weekend's MCI WorldCom 200. 
</P>
<P>
	He earned his only Indy car title on the irregular, one-mile  
oval 12 years ago, setting a track record by averaging 138.020 mph 
during the race in a turbocharged CART machine. 
</P>
<P>
	Later in 1987, Guerrero was second in the Indianapolis 500, and  
the next year qualified for his only Indy 500 pole while setting a 
track record of 232.482 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	But that Memorial Day weekend also marked the start of a skid.  
He finished last in the race when he spun into the wall during the 
second parade lap. 
</P>
<P>
	Accidents also knocked Guerrero out of the Indy 500 in 1993 and  
1994. 
</P>
<P>
	His luck improved in 1996, when he joined the IRL with Pagan  
Racing and had a fifth-place finish at Indianapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	Pagan started with Infiniti in 1997, but by the end of the  
season the Aurora had a virtual lock on the series. At the same 
time, Guerrero's relationship with owner Allan Pagan was 
deteriorating. It lasted four races into last season before the 
driver left. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, former sports car racer Price Cobb decided his  
new racing team had outgrown its drivers. 
</P>
<P>
	``All of a sudden, he was the perfect shoe,'' Cobb said. ``I sat  
down with Infiniti, one of our supporters, and we bounced off of 
each other a great deal of information and many, many names, and we 
came to the consensus that Roberto Guerrero was the man that we 
needed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not the least of Guerrero's achievements with Cobb was to finish  
fourth last August at Texas Motor Speedway after leading 22 laps -- 
the first time an Infiniti-powered car had led an IRL event. 
</P>
<P>
	Cobb believes the crew let Guerrero down in Dallas and again in  
this season's first race outside Orlando, Fla., when Guerrero 
finished 13th after running 88 laps with a piece of another car's 
bodywork caught underneath the chassis. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was arguably when we would have been challenging for the  
front, and it was all he could do to keep the car out of the 
fence,'' Cobb said. 
</P>
<P>
	But the engine was strong, justifying the owner's trust. Cobb,  
who won the World Porsche Cup in 1994, became impressed with Nissan 
while driving in IMSA's Camel GTP series. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nissan used to trounce us all the time,'' he said.  


</P>
</TEXT>
