<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Markets Calm Despite NATO Airstikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- As NATO airstrikes battered Yugoslavia for a  
third day, the world's financial markets remained calm Friday. 
Historians said the robust U.S. economy and the perception that the 
conflict won't drag on have so far insulated the market from any 
sharp moves. 
</P>
<P>
	That could change drastically if the war spills into other  
nations or if it looks like ground troops will be needed to end the 
Serbian persecution of ethnic Albanians in Yugoslavia's Kosovo 
province, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are considerable risks,'' said Arnold Kaufman, editor of  
Standard &AMP; Poor's weekly newsletter, The Outlook. ``The conflict 
could spread and affect the economies of more significant trade 
partners. And the market doesn't like the possibility of major 
conflict.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Friday, while NATO forces launched their first daytime attacks  
over Kosovo, U.S. stocks slid modestly. The Dow Jones industrial 
average fell 14.15 points to close at 9,822.24. Asian and European 
markets turned in a mixed performance. 
</P>
<P>
	Market response to the fighting over Kosovo has fallen in line  
with previous military conflicts, with several jittery days 
followed by one big rally, economists said. Stocks slid early this 
week as conflict loomed, but the Dow roared back with a 
169.55-point gain Thursday, the day after the bombing started. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's an ominous feeling in the days before military  
action,'' said Yale Hirsch, editor and publisher of the Stock 
Trader's Almanac. In recent conflicts, from the Persian Gulf War to 
NATO efforts in Bosnia, ``that's been followed by a feeling of 
pride, a sense that we're pretty good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. stocks rose over the course of the Gulf War, but fell  
during the Vietnam War, when the economy was also marred by high 
inflation. Analysts said the strength of the current economy should 
help U.S. markets bear up throughout the Kosovo conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Losey, chairman of the finance and real estate department  
at American University, said financial markets tend to fluctuate as 
long as the potential risk of a conflict remains unclear. 
</P>
<P>
	Once there's a significant victory, markets often rise. The  
first sign of trouble can send them reeling. 
</P>
<P>
	``At the start of the Gulf crisis, there appeared to be a  
substantial risk that it would become a conflagration and that 
world oil supplies would be endangered,'' he said. That risk pushed 
the Dow down 12 percent between Aug. 2, 1990, when Iraq invaded 
Kuwait, and Jan. 16, 1991, the day before U.S. air attacks began. 
</P>
<P>
	Once the attacks were launched, Losey noted, ``it became obvious  
after only a few hours that we were going to win that conflict.'' 
On that day, the Dow rose 4.6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said the markets may have held steady this week because  
the conflict in Kosovo is fueled by humanitarian concerns, rather 
than the economic factors that drew the United States into the 
Persian Gulf in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Balkans are not a major trading partner, and may not pose  
a threat to any of our major trading partners,'' said Owen Lamont, 
an associate professor of finance at the University of Chicago's 
Graduate School of Business. He predicted Russia would have to 
advance its efforts to support Yugoslavia before U.S. markets would 
falter. 
</P>
<P>
	Market historians said signs of an advancing conflict -- such as  
news of the first casualties, or the arrival of ground troops -- can 
spur market movement. On Friday some traders sold stocks, concerned 
that the crisis could escalate this weekend, leaving them unable to 
respond until markets reopen Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, others doubted that a major market shift will ever occur.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's the third day of a raid, and it just doesn't sound like  
we're going to go into a full battle,'' said Larry Wachtel, market 
analyst at Prudential Securities. ``The market has barely reacted 
up until now, and I don't think it will.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kaufman said the markets may be lulled by the quick resolutions  
to conflicts in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think Americans now feel there's little risk in these  
skirmishes,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
