<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cuban-Americans in Majors Angered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Several major leaguers are angry with the Baltimore Orioles'  
decision to play Cuba in Havana on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't like the idea of Fidel Castro getting all the  
publicity,'' Fernando Vina, the Milwaukee Brewers' All-Star second 
baseman, said in Phoenix. 
</P>
<P>
	New York Mets coach Cookie Rojas was short and to the point: ``I  
don't agree with it. That's all I'm going to say,'' he said in 
Jupiter, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	San Francisco Giants pitcher Osvaldo Fernandez, who escaped Cuba  
in 1995, had mixed feelings. 
</P>
<P>
	``For the Cuban people, I want this to happen for them so they  
can see what a big-league team looks like, and what organized 
baseball looks like, and because it might open doors for a lot of 
players there. But for the system, the government, no I don't 
really care for it,'' said Fernandez, who hasn't pitched for the 
Giants since July 1997 because of elbow problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida Marlins owner John Henry, whose team has the largest  
Cuban-American fan base in the majors, has been the most vocal 
opponent in baseball -- even taking part in fan protests. 
</P>
<P>
	``The major problem here is ignorance,'' he said. ``People are  
not aware of the depth of oppression in Cuba. If they were, no one 
would support this game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Henry, who purchased his team in January, said the only reason  
Orioles owner Peter Angelos wanted to play Sunday's exhibition game 
against Cuba's national team was to expose the Orioles to Cuban 
players. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has shown he doesn't care what we think. He sure didn't ask  
us what we think,'' Henry said. ``He's interested in getting a 
competitive advantage -- to get the Orioles' name plastered across 
Cuba so the next Cuban baseball player who defects will head for 
Baltimore. ... A lot of people in baseball believe this. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, the Florida Marlins should be the team playing a  
game in Cuba, if the game in Cuba were the right thing to do. But 
it's not right thing to do,'' Henry said. 
</P>
<P>
	Angelos said recruiting wasn't behind the trip.  
</P>
<P>
	``It is important for all of us to open our minds and open our  
hearts to people of other countries. This is a wonderful thing that 
is happening throughout the world,'' he said Friday. ``I don't know 
of anything that has ever been done for a constructive purpose that 
didn't generate controversy. Anything that departs from what is 
customary is going to generate a difference of opinion, but it's a 
worthwhile endeavor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	New York Yankees pitcher Orlando ``El Duque'' Hernandez, the  
latest Cuban star player to join a major league team, has declined 
comment on the trip. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not too fond of the idea,'' said Milwaukee Brewers  
outfielder Alex Ochoa, whose mother was five months' pregnant with 
him when she fled Cuba in 1971. 
</P>
<P>
	``Knowing what my parents went through makes it hard for me to  
like the idea that we're going to let Fidel Castro get that 
attention,'' Ochoa said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't totally agree with the situation, with Fidel Castro in  
the stands, that will be hard to see.'' 
</P>
<P>
	St. Louis Cardinals manager Tony La Russa, a Florida native,  
also opposes the trip. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it's a good idea for several reasons,'' he said.  
``Why get it started? If I had a vote, I'd vote no.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
