<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Mass Killings Reported in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Serb forces executed scores of  
Kosovo Albanians and shelled numerous villages as fighting raged 
today throughout the province despite NATO air attacks, ethnic 
Albanian sources said. Meanwhile, Serbs were looting ethnic 
Albanian-owned stores in the capital and setting them ablaze. NATO 
officials stressed today that the air attacks were the beginning of 
what could be a long operation to make President Milosevic end his 
offensive in Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Downs Two Yugoslavia MiGs  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO jets shot down two Yugoslav MiG  
fighters and captured their pilots today in Bosnia, thwarting an 
attempted attack on NATO-led peacekeeping forces, alliance and U.S. 
officials said. The confrontation outside Yugoslav territory was a 
dangerous broadening of the showdown between the Western alliance 
and Yugoslav President Milosevic over Kosovo. Meanwhile, 
Yugoslavia's U.N. envoy said today that ``hundreds of civilians'' 
have been killed in NATO airstrikes which hit a cemetery for Nazi 
victims, two refugee camps and two youth hostels. 

</P>
<P>
	Anti-NATO Protests Target Embassies  
</P>
<P>
	ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- Protesters opposed to NATO attacks on  
Yugoslavia directed their anger at American sites around Europe 
today, drenching olive branches in red and calling President 
Clinton a ``fascist.'' Up to 10,000 people in Bulgaria gathered in 
the nation's capital of Sofia to protest the NATO airstrikes. In 
Greece, a NATO member, 15,000 protesters marched to the U.S. 
Embassy. In Russia, hundreds of protesters gathered outside the 
U.S. and British embassies. 

</P>
<P>
	French Tunnel Death Toll Hits 35  
</P>
<P>
	CHAMONIX, France (AP) -- Firefighters searched among the charred  
remains of cars and tractor-trailers today for victims of a 
catastrophic fire -- a blaze that killed at least 35 people in a 
seven-mile tunnel under Western Europe's highest peak. The blaze in 
the Mont Blanc tunnel, which broke out Wednesday on a Belgian truck 
carrying flour and margarine, was not extinguished until this 
afternoon. The Alpine tunnel is a major route connecting France and 
Italy, used daily by up to 4,000 trucks. 

</P>
<P>
	Chinese Premier To Visit U.S.  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji will travel to the  
United States next month to meet with President Clinton. Zhu's 
visit may give the United States and China a chance to reach 
agreement on trade initiatives that will clear the way for China's 
entry into the World Trade Organization. However, the discussions 
are occurring at a time of increased tensions over China's record 
on human rights and allegations of Chinese espionage at U.S. 
nuclear laboratories. 

</P>
<P>
	CT Scans Can Check Heart Disease  
</P>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Ordinary hospital CT scanners can be  
equipped to snap stop-action pictures of the heart, offering a new 
way of detecting dangerously clogged arteries many years before 
they cause trouble. Fatty buildups in the heart's arteries begin in 
early adulthood, but often there is no sign of damage until a heart 
attack strikes in middle age or beyond. However, these deposits 
frequently contain calcium that shows up on CT scans. 

</P>
<P>
	Students Help Others on Spring Break  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Some college students still party over spring  
break but many are choosing to spend the week involved in volunteer 
or charity work. Schools, uneasy about the binge drinking and 
violence associated with the annual break, are helping students 
skip the revelry. ``This generation does want to make a 
difference,'' said Thomas Greene of Norwich University, a Vermont 
school that sent students to Washington to work in soup kitchens 
and build houses. Last year, 20,000 students from across the nation 
did some alternative break activity, estimates Break Away, a group 
at Vanderbilt University in Nashville, Tenn. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Down 7.49  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices dipped lower in late afternoon as  
investors kept an eye on NATO air strikes in Kosovo while adjusting 
portfolios before the end of the quarter. Just before the close, 
the Dow Jones industrial average was down 7.49 at 9,828.90. Losers 
on the New York Stock Exchange outnumbered gainers 1,579-1,351. The 
Nasdaq was at 2,427.13, down 7.67. 

</P>
<P>
	Fisher To Coach San Diego State  
</P>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Steve Fisher, with one national title and two  
other Final Four appearances on his resume, will be San Diego 
State's new coach, The Associated Press has learned. San Diego 
State called a news conference for 6:15 p.m. EST today to make the 
announcement. Fisher, presently an assistant with the NBA's 
Sacramento Kings, was 184-82 at Michigan, and had a 20-6 record in 
the NCAA tournament. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by JEROME MINERVA  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
