<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 10:05:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> F-16 Crashes Near Arizona Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- An F-16 fighter crashed this morning during a  
training mission west of Phoenix, the fifth warplane out of Luke 
Air Force Base to go down since October, military officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The single-seat F-16 crashed about 22 miles southwest of the  
training base in suburban Glendale. 
</P>
<P>
	The pilot ejected safely and was taken to the base hospital for  
examination, said base spokeswoman Mary Jo May. The pilot's 
identity was not released. 
</P>
<P>
	May had no details of what caused the crash.  
</P>
<P>
	Witnesses said they heard the plane's engines sputtering and  
reported the plane appeared to be on fire as it went down. 
</P>
<P>
	``I saw a big ball of fire going across, then he hit the  
ground,'' said Willie Falcido, a maintenance man who saw the crash 
from the roof of an elementary school. 
</P>
<P>
	The crash was the fifth since October involving an F-16 at Luke,  
the largest F-16 training base in the world. Pilots fly more than 
100,000 sorties out of the base each year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 23:51:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ohio State Aims To Keep Dream Alive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- If any team in America knows what  
it's like to have no chance, it's Ohio State. 
</P>
<P>
	They've come this far, from the emptiness and frustration of an  
8-22 season all the way to the Final Four in one year. The Buckeyes 
are not ready to stop dreaming just yet. 
</P>
<P>
	``Coach said we're playing with the house money right now,''  
guard Brian Brown said. ``Nobody expected Ohio State to be in the 
Final Four. I think we've messed up a lot of people's pools.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ohio State (27-8) plays Connecticut (32-2) today in a national  
semifinal game that some view as a prelude to the main event, Duke 
and Michigan State. If people want to overlook the Buckeyes, that's 
fine with them. 
</P>
<P>
	But remember, to get here they've already knocked off No.  
1-seeded Auburn and St. John's -- two pretty impressive upsets. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel like we're playing an undercard,'' said Scoonie Penn,  
whose emergence as a sensational scorer and floor leader sent the 
Buckeyes on this improbable journey. ``We probably don't get spoken 
about as much as the other teams. They're the No. 1 seed, we're the 
No. 4 seed. I feel like we've been in that situation all season, 
playing the underdog role.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's the understatement of the tournament. Ohio State was  
pitiful last year, going 1-15 in the Big Ten. Penn, who followed 
coach Jim O'Brien from Boston College, had to watch from the 
sideline. 
</P>
<P>
	Somehow, O'Brien convinced Penn and backcourt-mate Michael Redd  
that the losing would stop. It's hard to imagine that O'Brien, even 
in his most optimistic dreams, envisioned this. 
</P>
<P>
	``He made guys believe in this program,'' Penn said. ``When I  
first arrived here, I don't think anyone in this basketball program 
really knew how to win anymore. It was time to turn this around.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Borrowing a trick from Pat Riley (``Three-Peat'') and John  
Calipari (``Refuse to Lose''), O'Brien has coined a phrase for this 
weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	``Don't settle,'' O'Brien said. ``It would be very easy for us  
to just walk in and say, `You know, fellas, if you lose, this has 
been great. Nobody's going to have anything but nice things to say 
about you.' We've achieved more than anyone could have thought we 
would have.' 
</P>
<P>
	``Is this what we want to have? Or do we want to try to get a  
little bit more?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Whether Ohio State keeps going may depend on the guard matchups.  
</P>
<P>
	Penn and UConn's Khalid El-Amin don't know each other from way  
back, the way their coaches do. They do know how to run a team, 
motivate everyone who crosses their path and turn 5-foot-10 bodies 
into catalysts that seem perfectly built for the last weekend in 
March. 
</P>
<P>
	``He could play basketball at 5-6 or 6-4,'' UConn coach Jim  
Calhoun said of his star point guard. ``He's a kid with some great 
ability as far as quickness, shooting strength. But the greatest 
asset for him is his character and mind-set. 
</P>
<P>
	``He wants to win every single drill, every single scrimmage and  
every single game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Especially the one against Ohio State.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 12:45:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Iberia Airlines Pilots Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MADRID, Spain (AP) -- More than 50 Iberia airline flights were  
canceled Friday as the carrier's pilots began a planned eight-day 
strike that threatens to create havoc for travelers during the 
Easter holiday period. 
</P>
<P>
	The flights canceled included 11 to Germany, Switzerland,  
Portugal and the Netherlands. The remainder were domestic flights, 
Iberia spokeswoman Consuelo Arias said. 
</P>
<P>
	An agreement between the company and the Spanish Airline Pilots  
Union, SEPLA, will ensure that 95 percent of Iberia's roughly 800 
daily flights will not be affected. 
</P>
<P>
	The two sides met Friday in the dispute over delays in signing a  
new labor agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	SEPLA says Iberia has declined to sign a final version of the  
labor agreement and is trying to renegotiate some of the terms, 
such as bonuses for pilots who fly at night. 
</P>
<P>
	Iberia, which the government plans to privatize, estimated that  
some 200 flights will be canceled during the first four days of the 
strike. It was not known how many may be affected during the final 
four days. 
</P>
<P>
	The cancelations are expected to mean about $100 million in  
losses for the airline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
