<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nomura Has One-Time Losses of $4.6B </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's leading investment house, Nomura Securities  
Co., has disclosed one-time losses of about $4.6 billion after 
pumping money into an affiliated finance company, making it the 
latest victim of plunging Tokyo real estate prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the losses reflect the poor performance of Nomura's U.S.  
subsidiary, Nomura America Holding Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Nomura said Friday that it will give 348 billion yen, or $2.9  
billion, to Nomura Finance Co. in April. The company, which 
specializes in real estate lending through the sale of securities 
backed by mortgages, also received 371 billion yen from Nomura in 
the fiscal year that ended in March 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly a decade of falling real estate prices and a lackluster  
stock market have left many of Japan's financial firms struggling 
with a huge bad debt burden, and Nomura said it will need billions 
in bank loans to foot the bill for its unit's latest problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Nomura Securities also said it was recording a one-time loss of  
$1.4 billion at its U.S. subsidiary, Nomura America Holding, Inc., 
a unit it also has bailed out in the past. 
</P>
<P>
	It will incur other extraordinary losses from the sale of  
securities and because of more stringent accounting standards. 
</P>
<P>
	Nomura's parent company in Japan still expects a pretax profit  
of about $2 billion for the fiscal year ending Wednesday, said 
Kenichi Watanabe, a director at Nomura Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	But he declined to comment on Nomura's consolidated earnings  
forecast, which includes the operations of majority-owned 
affiliates, saying only that the company will announce earnings 
results in April. 
</P>
<P>
	Nomura did not expect to have to provide any more aid to its  
finance affiliate, said Toshiaki Ito, an executive managing 
director at Nomura Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	For its part, Nomura Finance will halt new lending and try to  
recover its outstanding loans as soon as possible. The unit will 
try to cut its operations by two-thirds by March 2001, Ito said. 
</P>
<P>
	To help cover the cost of the bailout, Nomura Securities asked  
six banks for loans totaling 460 billion yen, or about $3.9 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. unit of Nomura Securities expects its holdings of  
mortgage-backed securities to fall to about $7 billion at the end 
of this month, from $9 billion in September, said Watanabe. 
</P>
<P>
	Nomura had to inject $530 million into the U.S. unit in  
September to help offset pretax losses of about $700 million for 
the six months ended Sept. 30. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
