<HEADLINE> McDonald's Begins Selling Furbys </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAK BROOK, Ill. (AP) -- Furby and fries, please.  
</P>
<P>
	McDonald's on Friday launched a Happy Meal promotion featuring  
one of the hottest toy sellers during last year's holiday season -- 
Furby -- hoping to enjoy the same success it has had with Teenie 
Beanie Baby promotions. 
</P>
<P>
	Customers buying a children's meal will get one of 80 different  
varieties of Furby, an odd-looking creature that will either blink, 
wiggle its ears, growl or move its feet. Unlike the larger versions 
manufactured by Tiger Electronics, however, the McDonald's toy is 
not electronic and does not speak. 
</P>
<P>
	At a restaurant in Los Angeles, Roberta Berne turned the  
bug-eyed plastic toy over with a bemused expression and hoped her 
two children would like it. 
</P>
<P>
	``It does look a little silly,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	McDonald's said it has ordered tens of millions of the creatures  
for the promotion, which lasts through April 22. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also is giving away 3,500 full-size Furby in  
contests tied to its Monopoly game contest that also is currently 
running. 
</P>
<P>
	The chain's Teenie Beanie Baby promotions over the past two  
years have been so successful that McDonald's this spring is 
expected to launch a third incarnation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
