<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Youth Baseball a Cuban Passion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- The ping of an aluminum bat hitting a ball rings  
across the diamond. Tiny feet stir the infield's dust. Parents rise 
to their feet to cheer. 
</P>
<P>
	The baseball field at Brothers to the Rescue Memorial Park is  
alive with cries of ``Good swing!'' and ``Watch the ball!'', 
interspersed with shouts in Spanish: ``Corre! Corre!'' and ``Sigue! 
Sigue!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly all of the 5-, 6- and 7-year-olds on a team called the  
Reds are of Cuban descent. Baseball is a passion their parents and 
grandparents brought across the Florida Straits when they fled 
their homeland. 
</P>
<P>
	But many parents say it's wrong for the Baltimore Orioles to  
travel to Havana to play an exhibition game Sunday against the 
Cuban national team. They say the Cuban government has spilled too 
much blood for such a game to be acceptable. 
</P>
<P>
	``They shouldn't go,'' Vicente Alvarez said as he watches his  
grandson through the dugout's chain-link fence. ``Most of the 
people I talk to agree with me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alvarez lists his reasons: 41 Cubans trying to escape the island  
who died in 1994 when their tugboat was rammed by Cuban government 
vessels; four men who died in 1996 when their unarmed airplanes 
were shot from the sky by Cuban military jets. 
</P>
<P>
	The ballpark in suburban Miami was named in honor of those four  
fliers, who belonged to the exile group Brothers to the Rescue. But 
as the boys jog in from the field after an inning, their minds seem 
to be on hitting -- not history. 
</P>
<P>
	Second baseman Jonathan Alvarez, 6, runs to the dugout and leans  
against the chain-link fence, slipping his hands through the wire 
to greet his grandfather, who arrived late. Alvarez grips his 
grandson's tiny fingers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jonathan, did you bat?'' he asks in Spanish.  
</P>
<P>
	``Si,'' the boy answers. ``A home run.''  
</P>
<P>
	The teams compete in the Flagami Khoury League -- the same league  
Jose Canseco of the Tampa Bay Devil Rays once played in. 
</P>
<P>
	Keeping score for the Reds with a pencil and notebook is  
Marisela Rodriguez-Blair. A lover of baseball, she says she has 
mixed emotions about the Orioles game. But she comes down against 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really think that they have no business there,'' she says.  
``Goodwill starts in the United Nations, not in the ballpark.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She comforts her son, Bryan Blair, when the 6-year-old walks in  
after being called out and tosses his helmet to the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	``Do you know that I love you more than anybody in this world?  
And I'm proud of you, even when you get an out,'' she says. ``Now, 
get your gloves,'' she tells the boys, sending them back to the 
field. 
</P>
<P>
	``My kid has a very hot temper. It's part of being Cuban, I  
think,'' she says. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in South Florida, scores of Cuban exiles have  
protested the Havana game and a second meeting of the Orioles and a 
Cuban team at Camden Yards on May 3. They argue the games are 
particularly inappropriate after the Cuban government's recent 
crackdown on political dissent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles will be the first major league team to play a game  
on the island since 1959. ESPN plans to televise the game. But Juan 
Malagon, coach of the Reds' opponents, the Marlins, says he will 
not watch. 
</P>
<P>
	He says Cuban President Fidel Castro will use the spectacle to  
profit politically, declaring it a victory for the Cuban 
revolution. 
</P>
<P>
	Malagon says even his 6-year-old son Ronald knows what to say  
about the bearded man in olive fatigues. 
</P>
<P>
	``When Fidel comes on television, I ask him, `Who's that?' And  
he tells me, `That's the devil, papa.' I taught him,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	When the game is finished, the Reds win 24-10. The team's coach  
calls it the best game of the season. The boys gather near the 
plate, assemble into two lines and give each other high-fives. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very pretty to see them taking the first steps of  
baseball,'' says Genaro Lee, whose 6-year-old son is among the 
players. ``Here, baseball has life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lee says he supports the Orioles' visit to Havana.  
</P>
<P>
	``Why not?'' he says. ``It's a game.''  
</P>
<P>
	He also says he hopes to watch on television, but he hesitates  
when asked who he is rooting for. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ah ... tough ...'' he says with a smile. ``I want to see the  
Cuban team win.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
