<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 05:46:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> UConn Huskies Hope To Stay Healthy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- Rip.  
</P>
<P>
	That's Connecticut star Richard Hamilton's nickname. The Huskies  
hope it doesn't describe their delicate physical state going into 
the most important game in school history Saturday against Ohio 
State in the NCAA semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
	A quickie summary of the Huskies' aches, pains and assorted  
maladies: 
</P>
<P>
	--Jake Voskuhl, their space-filling 6-foot-11 center, has missed  
two games this season with soreness in his left foot that 
temporarily put him on crutches and left him less than 100 percent 
at other times. 
</P>
<P>
	The Huskies need a productive Voskuhl to combat 6-11 Ohio State  
center Ken Johnson, who blocked seven shots and altered the tempo 
of the Buckeyes' regional final victory over St. John's. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the injury, Voskuhl has practiced as hard as ever during  
workouts that have not changed in length or intensity even during 
the NCAA tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why should we change now?'' Voskuhl said. ``We've been doing  
things the same way all season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the pregame emphasis placed on two teams driven by star  
guards, coach Jim Calhoun said what the Huskies most need to do is 
rebound the way they did by outrebounding 25 of 34 opponents this 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``If a guy comes up with 17 points, 10 rebounds, if those things  
start happening ... that may determine the game,'' Calhoun said. 
</P>
<P>
	--Kevin Freeman, the 6-7 forward who was the MVP of the Big East  
tournament, has an ear infection that is not considered especially 
worrisome. At least it wasn't serious enough to keep him off the 
team plane. 
</P>
<P>
	--Albert Mouring, a backup guard and one of the Huskies' key role  
players with a 7.4 scoring average, missed the second half of the 
West Regional final against Gonzaga with a sprained right knee. But 
it didn't keep him from going hard in practice this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Miss the Final Four? Are you kidding?  
</P>
<P>
	``No way you can miss THAT,'' he said. ``You'd have to be  
crazy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--Hamilton, who is 6-foot-6 yet is 15 pounds lighter than 5-10  
point guard Khalid El-Amin, needed right foot surgery in July while 
training for the world championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet he has recovered to score in double figures in all but two  
games, even while battling a deep thigh bruise that limited his 
effectiveness late in the regular season. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a tough time, being out, but everybody stuck with me  
and told me it would be all right,'' Hamilton said. 
</P>
<P>
	So all right that the Huskies (32-2) are the only other team  
besides Duke to be No. 1 rated this season. After never reaching 
the Final Four in 20 prior NCAA tournament appearances, the Huskies 
are within two victories of the school's first national 
championship. 
</P>
<P>
	It's pressure, for sure, but probably no more so than they faced  
in the three regional finals they lost under Calhoun -- to UCLA, to 
Duke on a last-second shot by Christian Laettner, to North 
Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	The difference this year, Calhoun said, is ``This team wouldn't  
let anybody get in the way of getting to St. Petersburg.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Or from Calhoun's son, Jim Jr., of going there for his dad's  
first Final Four appearances in 27 seasons of coaching at 
Northeastern (14) and Connecticut (13). The younger Calhoun's wife, 
Jennifer, gave birth March 5 to the couple's first child, Emily. 
</P>
<P>
	When the Huskies stepped off the team plane Wednesday night,  
Calhoun got his first look at his first grandchild. 
</P>
<P>
	`It's thrilling,'' said Calhoun, who has a 552-227 career  
record. ``She's more beautiful than I thought.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He'll probably feel the same way if he finds himself cradling  
the NCAA championship trophy Monday night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
