<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Low pressure near the Carolina coast this morning was bringing  
rain to areas from southeastern Virginia into eastern South 
Carolina. A cold front was producing scattered showers over 
northern Florida, and scattered thunderstorms extended west through 
the Gulf of Mexico into southern Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	But a strong area of high pressure was keeping a large portion  
of the country dry this morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Rain was forecast later today from southern Virginia, south  
through the Carolinas, and into Georgia. To the south, a cold front 
was expected to produce more thunderstorms in Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	A large area of high pressure was likely to keep the Northeast  
dry today. 
</P>
<P>
	In the West, two storm systems were threatening. One system was  
expected to bring rain showers and a few thunderstorms to the 
Southwest. To the north, another system was likely to bring rain 
and snow to the Northwest and northern Rockies. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures were expected in the 30s and 40s from the Northeast  
to the northern Plains; in the 60s and 70s along much of the West 
Coast and the middle Plains; in the 70s and 80s in the Southwest; 
and in the 80s in southern Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Thursday's high temperature in the U.S. mainland was 87 degrees  
in McAllen, Texas. The low was 10 degrees in International Falls, 
Minn. 
</P>
</TEXT>
