<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Orioles-Cuba Tickets by Invitation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAVANA (AP) -- Cuban baseball fans got the news Friday on  
government radio and television: 
</P>
<P>
	Tickets for Sunday's exhibition game between the Baltimore  
Orioles and a national Cuban team will be by invitation only. 
</P>
<P>
	The invitations will go to organizations linked to the  
government, such as schools and sports clubs. Those not among the 
lucky ticket-holders can watch on television. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was not invited to the game, which I want to see so much!''  
said Salvador Aguilar Martinez, part of a group of baseball fans at 
Central Park and unhappy about the decision to make the game an 
invitation-only event. 
</P>
<P>
	Cubans of all ages and walks of life are waiting for this  
moment, which will give them a chance to see how their players 
stand up beside the major leaguers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love the Marlins,'' said Sergio Giral, who was among about  
100 people Friday at Central Park, a gathering spot for those who 
like to argue baseball. ``I would support moves to see other big 
league teams come here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``At last we are going to see some tough baseball,'' said Miguel  
Marquez, 65, among the fans gathered at the Latinoamericano Stadium 
to discuss the baseball showdown. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Sunday game will be marvelous,'' Marquez added. ``I have  
waited a long time for this moment. Anything can happen in a 
game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brigades of workers Friday cleaned up the field at the old  
stadium, which since 1961 has been the site of all the national 
Cuban baseball tournaments. Later in the evening, the hometown 
Industriales played the Santiago team in a series final. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, the Communist Party daily Granma played down the  
exhibition game in favor of the national playoffs, calling them ``a 
true fiesta of the people that will decide the national champions 
of Cuban baseball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The precise time of the Orioles' arrival in Havana was being  
kept secret in Cuba and Miami, where their charter plane will take 
off for the short flight. Sports officials said the team was 
expected to arrive Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles will start Scott Erickson against one of two  
right-handers: Jose Ibar, who has a record of 38-5 in the last two 
Cuban championships; and Pedro Luis Lazo, known for his mean 
fastball. 
</P>
<P>
	The last time Cubans played a big league team on the island was  
in March 1959 -- three months after the triumph of the revolution 
that brought Fidel Castro to power. The Los Angeles Dodgers won the 
exhibition game with Cincinnati. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
