<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 6 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Begins More Airstrikes  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- NATO has launched a third night of airstrikes  
in Yugoslavia, the Pentagon said today, calling the allied 
operation against Serb targets large, involving air-launched cruise 
missiles and U.S. stealth fighter jets. The NATO attack began with 
cruise-missile-equipped B-52 bombers leading the assault, Pentagon 
spokesman Kenneth Bacon said. Also in the mix were F-117 stealth 
fighter jets equipped with laser-guided munitions. Bacon also 
confirmed that NATO warplanes shot down two Yugoslav MiG-29 jet 
fighters over neighboring Bosnia. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Appeals to Serbian People  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton appealed directly to the  
Serb people today for support in NATO's struggle against Yugoslav 
President Slobodan Milosevic. ``He has jeopardized Kosovo's future 
and brought you more war,'' Clinton said in a satellite-beamed 
message he labeled ``the plain truth.'' With Yugoslav authorities 
tightly controlling the media in Belgrade, administration officials 
said the purpose of Clinton's broadcast, and a similar one by 
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright in the local Serbo-Croatian 
language, was to explain to the Serb people why NATO bombers had 
attacked their country. 

</P>
<P>
	Kevorkian Found Guilty of Murder  
</P>
<P>
	PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) -- Dr. Jack Kevorkian was convicted today of  
second-degree murder and delivery of a controlled substance for 
giving a lethal injection to an ailing man whose death was shown on 
CBS-TV's ``60 Minutes.'' It was the first time in five trials that 
``the suicide doctor'' was found guilty. Kevorkian, 70, could get a 
life term for the death of 52-year-old Thomas Youk, who suffered 
from Lou Gehrig's disease. Kevorkian served as his own attorney 
during the short trial and repeatedly stumbled over legal 
procedure. 

</P>
<P>
	Nuclear Waste Arrives at N.M. Dump  
</P>
<P>
	CARLSBAD, N.M. (AP) -- After 25 years of lawsuits, studies and  
protests, the nation's first nuclear dump -- deep beneath the New 
Mexico desert -- received its first truckload of radioactive waste 
today. The truck left Los Alamos National Laboratory and traveled 
270 miles south to the Waste Isolation Pilot Plant near Carlsbad. 
Ultimately, up to 6.2 million cubic feet of waste generated since 
the dawn of the atomic age will be entombed over the next 30 years 
in the salt beds nearly a half-mile below ground. 

</P>
<P>
	Pastor Found Guilty in Gay Marriage  
</P>
<P>
	DOWNERS GROVE, Ill. (AP) -- A Methodist minister who officiated  
at the ``marriage'' of two gay men was convicted in a church trial 
today of disobedience in the first test of the denomination's ban 
on same-sex ceremonies and could be defrocked. The jury of 13 
pastors decided 10-3 that the Rev. Gregory Dell disobeyed church 
law when he presided over the ``holy union'' of the Chicago men 
last September. Immediately after the verdict, the penalty phase of 
the trial began. 

</P>
<P>
	McDonald's Enters Coffee Bar Craze  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Increasing numbers of Britons, forsaking their  
traditional cup of breakfast tea, are lining up at coffee bars to 
order the likes of a semi-skimmed cappuccino with a double shot of 
espresso. Seeking to cash in on explosive growth in British coffee 
bars, McDonald's has become the latest U.S. heavyweight to enter 
the market here. McDonald's has purchased Aroma Ltd., a chain of 23 
shops that sell coffee concoctions and sandwiches in a lively 
atmosphere of recorded Caribbean music and bright yellow and orange 
decor. 

</P>
<P>
	Speaker Hastert Chats Online  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Speaker Dennis Hastert misses being able  
to spend time around young people now that his new post keeps him 
away from home a lot more. So today, the former high-school 
government teacher and coach connected with local students via the 
Internet. Kids from the Illinois Republican's own alma mater, 
Oswego High School, even came back from their just-started spring 
break for the chance to have a live online chat with such a 
powerful alumnus. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Falls 14.15 to 9,822.24  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices drifted lower today in sluggish  
trading as investors adjusted their holdings before the end of the 
quarter and kept an eye on NATO air strikes in Kosovo. The Dow 
industrials closed down 14.15 at 9,822.24. Losers on the New York 
Stock Exchange outnumbered gainers 1,609-1,358. The Nasdaq was at 
2,419.17, down 15.63. 

</P>
<P>
	Braves Closer Might Miss Season  
</P>
<P>
	KISSIMMEE, Fla. (AP) -- Atlanta Braves reliever Kerry Ligtenberg  
said today he will likely have season-ending surgery on his ailing 
right elbow. The right-hander was diagnosed with a partial tear of 
the medial collateral ligament in his right elbow March 10. 
Ligtenberg, who took over the closer's role after Mark Wohlers 
experienced control problems, had 30 saves in 34 chances last 
season. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by JEROME MINERVA  
</P>
