<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2:25 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Mass Killings Reported in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Serb forces executed scores of  
Kosovo Albanians and shelled numerous villages as fighting raged 
today throughout the province despite NATO air attacks, ethnic 
Albanian sources said. The dead reportedly include a prominent 
lawyer and his two sons who were arrested on the first day of the 
attacks. Those could not be independently confirmed because 
international monitors withdrew last week and Serb authorities 
expelled foreign journalists. NATO officials stressed today that 
the air attacks were the beginning of what could be a long 
operation to make President Milosevic end his offensive in Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Downs Two Yugoslavia MiGs  
</P>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- NATO forces shot down two Yugoslav  
MiG-29 fighters today as they attempted to strike NATO-led 
peacekeeping troops in Bosnia. The pilots were captured in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina by the peacekeeping forces, alliance spokesman 
Jamie Shea said. U.S. State Department spokesman James P. Rubin 
said the planes were shot down by aircraft. The goal of the attacks 
is to force President Slobodan Milosevic to agree to a peace deal 
for Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Launches Daylight Attack  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO forces launched their first  
daylight attack today on Yugoslavia, Belgrade's independent Studio 
B television reported. Air raid sirens wailed at midafternoon in 
Belgrade and bombs hit suburban targets, the station reported. NATO 
officials said today that allied aircraft had flown 400 sorties 
against Yugoslavia in the first two days of air operations and had 
struck 50 targets, all air defense and related facilities. They 
said the attacks have been a successful start to forcing President 
Slobodan Milosevic to cooperate on a peace deal for Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	French Tunnel Death Toll Hits 35  
</P>
<P>
	CHAMONIX, France (AP) -- Exhausted firefighters endured searing  
heat and poisonous smoke to extinguish a fire that killed at least 
35 people in a tunnel under Western Europe's highest peak. Crews 
searched through charred trucks for victims of the fire that 
started Wednesday. Up to 40 people may have died in the seven-mile 
tunnel under Mont Blanc, a fire official said. The tunnel, 
connecting Italy and France, turned into an inferno when the fire 
broke out in a truck carrying flour and margarine. 

</P>
<P>
	Chinese Premier To Visit U.S.  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji will travel to the  
United States next month to meet with President Clinton, the White 
House said today. Zhu's visit may give the United States and China 
a chance to reach agreement on trade initiatives that will clear 
the way for China's entry into the World Trade Organization. 
However, the discussions are occurring at a time of increased 
tensions over China's record on human rights and allegations of 
Chinese espionage at U.S. nuclear laboratories. 

</P>
<P>
	Rubin Criticizes GOP Tax Plans  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin criticized  
Republicans today for planning to use large parts of expected 
federal surpluses for a tax cut, saying they would squander a 
chance to strengthen the economy and buttress federal retirement 
programs. Rubin spoke a day after the House and Senate approved 
similar GOP-written budgets for fiscal 2000 calling for $778 
billion in tax reductions over the next decade. Rubin's comments 
underlined the administration's preference to use projected 
surpluses for domestic spending and a smaller tax cut. 

</P>
<P>
	Safety of Diabetes Drug Reviewed  
</P>
<P>
	BETHESDA, Md. (AP) -- Federal officials said today they have  
linked 38 cases of acute liver failure to the diabetes drug Rezulin 
and believe the risk of liver problems grows over time as patients 
take the drug. In all, Food and Drug Administration officials have 
discovered 43 cases of acute liver failure among Rezulin patients, 
38 of which were probably caused by the medicine, they told a panel 
of scientific advisers weighing the drug's safety. Several doctors 
told the panel that Rezulin helps many patients, and the benefits 
outweigh the risk. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Down 15.81  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 2 p.m. EST, the Dow Jones industrial  
average was down 15.81 points at 9,820.58. Losers on the New York 
Stock Exchange outnumbered gainers 1,567-1,284. The Nasdaq was down 
6.66 at 2,428.14. 

</P>
<P>
	Brand, Ellis Win AP Awards  
</P>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- Duke sophomore center Elton Brand,  
the only unanimous All-America selection this season, was honored 
today by The Associated Press as college basketball's player of the 
year. Brand enters the Final Four averaging 17.8 points and 9.6 
rebounds for the top-ranked Blue Devils. Auburn's Cliff Ellis was 
chosen as coach of the year. He led the Tigers to a 29-4 record and 
they reached their highest ranking ever, No. 2. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SUZANNE ROWLAND  
</P>
