<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Michigan State, Duke To Meet Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- One team dominated the tough  
Atlantic Coast Conference with an unprecedented 16-0 mark and has a 
31-game winning streak. 
</P>
<P>
	The other finished 15-1 in the Big Ten, considered the nation's  
best conference all season, and has won 22 straight games. 
</P>
<P>
	So, with the Tale of the Tape apparently so even, why is  
top-ranked Duke such an overwhelming favorite to beat fellow No. 
1-seed Michigan State tonight in the NCAA semifinals? 
</P>
<P>
	``They really are a team with depth and they have a lot of  
things going for them,'' Spartans coach Tom Izzo said. 
</P>
<P>
	Both teams also have an All-American: Duke's sophomore center  
Elton Brand, the only unanimous choice; and Spartans junior guard 
Mateen Cleaves, also on the first team. 
</P>
<P>
	Duke (36-1) and Michigan State (33-4) even met during the  
season. The Blue Devils held on for a 73-67 victory in early 
December in the Great Eight in Chicago, one of just two games they 
didn't win by double-digits. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, Duke remains a favorite to beat the Spartans again  
and then win the championship Monday night against Ohio State or 
Connecticut. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blue Devils lead the nation in scoring (92.9) and average  
margin of victory (25.9), and are second in field-goal percentage 
(51.8). 
</P>
<P>
	``He's done a lot of great jobs with a lot of great players,''  
said Izzo, in his first Final Four. ``He doesn't let them get away 
from him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He, of course, is Duke's Mike Krzyzewski, who is in his eighth  
Final Four since 1986. He's trying to become just the fourth coach 
to win three national championships. 
</P>
<P>
	``We certainly don't feel like we're invincible,'' Krzyzewski  
said. ``I don't think any of our players or coaching staff have 
ever portrayed that mood, that opinion. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're a fairly young team with five sophomores and a freshman  
in our first eight. With that level of experience we can lose to 
anybody,'' he continued. ``We just have played so hard this year 
and so passionately that we haven't lost except that one time and 
that's been a strength of our team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For most of the season and all of March, the talk has been of  
Duke winning its third championship of the '90s, a decade in which 
it's made five trips to the Final Four. 
</P>
<P>
	The Spartans, however, are fed up with all the hype and are  
ready to prove something themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	``After a while it gets on your nerves,'' Michigan State forward  
Andre Hutson said of Duke's aura. ``You just have to look past it 
because they've earned a lot of respect. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to give the guys credit. They play hard, they've only  
lost one game this season and they have a lot of great players. ... 
You have to turn off the TV sometimes and put away the papers and 
concentrate on what you have to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And if the Spartans do what they want to do, it would be one of  
the great Final Four upsets ever. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
