<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 00:42:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Small Town Crafts Economic Boost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALVA, Okla. (AP) -- Even Alva officials admit they have little to  
offer when it comes to economic development, nothing that makes the 
little northwestern Oklahoma town stand out from the crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	As Mayor Stan Kline puts it, the town's greatest attributes are  
a safe environment, a relatively high quality of life and good 
people -- pitches that businesses looking for a new location hear 
from just about every town they consider. Market incentives speak 
louder than anything. 
</P>
<P>
	``These bigger communities, they can actually come up with cash  
money,'' Kline said. ``In a community of less than 5,000 people, it 
takes every dime we generate to run the city. We don't have $3 or 
$4 million to draw a company.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So the city has come up something experts say is a first, a  
municipal version of Economics 101 that relies on Alva's one truly 
unique resource -- Northwestern Oklahoma State University. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal is simple: enact a 1 percent city sales tax to fund  
scholarships for new students at the college. Supporters say more 
people in town means more money spent at local businesses -- and 
that could make Alva more attractive to industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's where you get the economic development, having these  
students living in Alva either in our dorms or in apartments and 
buying things in town,'' Northwestern spokesman Steve Valencia 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Alva residents will vote on the proposal May 11. Kline said the  
tax would raise about $500,000 per year, which would be split 
between scholarships and development of parks and recreation areas. 
</P>
<P>
	Tim Venable, managing editor of the economic development trade  
journal Site Selection, said many communities collect a local tax 
to fund development efforts. He said using a college as the main 
draw is new. 
</P>
<P>
	``What a community like this has to do, and it sounds like what  
they're doing, is they have to look for that distinctive feature 
and capitalize on that,'' he said. ``It's tough for small 
communities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alva knows. There's no interstate, and its population dipped  
below 10,000 in the last census. It is 110 miles away from Oklahoma 
City. 
</P>
<P>
	With 536 student employees and a payroll of $6.5 million,  
Northwestern is by far Alva's largest employer. Agriculture 
accounts for most of the rest. 
</P>
<P>
	The liberal arts and teacher education college has 1,369  
students. Joe Struckle, the university's president for 24 years, 
said the school hopes to double enrollment over the next few years, 
and scholarships would help. 
</P>
<P>
	For the plan to work, Northwestern must be able to attract new  
students to a town with a two-screen movie theater and one that's 
an hour's drive from the nearest shopping malls. One condition of 
the scholarships would be that students must live in Alva. 
</P>
<P>
	Struckle said he believes Alva residents will approve the tax  
measure, but knows he and other supporters have lobbying to do. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to have to produce, and we know that,'' he said.  
``By God, you can always give money away.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0297 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 23:41:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Irwin Wins Primestar 500 Pole </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT WORTH (AP) -- By definition, professional race car drivers  
are fearless. 
</P>
<P>
	There were some great examples of that Friday in the opening  
round of qualifying for the Primestar 500 at Texas Motor Speedway, 
where 37 drivers were faster than the previous track record. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a horsepower racetrack and it's kind of a gutsy  
racetrack,'' Kenny Irwin said after taking his Robert Yates Racing 
Ford around the reconfigured 1 1/2-mile oval at 190.154 mph -- burying 
the record of 185.906 set last April by Jeremy Mayfield. 
</P>
<P>
	``By no means did I come close to holding it wide open here, but  
it suits us,'' Irwin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Irwin won his first Winston Cup pole in the 1998 season-finale  
at Atlanta Motor Speedway in November. That track is very similar 
to the Texas oval, particularly now that a $3.4 million 
reconfiguration and repaving has been completed. 
</P>
<P>
	``For whatever reason, these type of configurations are good for  
Robert Yates engines. They're horsepower tracks,'' Irwin said. 
</P>
<P>
	The changes at Texas Motor Speedway eliminated problem areas in  
turn four and in the transitions from the corners to the 
straightaways on the D-shaped oval. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's all the racetrack,'' last year's top rookie said of the  
jump in speeds. ``The changes they made in (turns) one and two are 
the biggest reasons. The track is just faster.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bobby Labonte, who broke his right shoulder blade when he  
crashed his Busch Series car last week in Darlington, put his car 
on the outside of the front row with a lap of 189.853. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not as sore as I thought I'd be today,'' said Labonte, who  
got relief help from Matt Kenseth after driving the first 45 laps 
of the Winston Cup race Sunday in Darlington. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan for Sunday's 500-mile race is for Kenseth, a regular in  
the Busch Series, to stand by in case Labonte needs to get out of 
the car again. 
</P>
<P>
	Labonte, a Texas native and local favorite, spent most of this  
week working with trainers for the NFL's Carolina Panthers 
rehabilitating his injured shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tomorrow's going to play a big key in how we do it on  
Sunday,'' Labonte said. ``It feels pretty good right now, but we'll 
see how it feels when I get out there with some other cars and run 
a few more laps at a time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Park, another rookie last year, was a bit of a surprise as  
he took third place on the grid with a lap of 189.341 in a 
Chevrolet. For Park, who missed 15 races last year after a very bad 
crash in Atlanta, it was easily his best qualifying effort. His 
best previous start was 12th. 
</P>
<P>
	He was followed by two-time Winston Cup champion Terry Labonte,  
Bobby's older brother, whose Chevy ran 189.122. 
</P>
<P>
	Ward Burton was fifth in a Pontiac at 188.990, followed by the  
Ford of Mark Martin at 188.957, the Chevys of Ken Schrader and Jeff 
Gordon at 188.778 and 188.699 and, rounding out the top 10, the 
Ford of Bill Elliott at 188.587. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Burton, Ward's younger brother and the current series  
points leader, was expected to contend for the pole on Friday, but 
wound up 20th at 187.311. 
</P>
<P>
	The twenty-five fastest qualifiers locked up starting spots in  
the 43-car field, with the rest of the lineup to be set today 
following the final round of time trials. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the drivers who failed to make the top 25 and will have to  
either try again Saturday or stand on their first-day laps were 
former series champions Dale Earnhardt, who was 38th, and Darrell 
Waltrip, 46th of the 48 drivers who made qualifying attempts. 
</P>
<P>
	On a track where crashing was commonplace during the first two  
Winston Cup weekends, the only incident among NASCAR's elite came 
during qualifying when Ken Bouchard smacked the wall hard. 
</P>
<P>
	Bouchard, who suffered a concussion, was flown by helicopter to  
a Dallas hospital, where he underwent tests and evaluation. Track 
officials said the driver from Fitchburg, Mass., was awake and 
alert, but was kept overnight for observation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0298 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 16:35:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Irwin Wins Primestar 500 Pole </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT WORTH (AP) -- Kenny Irwin must like these fast Bruton Smith  
tracks. 
</P>
<P>
	Irwin, who won his first Winston Cup pole in the 1998 season  
finale at Atlanta Motor Speedway in November, set a track record on 
Friday in capturing the top qualifying spot for the Primestar 500 
at Texas Motor Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year's top rookie cruised around the 1 1/2-mile oval on his  
qualifying lap at 190.154 mph, the fastest of 37 drivers who beat 
the previous record of 185.906, set last April by Jeremy Mayfield. 
</P>
<P>
	The speeds were boosted by a $3.4 million offseason  
reconfiguration and repaving of the track to eliminate problem 
areas in turn four and in the transitions from the corners to the 
straightaways on the D-shaped oval. 
</P>
<P>
	Both of the ovals at which Irwin has won poles are owned by  
Speedway Motorsports Inc., the company headed by Smith that also 
owns and operates four other racetracks. And both are similar in 
look and feel. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's awesome,'' the 29-year-old Irwin said. ``I don't care  
what anybody says about this racetrack, they've done a great job. 
It's real fast, but I really like it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Irwin says he liked it before the changes, winning a NASCAR  
Craftsman Truck Series race here in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Bobby Labonte, who broke his right shoulder blade when he  
crashed his Busch Series car last week in Darlington, put a Pontiac 
on the outside of the front row with a lap of 189.853. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not as sore as I thought I'd be today,'' said Labonte, who  
