<DOCNO> APW19990326.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 05:15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Authors Defend Evolution Teaching </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Fearing a growing assault on the teaching of  
Darwin's theories, a group of textbook authors has launched a 
campaign in defense of evolution education. 
</P>
<P>
	A joint statement, to be released today at the National Science  
Teachers Association, a convention of 20,000 science teachers, 
comes as some public school districts consider softening their 
evolution curricula. 
</P>
<P>
	``As scientists and teachers, we find it unacceptable that  
school districts considering our books for adoption would be 
encouraged to choose one book over another based on the perception 
that teachers should avoid the topic of evolution,'' the statement 
by 23 authors reads. 
</P>
<P>
	Backed by the California-based National Center for Science  
Education, the signers include Bruce Alberts, president of the 
National Academy of Sciences and an author of a cell biology book. 
</P>
<P>
	Evolution education continues to raise passions in American  
schools more than 70 years after teacher John Scopes was convicted 
of violating a Tennessee law against teaching it. And the debate 
rages a decade after the Supreme Court ruled that public schools 
can't teach that God created the universe. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the last five years, the National Center for Science  
Education has logged scores of complaints from parents and 
educators worried about attacks on evolution education. 
</P>
<P>
	Some school districts have pushed for textbooks that are  
considered ``soft'' on evolution teaching, said Molleen Matsumura 
of the NCSE. 
</P>
<P>
	Others have advocated disclaimer stickers on texts, such as one  
approved by the Alabama Board of Education in 1995. The Alabama 
label explains that evolution is a theory and that text statements 
about the origins of life should be considered as such. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, the Melvindale-Northern Allen Park School Board in  
Michigan decided to supply some of its libraries with books that 
raise questions about the validity of evolutionary theory. 
</P>
<P>
	And in Texas last year, school districts across the state were  
urged to adopt textbooks that didn't ``harp on'' evolution, 
Matsumura said. 
</P>
<P>
	A Christian publisher's textbook, ``Of Pandas and People,'' has  
grown in popularity. It, and others like it, subscribe to the 
theory that the world and its living creatures came about by 
``intelligent design.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The evolution scientists say that's just code for creationism.  
</P>
<P>
	The evolutionists are ``vastly overreacting to what we're trying  
to accomplish,'' said Raymond G. Bohlin, who has a doctorate in 
molecular biology and heads the Probe Ministries, based in 
Richardson, Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	What he and others want, he said, is for evolution to be fairly  
represented and juxtaposed with other theories of life. 
</P>
<P>
	But there are no other theories, the scientists who signed the  
statement say. 
</P>
<P>
	Teaching biology without evolution is like teaching physics  
while ignoring gravity, they say. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's academically and intellectually dishonest to teach  
biology any other way,'' said Eric Strauss, author of a popular 
introductory biology textbook and a biology professor at Boston 
College. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 15:14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Muslim Pilgrims Pray at Mecca </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOUNT ARAFAT, Saudi Arabia (AP) -- Two million Muslim pilgrims  
dressed in seamless white robes prayed today on this desert 
mountainside, reflecting on their lives in an annual ritual 
considered a foretaste of the day of judgment. 
</P>
<P>
	Saudi officials handed out chilled water and juice to the  
faithful, who endured 104-degree heat for the ritual at Mount 
Arafat, a central part of the annual hajj pilgrimage. 
</P>
<P>
	By midday Friday, the mountain plain near Mina, six miles north  
of Mecca, was a sea of white, dotted by the green and black 
umbrellas of those seeking relief from the scorching sun. Medical 
workers rushed to treat those who fainted from the heat, carrying 
some out on stretchers hooked up to motorcycles. 
</P>
<P>
	All day, hoses sprayed a fine mist on the pilgrims to help them  
stay cool. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the heat, some pilgrims walked all the way to the top of  
the mountain to pray and beg for mercy at the spot where Islam's 
founder, Prophet Mohammed, gave his final sermon 1,400 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Mamdouh Mohammed, a 42-year-old Egyptian, was making the  
pilgrimage with his year-old son in his arms. 
</P>
<P>
	``I brought him here so that he will comprehend Islam at an  
early age,'' Mohammed said. ``I want Allah to see him and instill 
in him the good, pure spirit that every Muslim must have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Saudi Crown Prince Abdullah was among thousands participating in  
noon prayers at Namrah Mosque on Mount Arafat. An hour-long sermon 
there touched on the ``enemies of Islam,'' singling out those who 
pit weaker Muslim nations against each other or label Muslims as 
terrorists. 
</P>
<P>
	Iranian pilgrims chanted ``Death to America!'' and ``Death to  
Israel!'' during a peaceful demonstration inside their camp of 
60,000 at Mount Arafat. Saudi forces did not intervene in the 
rally, which lasted less than an hour. 
</P>
<P>
	Technically, Saudi Arabia bars demonstrations during the hajj  
pilgrimage, but the government has tolerated low-key Iranian 
rallies. In 1987, an Iranian rally led to clashes with Saudi forces 
in which 402 pilgrims, mostly Iranians, were killed. 
</P>
<P>
	The Iranian government insists on holding the protests, known as  
the ``disavowal of infidels,'' during the pilgrimage to denounce 
the United States and Israel. 
</P>
<P>
	When evening came, the pilgrims traveled three miles to  
Muzdalifah, the next stage in the hajj journey all able-bodied 
Muslims are required to make once if they can afford it. 
</P>
<P>
	The pilgrims then head to Mina before dawn, where they will cast  
pebbles Saturday at a pillar representing the temptations of Satan. 
They then return to the holy city of Mecca, where more rituals 
follow, including sacrifices of rams or oxen. 
</P>
<P>
	Such sacrifices are carried out throughout the Muslim world  
beginning Saturday, the start of the three-day Islamic holiday of 
Eid al-Adha. Shops and government offices close for the holiday, 
one of the most important on the Islamic calendar. 
</P>
<P>
	This year the ritual at Mount Arafat was performed on Islam's  
holy day, Friday, making this year's hajj a ``greater pilgrimage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The sheer numbers making the pilgrimage have made the hajj  
vulnerable to disasters. In 1997, fire tore through an overcrowded 
tent city at Mina, killing more than 340 pilgrims and injuring 
1,500. A stampede last year killed 180 pilgrims. 
</P>
<P>
	Saudi television broadcast short warnings Friday, urging  
pilgrims to avoid carelessly flicking cigarette butts in the tent 
cities where many are housed. Footage of firefighters patrolling 
the sprawling campsites on motorcycles accompanied the warnings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990326.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-26 15:14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
